<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Corruption 1stLd-Writethru a0607 12-08 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Corruption, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker, 5 Others Target of Prosecution, Arrests Made</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf `During a ...' with one graf to CORRECT to $54
billion, sted million. Picks up 5th graf, `Prosecutors have .. .'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation into corruption in East
Germany reached the top level Friday with the announcement of
criminal charges against former Communist Party chief Erich
Honecker and five of his ousted lieutenants.
   Four of the disgraced former Politburo members were thrown in
jail pending an investigation. Honecker, who underwent gall bladder
surgery last summer, was too ill to be jailed and remained under
house arrest, prosecutors said.
   After decades of hearing their leaders say the West was poised
to plunder the Communist nation, shocked East Germans have grown
increasingly angry as they have learned the extent of the
plundering from within.
   During a parliament session Dec. 1, one lawmaker alleged former
officials stashed $54 billion in Swiss bank accounts.
   Prosecutors have not confirmed that figure, but there have been
nearly daily revelations of corruption and lavish living by the
country's former hard-line leaders.
   The latest comes with the opening of criminal investigations
against Honecker, 77; former Premier Willi Stoph, 75; and four
aging cronies.
   Four of the six former Politburo members already are in prison,
said prosecution spokesman Peter Przybylski. Former Politburo
member Hermann Axen, 73, was having an eye operation in Moscow.
   ``They are accused of damaging the economy of the German
Democratic Republic and of personally enriching themselves by abuse
of office and corruption,'' Przybylski said.
   The charges carry a penalty of up to 10 years in prison.
   Those arrested were Stoph; Guenther Kleiber, 58; Werner
Krolikowski, 65; and Erich Mielke, the 81-year-old former chief of
the once-dreaded secret police.
   Przybylski did not say when the trials would take place, adding
that police had searched the suspects' homes. He also did not
specify their alleged crimes.
   For weeks, officials have been disclosing how the ousted
leadership lived lavishly with the best imported goods and had
fancy hunting lodges, while the state-run news media has spoken of
fortunes smuggled abroad.
   Honecker and other former Politburo members already were under
house arrest in their exclusive compound outside East Berlin.
Honecker was ousted as party leader on Oct. 18 and all were later
expelled from the party.
   Three other former Politburo members already had been imprisoned
on suspicion of corruption.
   East Germans also are reeling from the scandal involving the
nation's former chief foreign trader, Alexander
Schalck-Golodkowski, who surrendered to West Berlin authorities
Wednesday.
   Schalck-Golodkowski is accused of running a ring that illegally
sold weapons to countries in South America, Africa and the Middle
East.
   He insists he is innocent, but has agreed to pay back $31
million. That's only a fraction of the sum East German news media
say he may have embezzled.
   His deputy, Manfred Seidel, was arrested and charged with
smuggling out $110 million. Another figure connected to the scandal
has committed suicide, the official news agency ADN said.
   The allegations are particularly embarrassing for a country that
routinely has said it is short of desperately needed Western
currency.
   Also Friday, the Christian Democrats said investigators had
found the party's former leader, Gerald Goetting, responsible for
financial irregularities. The allegations were turned over to
prosecutors for possible criminal charges.
   The Christian Democrats are one of the four smaller parties that
recently broke a decades-long alliance with the Communists.
</TEXT>
