<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Soviets-Vietnam Bjt   12-08 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Vietnam, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sources: Soviets Withdrawing Fighters From Cam Ranh Bay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is packing up MiG-23 fighter
jets based at Vietnam's Cam Ranh Bay, the U.S.-built port the
Soviets turned into their largest naval facility outside their
borders, administration sources say.
   ``There have been a series of reports that they have been
disassembling and packing up their MiG-23s for shipment,'' said one
source, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name.
   ``The reports have triggered speculation the Soviets might be
scaling down, or could be preparing a pullout from Cam Ranh Bay.''
   The changes indicate ``it could be a complete pullout, or it
could lead to a significant reduction'' in Soviet military
involvement at the base, the source said Thursday.
   There could be several reasons behind such a possible pullback,
the source and other Asian specialists said in a series of
interviews.
   The move could be a reflection of the worldwide Soviet reduction
in naval activities that has occurred over the past months, which
some U.S. analysts have speculated may be due to economic pressures.
   The Cam Ranh changes also could foreshadow a possible unilateral
Soviet initiative designed to one-up the United States as it
prepares to enter into negotiations on renewing leases for U.S.
bases in the Philippines, the administration source said.
   ``It could be a setup to embarrass us,'' the source said.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev proposed several years ago to
withdraw from the base _ his most strategic foreign site in Asia _
if the United States would pull out of the six bases it has leased
in the Philippines.
   U.S. officials rejected the proposal.
   The leases on the U.S. bases expire in 1991 and the renewal has
become a hotly debated topic, particularly in light of the recent
U.S. intervention against the rebel forces attempting to overthrow
President Corazon Aquino.
   One defense analyst, who declined to comment specifically on the
MiG-23 move, said the idea of a unilateral Soviet drawdown to point
up the U.S. problems with the Philippines wouldn't be out of line
with Pentagon assumptions.
   ``They'd like to complicate our lives,'' the analyst said of the
Soviets. ``We've been predicting some de-emphasis there.''
   Jonathan Pollack, the head of the RAND corporation's political
science department and a specialist on the role of the Soviet Union
in Indochina, said the Soviets have tended to keep about 20 vessels
and 40 aircraft at the Cam Ranh base.
   Pollack, in a telephone interview, said he would not be
surprised by a Soviet cutback.
   ``If there are changes in the more distant deployments, it could
be explained by a mix of factors _ not only economic, but also a
reconsideration of what is crucial to Soviet security concerns,''
he said.
   The analyst said that ``lots of Gorbachev's proposals are for a
P.R. (public relations) effect,'' but he wouldn't be surprised if a
reduction at Cam Ranh Bay was made without any publicity.
   ``In the context of what clearly is a major change in the
U.S.-Soviet relationship, the value of distant Soviet bases is
reduced,'' he said.
   Cam Ranh Bay _ located several hundred miles from Ho Chi Minh
City, formerly Saigon, on Vietnam's eastern coast _ offers one of
the finest harbors in Indochina and provides a safe anchorage to
all types of vessels year round.
   The Japanese made use of the harbor in World War II, but it was
transformed into a modern military facility by the United States
during the Vietnam conflict when warehouses, airstrips and other
naval support facilities were built.
   According to the London-based International Institute for
Strategic Studies, the Soviet Union has regularly deployed at the
base an average of one or two submarines and a range of surface
combat ships, as well as patrol, mine warfare, amphibious and
support vessels.
   The air units have included six Tu-95 ``Bear'' long-range
bombers, 16 Tu-16 ``Badger'' fighter aircraft and a squadron of the
MiG-23 ``Flogger'' fighter jets, the institute reported in its
``The Military Balance 1989-1990'' publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gorbachev Bjt   12-08 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Hard for Bush to Get a Handle on Soviet Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bounce isn't there anymore. Mikhail
Gorbachev doesn't light up a room simply by entering it. Often
unpredictable in the past, the Soviet leader did not challenge
President Bush at the Malta summit with dazzling new proposals.
   The closest he came was proposing that nuclear-armed warships be
included in arms control negotiations. But Gorbachev had
telegraphed the initiative through the media before he sat down
with Bush, and the administration had decided to resist even
tinkering with the U.S. Navy before the president left Washington.
   Gorbachev also showed Bush a map illustrating how the Soviet
Union was ringed by American military might. The Soviets had used
the tactic of negotiating with pictures before, and the gambit did
not produce U.S. concessions.
   Gorbachev pulled no rabbits out of a hat, offered no massive
withdrawal of Soviet forces, extended no invitation to banish
nuclear weapons.
   As a result, the president was not placed in the position of
having to cope with an ingenious and inventive adversary by meeting
him halfway.
   The relief on the American side was as obvious as the choppy
weather. Bush had all the time he needed to lay out a dozen mild
suggestions to improve U.S. relations with Moscow. He was not
forced to come up with a quick reply to dramatic and unexpected
propositions from the Soviet side.
   Still it wasn't all sweetness and light, as Bush remarked at the
end.
   The hundreds of reporters who dutifully filed from Malta the
gushing accounts of an improved superpower relationship provided to
them by anonymous U.S. ``sources,'' are balancing the record now
that they are back home with the negative side of Bush's first
rendezvous with Gorbachev.
   It turns out, for instance, that the Soviet leader has no
intention of complying with a U.S. demand that he force the ouster
of President Najibullah in Afghanistan.
   Bush told Gorbachev the Moslem rebels who are trying to take
power in Kabul with U.S. support are unwilling to reach a
settlement with Najibullah to end an 11-year-old civil war that has
taken an estimated 1 million casualties.
   But Gorbachev dismissed the demand, saying Najibullah, whose
forces are armed by Moscow, is a national figure who is growing
more popular all the time.
   It also turned out that the Soviets have not shelved their
opposition to the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative. The dispute
over ``Star Wars'' is still an obstacle to concluding a treaty to
trim bombers, missiles and submarines in time for the
Bush-Gorbachev summit meeting in Washington next June.
   The Soviets offered in September to separate negotiations over
space-based defenses from the talks on reducing strategic weapons
arsenals 30 percent to 50 percent. But it turned out at the summit
that Gorbachev still is determined to establish clear rules on what
the two sides can do with weapons in space.
   Two other problems surfaced even before the summit adjourned.
   Gorbachev told Bush he did not know how Soviet arms are getting
to leftist rebels in El Salvador. And he is determined to have
negotiators cap submarine-launched cruise missiles.
   That's a double problem. The missiles are hard to keep track of
and the United States is reluctant to curb one of its trump cards
in the nuclear weapons competition.
   Gorbachev has been in power nearly five years now.
   American participants in the Malta summit found him confident as
ever.
   He also seems graver, which is understandable considering the
uphill task he has undertaken to reconstruct the Soviet economy and
to maneuver around the dazzling changes that are sweeping Eastern
Europe.
   ``He gave me the impression of a man sure of himself, in
control, not ebullient, nor the quiet of worry,'' said a senior
U.S. official who was at the table with Bush aboard the Maxim Gorky.
   ``He spoke in a very forthright manner about the economic
problems he was up against, his thoughts for tackling them. His
basic theme was `I've got problems and I`m working on them,''' the
official recalled.
   But when you look at the Soviet problems, the official said,
``they are very deep and very broad.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid was in Malta, covering his ninth
U.S.-Soviet summit for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
