<FIRST>r w PM-AirlineReport     12-08 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Report,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fewer Passengers Bumped</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Airline Statistics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major airlines are bumping fewer passengers
off assigned flights, the Transportation Department says.
   The latest Air Travel Consumer Report released Thursday showed
2.61 passengers for every 10,000 boardings were told they would
have to take another flight because of over booking during the
first nine months of the year.
   The rate for the same period last year was 3.02.
   Mishandled baggage reports against U.S. airlines declined, while
overall consumer complaints increased slightly in October, the
report said.
   The monthly report showed the nation's dozen largest airlines
operated on time 79.5 percent of the time in October, about the
same as in September.
   Mishandled baggage reports declined from 7.25 per 1,000
passengers in September to 6.98 in October.
   Consumer complaints totaled 1,143, compared with 1,104 a month
earlier.
</TEXT>
