<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Shootings 4thLd-Writethru a0401 12-08 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Shootings, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0401,1060</SECOND>
<HEAD>Montreal Mass Killer Identified; Said Women `Spoiled' His Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with police saying Lepine had planned
to enter engineering school, was war-movie fanatic; picks up 4th pvs, `As
he...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY7,24,MTL6A, LaserColor MTL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gunman who roamed through the University of
Montreal's engineering school and killed 14 women carried a suicide
letter vowing to seek revenge on women for ruining his life, police
said Thursday.
   The killer _ identified by police Thursday night as Marc Lepine,
25, of Montreal _ also wounded nine women and four men before
killing himself Wednesday in the worst mass murder in Canadian
history.
   Police identified Lepine as a war-movie fanatic who ``was always
frustrated by women,'' said police spokesman Andre Tessier.
   Lepine had trouble developing relationships with women and broke
off all communication at the first sign of rejection, said police
spokesman Andre Tessier. Lepine had taken courses with the aim of
entering the engineering school, Tessier said.
   As he roamed through the modern, six-story engineering building
firing a rifle, Lepine ranted, ``I want the women!'' and ``You're
all a bunch of feminists! I hate feminists!'' witnesses told police.
   One of the wounded remained in critical but stable condition
Thursday. The rest were out of danger.
   A Montreal gun shop salesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Lepine bought the hunting rifle used in the
slayings on Nov. 21 for $510. The provincial gun permit was in the
name of Marc Lepine.
   Earlier, a broadcast report gave the name as Marc Lapin.
   The employee said Lepine bought a handgun there about two years
ago.
   ``He didn't appear to be any crazier than anyone else _
actually, he was a bit of a joker,'' he said.
   Police said Lepine, who was single and unemployed, was born in
Montreal to a Quebec mother and an Algerian father and was known as
Gamil Gharbi until age seven. His parents separated and he took his
mother's last name, Lepine, and the first name Marc.
   Senior police investigator Jacques Duchesneau told a news
conference Lepine ``had certain problems in relationships with
women. He was known to be always very gentle and courteous with
women until the relationship didn't go his way.
   ``He seemed to be very intelligent.''
   Duchesneau said Lepine ``was obsessed with war films and
electronics. He seemed to have no problems with alcohol or drugs.''
   In his letter, Lepine said he was committing a ``political act''
in killing the women because ``feminists had always ruined my
life,'' police reported.
   Duchesneau said Lepine used a .223-caliber Sturm Ruger
semi-automatic rifle.
   He also carried a hunting knife and sheath, two boxes of bullets
and a 30-bullet clip.
   He was described as about 5-foot-9 inches, weighing 160 pounds,
with brown hair and blue eyes.
   The gun shop employee said the firearm bought by Lepine was a
big seller, with hundreds sold in his store every year.
   Canada's gun control laws are generally stricter than those in
the United States.
   Duchesneau said ``it was quite clear'' that a three-page
handwritten letter signed ``Marc'' and found on Lepine's body was a
suicide note. He said it specified Dec. 6 as the date for Lepine's
death.
   He said it contained the names of 15 women that were believed
taken from a newspaper, but declined to elaborate except to say not
all were public figures.
   Duchesneau told reporters the letter said Lepine was seeking
revenge on women.
   ``He mentioned in the letter that he did that because of
political reasons. He said feminists kind of spoiled his life and
he hasn't been happy in life for the last seven years,'' the
officer said.
   ``I think he blamed women in general, saying that if his life
was ruined it was mainly because of women.''
   The letter also mentioned former army Cpl. Denis Lortie, jailed
for life after killing three people and wounding 13 in 1984 with
submachine-gun fire in the Quebec legislature.
   Duchesneau said Lepine identified himself as a student but did
not specify a school. He also said Lepine wrote that he was refused
for military induction because he ``wasn't a social person.''
   Duchesneau said Lepine ``was not very successful with certain
courses in his studies,'' and had few female friends.
   Police said 35 to 37 shots were fired.
   The school was crowded on the last day of classes before
examinations when the killer arrived at 4:30 p.m. EST.
   Police said he first shot a woman in a second-floor corridor,
then entered a room on that floor where a class with about 50 male
and 10 female students was in session.
   Witnesses said he told the class to separate by sex and sent the
men into the corridor before opening fire, killing six more women.
   ``It was just like Rambo. He had at least two ammunition belts
on his chest,'' said engineering student Robert Leclerc, who was in
the classroom.
   Leclerc, 23, said the killer told the women, ``You're all a
bunch of feminists. I hate feminists.''
   ``My friend, Nathalie, said, `No, it's not true. We're not
feminists.' He fired into the group,'' Leclerc said.
   Police said Lepine then went to the first floor where he killed
three women in a cafeteria, next entered a third-floor classroom
where he shot four women to death and then killed himself.
   The engineering school was closed Thursday in mourning.
   A temporary morgue was set up in the building so parents could
identify bodies.
   Pierre Leclair, head of public relations for Montreal police,
arrived at the school to find his daughter, Maryse, dead on the
floor.
   Montreal Mayor Jean Dore told reporters, with tears in his eyes,
that his babysitter was one of the women killed.
   A male student laid a wreath of roses in the snow outside the
engineering building Thursday morning. Someone left a poem mourning
the loss attached to a wall nearby.
   A candlelight vigil by about 2,000 people was held outside the
school Thursday night, but was marred by a scuffle when people on
the podium grappled for a megaphone used to address the crowd.
</TEXT>
