<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HumanRights     12-08 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Human Rights,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Colombia Most Dangerous for Rights Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia leads a list of countries in which
human rights activists were killed this year, and U.S. and
Colombian human rights leaders say the troubled country's
government shares the blame with its drug dealers.
   ``All the problems of human rights in Colombia are not due to
the drugs,'' Gustavo Gallon, director of the Colombian section of
the Andean Commission of Jurists, told reporters Thursday.
   Aryeh Neier, executive director of Human Rights Watch, said many
of the killings reflect ``alliances ... between drug dealers and
middle level military and police officials in parts of the
country.''
   Gallon and Neier spoke at a news conference at which the human
rights monitoring organization released a report showing 68
killings in 1989 of people who monitor human rights abuses in their
countries.
   Colombia topped the list with 24, followed by Brazil with 14
killings _ many of which, the report said, ``reflect the intense
struggle over land distribution in rural areas.''
   Gallon, speaking in Spanish with an interpreter, said, ``The
situation of human rights was already bad in Colombia long before
the drug problem existed. What has happened is that it has gotten
worse since.''
   Neier said, ``A large number of the killings do involve drug
dealers, but we also believe there have been alliances between drug
dealers and middle-level military and police officials in parts of
the country, and that a lot of theses killings reflect those
alliances.''
   The human rights official said he believed the government of
President Virgilio Barco ``is genuinely concerned about human
rights and is not itself, at least at the level of the president
and those associated with him, engaged in these kinds of killings
in any way.''
   ``But we want the Colombian government to act more firmly
against those within the armed forces and police forces in Colombia
who do have the alliances with the drug dealers,'' he said.
   The 345-page report discussed 1,200 cases of persecution of
human rights monitors in 72 countries, including arrest,
imprisonment and torture, killings and 10 unexplained
``disappearances.''
   South Africa topped the list in the total number of persecution
cases, taking up 36 pages.
   A South African human rights representative, Dean Simon
Farisani, said, ``While we appreciate at least the readiness of
(South African President F.W.) de Klerk not to throw police and
members of the defense force on our marching people, he had
absolutely no choice because those people continue to be involved
in a defiant campaign, defying the laws that have been imposed on
them.''
   Czechoslovakia, gripped by turmoil over reforms being sought by
a pro-democracy movement, was second in the number of cases of
persecution, taking up 23 pages.
   ``A substantial number of cases involve people who were released
from prison just a couple of weeks prior to publication of this
report,'' Neier said.
   ``The changes that have been taking place in Central and Eastern
Europe have had a significant effect,'' he said. However, he added,
``Not all of the persons we are concerned about in Czechoslovakia
have been released, so there is a way to go.''
   The report said all but five of the human rights killings
occurred in countries generally classified as democracies.
   Dictatorships, the report said, often ``don't have to engage in
killing because they very often suppress all activity of this sort
so firmly that no one has the opportunity to engage in human rights
monitoring,'' Neier said. ``It is when things open up some, but
don't open up all the way, that the greatest climate of danger
seems to prevail.''
   The New York-based Human Rights Watch is made up of five
regional committees: Africa Watch, Americas Watch, Asia Watch,
Helsinki Watch and Middle East.
</TEXT>
