<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Redux     12-08 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Redux,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peaceful Revolution Brings Reminders of 1968, But Differences Are
Profound</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer covered events in Czechoslovakia in
1968 before the Warsaw Pact invasion that ended the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The peaceful revolution sweeping Czechoslovakia
brings many reminders of the euphoric ``Prague Spring'' that was
crushed by Soviet tanks 21 years ago.
   The excitement, the endless discussions, the hopes and the sweet
taste of freedom to challenge decades-old dogmas are there. But the
similarities are few and the differences are profound:
   The ``Prague Spring'' was born within the ruling Communist Party
after years of fermentation. The change in 1989 came from an
opposition group that mushroomed into a popular movement in a
matter of days.
   In 1968, no one called for deleting the constitutional guarantee
of the Communist Party's power monopoly. Now, that guarantee is
gone, after just 10 days of huge demonstrations against one-party
rule.
   There were no slogans in 1968 urging free elections. Now, that
call is on signs and posters throughout the nation.
   The ill-fated 1968 predecessor of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
perestroika had lofty aims to overcome what was then conceded to be
a ``deep crisis of society.''
   A 24,000-word party program included a long list of goals,
ranging from civil rights guarantees in a state of law to a
market-oriented economy. It was a vision of ``broadest democracy.''
   Criticism spread in a way that was then without precedent in any
Communist country. Generals criticized their chiefs of staff,
editors their publishers, government officials their ministers, and
ministers the head of state.
   It became known as ``socialism with a human face,'' and it was
the last real chance for communism to survive in a country where
the party won a 1947 election.
   But even the most outspoken critics of the party, the signers of
the famous ``2,000 words'' in June 1968, stressed that the
Communists had a vital function in the work for ``the common cause
that has the title `socialism.'''
   ``The leading role of the party was never in doubt then,'' says
Cestmir Cisar, a Central Committee secretary in 1968 and a chief
target of Moscow's criticism at the time. ``People trusted the
party.''
   But now, Cisar said, ``20 years of pseudo-socialism that have
since passed have made people lose their confidence.''
   ``The young people totally reject the word `Socialism.' They do
not want to hear it. And that is understandable because they have
never known any other form of socialism.''
   ``In 1968, the society was ready to accept our kind of
socialism,'' he added. ``This time the Communist Party has
completely lost its (leading) position.''
   Like Cisar, Libuse Silhanova was expelled from the Communist
Party in a large-scale 1970 purge. She lost her teaching job and
barely managed by knitting for a cooperative.
   A founding member of the Charter 77 civil rights group, she says
that 1989 cannot be compared with 1968.
   ``Except for the spontaneity and the euphoria among the people
in the street, there are no similarities,'' she said. ``And the
euphoria is greater now.''
   But so is the concern that the reforms may still fail again, she
made plain. ``In 1968, there was virtually no fear in
Czechoslovakia of interference from abroad,'' she said. ``People
were shocked when the Russians arrived.''
   Now, she says, there is continued fear that the pro-democracy
movement will be suppressed by hard-liners still firmly entrenched
in the party hierarchy.
   ``A relapse is still possible,,'' she cautioned. ``We know the
secret police and the state security. They are wicked and tricky.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EmployeeExpenses     12-08 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employee Expenses,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Announces New Rules on Employee Expenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New IRS rules will free employees from having
to deal with expense accounts on their tax returns.
   If the rules are followed to the letter, employers will not have
to withhold taxes from their workers' expense allowances.
   The new regulations, announced Thursday by the Internal Revenue
Service, ``are designed to avoid harsh results for employers who
have reasonable substantiation methods,'' said Mary Oppenhiemer,
the agency's deputy assistant chief counsel.
   Starting in 1990, an employer must require that employees
substantiate expenses and turn back any portion of an advance that
is not substantiated. If those two conditions are met, the employer
need not list any part of the expense reimbursement as income on
the worker's W-2 form and the worker will not have to claim a
deduction for the allowance.
   In that case, Ms. Oppenhiemer said, ``the only amounts that will
ever show up on the employee's Form W-2 are amounts the employee
does not substantiate or does not return to the employer.''
   If the worker does not substantiate expenses or does not return
any overage, that excess would be listed as income on the W-2. An
employee then might be able to take an itemized deduction for part
of the allowance.
   The regulations permit employers to rely on a ``good-faith
interpretation'' of the law in accounting for 1989 expenses.
   Ms. Oppenhiemer told reporters the new regulations are in line
with the agency's moves toward simplification.
   ``We believe that the regulations will not impose any
significant new administrative burden on most employers,'' she
said. In fact, she said, the changes ``will actually reduce
compliance burdens for many taxpayers.''
   The regulations also require that taxes be withheld from expense
allowances unless the substantiation and return-of-excess
procedures are followed. Current rules say withholding is not
required if the employer reasonably believes the allowances will be
used for business expenses.
   The tougher withholding rule will take effect July 1.
   The IRS also announced that the standard mileage rate for
business use of an automobile in 1990 will be 26 cents a mile, up
from 25{ cents this year.
   This marks the first time the IRS has disclosed this annual
adjustment in advance; the rate for a year is usually announced
about two months before the end of that year.
   For 1990 and later years, the business mileage rate will be 26
cents across the board; present rules permit the full rate only for
the first 15,000 miles and 11 cents for each additional mile.
   The IRS said employers will be deemed to have met substantiation
requirements if they use the 26-cent rate in reimbursing employees
for business use of their cars.
   The standard mileage rate for use of a personal car for
charitable activities will continue at 12 cents a mile next year.
The rate for purposes of calculating medical and moving expenses
will remain at 9 cents a mile.
   Another new procedure announced Thursday provides a simplified
``safe harbor'' option for employer reimbursements for employee
travel expenses.
   This will allow employers to use a rate of $122 per day for 28
high-cost areas and $85 per day for all other parts of the United
States.
   The high-cost areas: Death Valley, Los Angeles, Palm Springs,
San Francisco and Santa Barbara, Calif.; Aspen and Vail, Colo.; the
Washington, D.C., area; Atlanta; Chicago; Annapolis, Columbia and
Ocean City, Md.; Andover, Boston, Martha's Vineyard-Nantucket and
Plymouth, Mass.; Conway, N.H.;
   Atlantic City, Newark, Ocean City-Cape May and
Princeton-Trenton, N.J.; New York City and White Plains, N.Y.;
Philadelphia; Newport, R.I.; Hilton Head, S.C., and Dallas-Fort
Worth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
