<FIRST>r a PM-RapPaging     12-08 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rap Paging,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Sky-Sky-Sky-Sky-SkyPager': Paging Service not Amused by Rap Hit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SkyPager is mentioned in a rap music hit,
but the owner of the nationwide paging service believes it's
off-beat publicity.
   Skypager service, owned by Mobile Telecommunication Technologies
Corp. of Jackson, is the theme of a popular rap song by Sir
Mix-a-lot, a Seattle band.
   Mtel officials have considered suing over the rap hit, citing
possible damage to SkyPager's marketing efforts aimed at
professionals.
   ``It's a delicate situation. We did not authorize anything
that's on there,'' said James Phillips, president of SkyTel Corp.,
Mtel's satellite paging subsidiary.
   The song, ``Beepers,'' is written by band leader Anthony Ray of
Seattle (alias Sir Mix-a-lot).
   Ray and another band member use SkyPager, which allows them to
call a toll-free number to page each other in most U.S. cities. The
service, geared to traveling executives, uses a satellite signal.
   A few lyrics from ``Beepers'':
   ``SkyPager. Looks like a phaser. That's the attire of a
Northwest player. ... How does Mix-a-lot communicate? With beepers,
baby. Beepers.''
   The song gives the service's toll-free telephone number and
repeats a part of the computer-synthesized message that callers
hear when they page Skypager clients.
   ``Welcome to SkyPager. To use SkyPager, press the pound key
after each entry. Please enter the pin number you wish.
   ``SkyPager. SkyPager. SkyPager. Sky-Sky-Sky-Sky-SkyPager.''
   ``That song certainly doesn't suggest the normal use of our
product,'' Phillips said. ``We don't know if we'll take any action
or not. We're friends of the music industry, and we want to stay
friends.''
   The Jackson company has a number of music industry customers,
including Stevie Wonder and Barbra Streisand.
   Band manager Larry Serrin of Artist Management Inc. said the
SkyPager name and voice is readily available to the public.
   ``It's pretty much public domain,'' he said. ``If anything else,
it's promoting SkyPagers.''
   A SkyPager customer alerted Mtel to the song a few weeks ago.
   So far, Phillips hasn't noticed much impact on business from the
song, except for increased calls to SkyPager's service center.
   ``I can't say much for the lyrics, but it's a good sound,'' he
said. ``Hopefully, people will just listen to the music.''
</TEXT>
