<FIRST>u i BC-Panama-FightReax     12-08 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Panama-Fight Reax,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans Quickly Put Duran Defeat Aside</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government billed the fight
between Roberto Duran and Sugar Ray Leonard as a political battle
with the United States, using it to drum up support for Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Government news media predicted it would be a night to celebrate
a triumph over imperialism. But Leonard spoiled the party in Las
Vegas Thursday night with an easy 12-round decision over Panama's
native son.
   ``With this defeat, what we have is a night like a tomb,'' said
one of the few people on the street after the fight.
   ``It is clear as water,'' another fan said. ``He lost. Sugar Ray
is a better boxer.''
   The government, in a sense, was the only winner in Panama.
Because of U.S. economic sanctions against Panama, television
transmission rights were sold only for transmission by a private
station that serves only Panama City and Colon.
   But just hours before the fight, the government ordered
television stations into a nationwide hookup, forcing the private
station that had the rights to share the signal with the government
station.
   Early in the evening, people gathered at homes or set up large
television screens on sidewalks and lined up beer coolers in
preparation for the fiesta to celebrate a Duran victory.
   In El Chorrillo, a slum near the entrance to the Panama Canal
where Duran was born and ran barefoot as a child, hundreds gathered
to watch the fight on a large television screen perched on a
flatbed truck.
   Loud music played for hours before the fight and fans danced in
the streets.
   ``This is more than just a fight,'' said national assemblyman
Luis Esquivel. He said the Noriega's Defense Forces, which give him
the clout to control the nation, had provided the screen.
   ``We are trying to develop our sense of nationalism,'' he said.
``Even if Duran loses, this will be an affirmation of our
nationality in the face of U.S. aggression.''
   Fans stood and sang the national anthem before the fight and
then cheered in the first few rounds. By the sixth round it was
clear victory celebrations were off.
   ``He is tied up,'' said a fan of Duran, who, at 38, appeared
slow in trying to get close to Leonard.
   As the last round ended, a woman picked up her chair, and said
dejectedly: ``Well, it's over.''
   ``But life goes on,'' she added, turning to a companion. After
all, if there wasn't a Duran victory to celebrate, there was
something else.
   A few minutes later, as music started playing again, the woman
was dancing in the street. It was just after midnight, and Panama's
Mother's Day had begun.
</TEXT>
