<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     12-08 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel Says He Would Become President If Crisis Required</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He was harassed, reviled and often
imprisoned for challenging the Communist government. Now, dissident
playwright Vaclav Havel says he is willing to become president.
   Havel, a banned playwright and leader of the opposition movement
that has brought the hard-line government to its knees, has
repeatedly declined political office.
   But, when asked again Thursday if he would accept the presidency
if it was offered, he said he would.
   ``I have repeatedly said that my occupation is a writer and that
I have no political ambitions. I don't feel myself to be a
professional politician, but have always put the public interest
ahead of my own,'' he told a crowded news conference in the Laterna
Magika theater.
   ``And, if God help us, the situation should develop in such a
way that the only service I could render my country would be to do
this, then, of course, I would do it,'' Havel said.
   He stressed that nobody is pushing his candidacy and that he
only would assume the presidency if this was the only way out of
the standoff between the beleaguered government and the
increasingly powerful opposition movement.
   ``The more democratic and more normal the condition in our
country, the less my role will be,'' the mustachioed, blond
playwright said.
   Havel has avoided interviews in the past two hectic weeks that
have seen his opposition group, the Civic Forum, direct a movement
that has forced the Communists to relinquish their 41-year monopoly
on power, ousted most hard-line leaders and paved the way for a
coalition government that could restore democracy.
   ``If I continually commented on the revolution, I could not have
participated in it,'' he said.
   He characterized events so far as a ``cultural revolution'' that
began as a student protest against police violence on Nov. 17 and
mushroomed into a movement that may return Czechoslovakia to its
democratic, humanistic traditions.
   ``What is important is what the students began with, that is,
the humanitarian dimension, resistance to violence, the longing for
truth and moral integrity,'' said Havel. His current role follows a
long tradition of Czech intellectuals doubling as political leaders.
   As a founder member of Charter 77, eastern Europe's oldest human
rights movement, Havel has spent most of the last 13 years under
police surveillance and served 4{ years in jail for his activism.
   Havel said the main aim of Civic Forum is to see the country
enjoy free elections soon, but he stressed that Czechoslovakia
should not necessarily return to its same prewar system of
capitalist democracy.
   Now, ``a modern contemporary government should design a modern
contemporary system which would return to people their honor and
freedom,'' Havel said.
   In this struggle, he said, naming the right prime minister ``is
more important than 10 presidents,'' whose role as head of state is
largely ceremonial.
   Havel said he would like to see Jan Carnogursky, a Slovak
dissident who is a lawyer and a respected Roman Catholic activist,
as premier.
   Civic Forum is pushing Carnogursky as a first deputy premier to
the Communist premier named Thursday, Marian Calfa, another Slovak.
   By tradition, if the premier is Slovak, Czechoslovakia's
president is a Czech.
   The incumbent president, Gustav Husak, is a Slovak who is
regarded as one of the Communists most responsible for the
crackdown on reform after the Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed the
``Prague Spring'' in 1968.
   Civic Forum said Thursday it wants as president a Czech who is
not a member of any political party and ``not connected in any way
with the current structures of government.''
   Havel? The playwright-turned-politician was presidentially
diplomatic.
   ``You don't accept the basic presidential quality of answering
in a roundabout way,'' he joked. ``I have heard news conferences by
President Bush and I've heard him give evasive answers and say `No
comment.' I so far have not said, `No comment.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArtsSlanderSuit Bjt   12-08 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arts Slander Suit, Bjt,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clash Over 19th Century Artist Bruises Egos in Art Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The volatile mixture of art and commerce has
erupted in a multimillion-dollar lawsuit filed by a collector
against a scholar and the venerable Metropolitan Museum of Art in
New York.
   The man in the middle: American artist John La Farge, a muralist
and stained glass maker who lived from 1835 to 1910.
   La Farge decorated the palaces of New York's gilded age and
public buildings nationwide. He invented the opalescent glass
widely commercialized by Tiffany.
   His works are selling for up to hundreds of thousands of dollars.
   The vagaries of assigning a monetary value to his individual
creative works are at the center of the lawsuit filed in federal
court here by Sean M. McNally. He's a collector and former Goldman
Sachs investment banker who devotes his time to studying and
dealing in La Farge works.
   McNally claims he's the victim of professional jealousy, while a
lawyer for La Farge scholar James Yarnall of Washington charges
that the lawsuit challenges the integrity of art scholarship.
   Others are concerned the real loser may be La Farge.
   ``La Farge is too great an artist to be cast around in the
gutter this way,'' says William Vareika, a Newport, R.I., gallery
owner.
   The lawsuit claims Yarnall, who is preparing a catalogue of La
Farge's works, engaged in a campaign to undermine the value of
McNally's collection and disparage his expertise on the artist. The
Met allegedly stood by Yarnall despite knowing he was wrong.
   Yarnall's lawyer, Peter R. Stern, called the lawsuit the case of
an art speculator against an art scholar.
   ``I think that this case represents a serious attack on all art
scholarship and history,'' said Stern.
   Met spokesman John Ross said McNally's claims are ``without
basis.'' He said Yarnall was an independent contractor who was
mistakenly listed in the museum's annual report as a staff member.
   According to McNally's court papers, the seeds of the dispute
were sown in February 1988 when McNally appraised a La Farge piece
called ``Moon Window'' for a private collector at $20,000.
   Yarnall told Met benefactor Richard M. Schwartz that ``Moon
Window'' was worth $200,000, the lawsuit said. Schwartz bought the
work for $165,000 a month later.
   In April, its companion piece sold at auction for $14,200.
   That sale showed Yarnall's appraisal to be inaccurate and set
him on his course to ``denigrate and diminish'' both McNally's
collection and his professional reputation, the lawsuit alleged.
   ``People get jealous,'' said McNally's attorney, Christopher W.
Hyde.
   According to the lawsuit, an example of this was when Yarnall
later told Schwartz in the presence of Met officials that a McNally
window was unimportant, badly restored and not worth the $150,000
Schwartz was ready to pay for it. That appraisal sank the deal.
   Then in June, Yarnall allegedly told Vareika, who was exhibiting
McNally's La Farge works, that one of McNally's windows was not
authentic.
   The lawsuit, filed Nov. 28, has slander, libel and contract
interference claims and seeks at least $28 million in punitive and
other damages.
   La Farge scholarship is particularly competitive because most of
the material about him has remained with descendants, said Henry
Adams, a La Farge expert and American art curator at the
Nelson-Atkins Museum in Kansas City.
   And the La Farge market is particularly difficult to evaluate
because of the broad range of quality and media in his work, Adams
said.
   Museums are put in a difficult position when asked to give
appraisals, said Ulysses Dietz, curator of decorative arts at the
Newark Museum.
   ``It's a real clash between the function of a museum and the
function of a marketplace,'' Dietz said, particularly when donors
of works are seeking tax deductions for their largesse.
   But lawsuits such as the one filed by McNally could have a
``very chilling effect on a museum's desire to help spread
information,'' he said. ``It's what every museum lives in constant
fear of.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Keating-Money     12-08 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Keating-Money,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEC Investigating Clusters of Contributions Linked to Keating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On Oct. 18, 1988, more than 30 family members
or business associates of controversial savings and loan figure
Charles H. Keating Jr. contributed $1,000 each to then-Sen. Chic
Hecht's re-election campaign.
   The Federal Election Commission _ which puts strict
$1,000-per-person limits on contributions to an election campaign _
is investigating whether such multiple contributions were handled
illegally, agency spokesman Scott Moxley said Thursday.
   The FEC acted at the request of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a
recipient of Keating's largess who asked the agency Oct. 30 whether
there was ``potentially illegal action'' by Keating's
``corporations and contributors.''
   McCain's request only referred to the Keating-related donations
he received, but Moxley said the agency can decide to expand the
probe to contributions to other members of Congress. He would not
say whether the FEC has done so.
   Keating and his associates and family members followed the
pattern of multiple donations during a campaign _ often on the same
day _ with a number of lawmakers as he admittedly sought to
increase his influence with Congress.
   Spokesmen for Keating did not return several telephone calls
seeking reaction on the FEC probe.
   Among Keating's contributions during the 1980s were $1.3 million
to the campaigns and causes of five senators: McCain and Democrats
Alan Cranston of California, the majority whip; Banking Committee
Chairman Donald W. Riegle Jr. of Michigan; Governmental Affairs
Committee Chairman John Glenn of Ohio and Dennis DeConcini of
Arizona.
   The five intervened on Keating's behalf with federal banking
regulators in April 1987 when his Lincoln Savings and Loan, of
Irvine, Calif., was collapsing.
   The Senate ethics committee is trying to determine whether there
was a connection between the intervention and the donations.
   Now taken over by the federal government, the expected $2
billion-plus cost of protecting Lincoln's depositors should make
this the most expensive thrift failure in the nation's history.
   Federal election law prohibits anyone from making a donation on
behalf of someone else. For instance, a corporate chief could not
have employees give $1,000 under their names and reimburse them to
skirt the donation limit.
   Moxley said the law is unclear on whether someone could
orchestrate contributions by employees with no promise of
reimbursement.
   The Associated Press requested an FEC check of campaign
contributions made on specific days by Keating, his immediate
family members and business associates. The dates were chosen at
random.
   The agency computer found:
   _More than 30 separate $1,000 donations went from Keating
associates or family members to the general election campaign of
then-Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev. on Oct. 18, 1988.
   _On April 9, 1988, Keating and five associates contributed to
the primary campaign of Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah. The same day,
Keating, his wife and two others gave to Hatch's general election
campaign.
   _On March 11, 1987, there were nearly 20 Keating-related
contributions to the primary campaign of Riegle and seven to his
general election campaign; and even more multiple donations the
same day. Many of the contributions could have been tickets to a
dinner for Riegle on March 23 at a Keating property, the
Ponchartrain Hotel in Detroit. The $1,000 per-person limit applies
to such events.
   _Sen. Timothy Wirth, a member of the Senate Banking Committee,
received four $1,000 donations on Feb. 13, 1987 for his general
election campaign.
   _DeConcini received two donations to his general election
campaign and four to his primary campaign on Oct. 29, 1987.
   McCain received $112,000 in campaign contributions from Keating
and associates, and promised to ``promptly refund'' any money the
FEC finds was given improperly. He previously announced he was
reimbursing American Continental Corp., the parent company of
Lincoln, $13,433 for flights the senator and his family took aboard
Keating's corporate plane to and from the Bahamas in 1984-86.
   DeConcini received $48,100 for his 1988 re-election campaign but
announced he was returning the money.
   Cranston received $39,000 in campaign money. He solicited from
Keating $850,000 for three voter education projects in California
and $85,000 for the California Democratic Party.
   Glenn received $34,000 in direct contributions and a political
action committee associated with him was given $200,000.
   Riegle received $76,100 for his 1988 re-election campaign but
announced he was returning the money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
