<DOCNO> AP891208-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Budget     12-08 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Budget,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Gets $292 Billion To Spend in 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and top aides
are ``crunching the numbers'' to meet White House demands the
Pentagon hold its spending to around $292 billion during the next
fiscal year.
   The White House, in its attempt to meet the Gramm-Rudman budget
cutting targets, has informed Cheney that military spending won't
be allowed to keep pace with inflation, Pentagon sources say.
   ``It's going to be a net reduction in real growth,'' meaning an
increase in actual spending of less than the expected inflation
rate of 4.1 percent, said a defense source, who spoke on condition
he not be identified by name.
   ``They're crunching the numbers,'' said another senior Pentagon
official, indicating Cheney and his aides now must draw up plans to
deal with the amount of funding the White House will allow.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams told reporters on Wednesday
that Cheney received a figure a day earlier from the White House,
but he declined to discuss it.
   The spokesman said the department now must make plans to conform
with the new figure for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, 1990 so
it may be included in the formal presentation of the president's
budget to Congress next month.
   He said Cheney is determined to send ``a realistic budget'' to
Congress.
   Cheney himself has said he does not want his budget labeled
``dead on arrival'' because it contained unrealistic expectations
of increased spending.
   The debate over the 1991 fiscal year's budget comes as the
Pentagon attempts to grapple with near-certain cuts over the long
term in light of eased tensions abroad and budget-deficit problems
at home.
   Cheney has ordered the service chiefs to come up with plans that
could allow up to $180 billion to be trimmed from future projected
budgets in the years 1992 through 1994.
   But House Armed Services Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
says the Bush administration bungled its announcement of future
cuts in defense spending by failing to spell out a military
strategy, leaving planners with a dollar figure target but no
guidance on policy.
   ``The budget exercise asked the services where they would cut.
It didn't tell them what threats to assume, what roles to emphasize
or what missions to minimize,'' Aspin said in a speech Thursday.
   Aspin said the cuts Cheney has discussed with reporters are
based on unrealistic budget projections.
   Under the last budget put out by the Reagan administration,
projected military outlays for fiscal 1991 were estimated at $304.7
billion.
   In the budget for the present fiscal year, Pentagon
appropriations set by Congress were $286 billion. An increase to
$292 billion would be 2.1 percent, though the $286 billion figure
is not final.
   The administration expects inflation to be 4.1 percent through
1990.
   The actual amount the department will spend will affect the
government's 1991 deficit, which must meet the Gramm-Rudman target
of $64 billion. For the current fiscal year, the deficit target
will range between $100 billion and $105 billion.
   Meanwhile, Air Force Secretary Donald Rice indicated budget
pressures may force the service to stretch out purchases of the
costly B-2 stealth bomber.
   The Pentagon has invested about $23 billion in the program and
hopes to purchase 132 bombers at a cost of about $70 billion. But
lawmakers profess ``sticker shock'' over the price tag _ estimated
at $530 million for each plane.
   The secretary told reporters he believes all 132 planes are
necessary and the bomber is an essential part of the Pentagon's
plans for nuclear deterrence, even if arms control agreements are
reached with the Soviet Union in the coming year on conventional
and strategic nuclear weapons.
   ``We are .. looking at the option of procuring it over a longer
period of time. ... We're interested in doing that only if it can
still be done efficiently,'' Rice said.
   ``I think 132 is a good number and if it were to be questioned,
it is something that doesn't need to be decided for quite a few
years to come,'' he added.
   In July, Air Force officials told congressmen that stretching
out purchases over several years could raise the aircraft's price
considerably.
</TEXT>
