<FIRST>r a PM-FBISpy     12-08 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI Spy,0648</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Ex-Agent Recalls Soviet Woman Who Was His Lover; Says He's No Spy
^By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``She was charming, outgoing, vivacious and
her English was atrocious,'' ex-FBI agent Richard Miller recalled
of the Soviet woman who became his lover and led to his conviction
as a spy.
   After five years in prison and reversal of his conviction,
Miller conceded his affair with Svetlana Ogorodnikov was ``the
stupidest thing I've done in my life,'' but insisted he never was a
spy.
   ``I love my country,'' said Miller, the only FBI agent ever
convicted of espionage. ``I'm a patriotic kind of guy. ... I know
in my heart I'm not a traitor.''
   The 52-year-old Miller, released on bail last month pending a
new trial, talked Thursday with a group of reporters who had sought
interviews. His lawyers, Stanley Greenberg and Joel Levine, stood
by to veto any questions about his planned defense. But Miller
openly answered most queries.
   Asked to describe the proudest moment in his FBI career, Miller
thought for a few minutes, then cited a 1972 trip to Washington,
when he and his family had a picture taken with then FBI chief J.
Edgar Hoover.
   ``That,'' he said, ``was one of the proudest moments.''
   The former agent was alternately serious and wise-cracking. He
called his upcoming third trial, ``Miller Three. It makes me feel
like Rambo.''
   He spoke of his troubled 20-year FBI career, his extramarital
affair with Mrs. Ogorodnikov, his return to the Mormon faith and
adjustment to life outside prison.
   ``In prison a person loses one of the most precious things a
person can lose and that is freedom of choice. They tell you when
to sleep, when to eat, when to do laundry. I'm having a difficult
time adjusting to making simple decisions.''
   His first trial ended in a jury deadlock. At his second trial in
1986, he was convicted of giving his lover a secret FBI reporting
guide in return for sex, money and gold.
   His attorneys claim he was a bumbler trying to redeem his
lackluster career by infiltrating the KGB through Mrs. Ogorodnikov,
a Soviet emigre. Miller still contends that was his misguided
purpose.
   ``A lot of the time I was a good FBI agent. One of the
exceptions was the stupid, idiotic thing I tried to do with
Svetlana. It was one of the stupidest things I've done. In fact, it
was the stupidest thing I've done in my life.''
   Mrs. Ogorodnikov and her husband, Nikolay, pleaded guilty to
conspiracy to commit espionage and are serving prison terms.
   ``As far as Svetlana goes, I'm very sad that she has to spend
time in prison and I wish her the very best as I would any person
who was in prison,'' Miller said.
   He said that his sexual indiscretions with Mrs. Ogorodnikov and
other women wrecked his career and his marriage.
   ``I probably have more guilt over that than any single thing,''
he said. ``I've always tried to be a very moral person and having
five affairs in two years is not very moral. ... I guess I got
caught up in the sexual revolution of the '80s.''
   Of his ex-wife, Paula, mother of his eight children, he said:
``I felt I betrayed her.''
   But they remain on good terms and he hopes to get permission to
spend Christmas with her and the children at her home in Utah.
   Miller was excommunicated from his Mormon faith for extramarital
affairs. But he said he abides by its precepts.
   In April, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned
Miller's conviction on grounds the jury should not have been told
Miller failed lie detector tests.
   He has a new judge and a trial scheduled for May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
