<FIRST>r w PM-SilveradoS&amp;L     12-08 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Silverado S&amp;L,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal S&amp;L Probe Includes Thrift Tied to President's Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loan and junk bond transactions among a group
of savings institutions _ including a Colorado thrift associated
with President Bush's son _ are being examined by federal
authorities for possible improprieties.
   S&amp;L regulator M. Danny Wall confirmed to reporters Thursday that
the Office of Thrift Supervision was continuing to look at several
thrifts which shuffled junk bonds and loans among themselves.
   Such ``daisy chains'' have been used by S&amp;Ls to hide
questionable credits from regulators.
   The transactions under scrutiny involved Lincoln Savings and
Loan Association, Irvine, Calif.; Silverado Banking, Savings and
Loan Association, Denver; San Jacinto Savings Association,
Bellaire, Texas; and MDC Holdings, a real estate investment company
affiliated with Silverado.
   Neil Bush, the president's 34-year-old son, served on the board
of directors of Silverado from 1985 until August 1988, four months
before regulators declared the S&amp;L insolvent.
   The relationship among the institutions raised concern among
regulators earlier in 1988, according to letters released by the
House Banking Committee.
   George Barclay, principal supervisory agent at the Federal Home
Loan Bank of Dallas, wrote to Washington regulators in September
1988 citing the ``apparent unhealthy lending relationship'' among
the institutions and MDC Holdings.
   In an October 1988 response to Barclay, Darrel W. Dochow,
regulatory director of the Federal Home Loan Bank System, wrote:
``Please be assured we are very concerned about the pattern of
activity that we have witnessed between San Jacinto, Lincoln,
Silverado and MDC.'' He indicated the Securities and Exchange
Commission was investigating MDC.
   Federal authorities are also investigating whether seven
thrifts, including Lincoln, Silverado and San Jacinto, inflated
their assets by selling junk bonds to each other at inflated
prices, according to American Banker, a trade publication.
   In a related matter, Wall said his agency investigated and found
invalid complaints that Silverado was treated leniently because of
its link to Neil Bush and to Larry Mizel, the owner of MDC Holdings
and a prominent Republican fund-raiser.
   James Moroney, a former analyst at the Federal Home Loan Bank of
Topeka, has alleged Silverado was insolvent in 1986 but that
regulators held off because of its political ties.
   In fact, Wall said, Silverado was targeted for early regulatory
action to minimize its losses and was seized in December 1988.
   He acknowledged regulatory problems at the Topeka bank, but said
Moroney's specific allegation lacked substance.
   ``This individual was not involved with Silverado. He was not
close to Silverado,'' Wall said. ``Maybe he was smelling smoke, but
that individual didn't have anything.''
   Wall, speaking to reporters after a speech to the Association of
Government Accountants, declined to say whether his agency had
looked into a specific transaction between Neil Bush and a major
borrower from Silverado. However, he said, ``We have looked at a
lot of transactions in and around Silverado.'' A bank owned by the
borrower provided Bush's oil and gas company with a $1 million line
of credit.
   A trade publication, National Thrift and Mortgage News, has
reported the FBI is investigating Silverado. Wall confirmed his
agency made ``referrals'' concerning Silverado but declined to
specify if the referrals were to the FBI or Justice Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
