<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial-Reaction     12-08 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial-Reaction,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorneys Say Officer a Scapegoat; Prosector: System Works</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Riot Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for a Hispanic officer found guilty of
manslaughter in the deaths of two black men said he was a fall guy
used to prevent racial backlash.
   A multi-ethnic jury on Thursday found Officer William Lozano
guilty of manslaughter in the deaths of motorcyclist Clement Lloyd,
23, and passenger Allan Blanchard, 24.
   Attorneys for the Colombian-born officer say they will appeal.
   ``Obviously, the court had its own agenda, and we were here for
justice and not some social engineering or some method of solving
racial problems in Miami,'' said Roy Black, Lozano's attorney. ``We
were here to try to get a fair trial.''
   Circuit Judge Joseph Farina ordered a presentencing
investigation and set a court date for next month.
   The Jan. 16 shooting sparked three days of racial unrest and
police feared that an acquittal in the case would bring more
unrest. The guilty verdict set off a celebration by blacks on the
street where the shooting took place.
   Miami has been racked by racial unrest four times this decade,
including two riots following acquittals of police charged in the
deaths of blacks.
   ``There is no doubt there are many people in this town who are
afraid of any more disturbances,'' Black said. ``And if you add up
the ledgers, it is cheaper to send one police officer to jail than
to pay several million dollars for another riot.''
   Assistant State Attorney John Hogan said the verdict after 7{
hours of jury deliberations was just.
   ``I don't think we take any particular pleasure in convicting a
police officer, but I think there's a great deal of pleasure
realizing the system works no matter what is one's profession or
what his family does,'' said Hogan, the lead prosecutor.
   Prosecutors said Lozano fired unnecessarily at Lloyd, who was
fleeing a police car after a traffic violation. Blanchard died of
injuries suffered in the resulting crash. Lozano claims Lloyd tried
to run him down.
   Black said the appeal would include his unsuccessful argument
for a change of venue. He noted the verdict was sealed for two
hours while preparations for any violence were made.
   ``When we got to the courthouse, you would think World War III
had started,'' Black said. ``There were more armed men with
automatic weapons than I've ever seen in my life and to have a
trial under circumstances like that is absurd.''
</TEXT>
