<DOCNO> AP891208-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearCargo     12-08 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Cargo,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOT Defends Nuke Shipment Routes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Transportation says the
government chose a ``reasonable'' route to transport damaged fuel
from the Three Mile Island nuclear plant to Idaho, despite concerns
that the cargo crosses too many urban areas.
   The DOT said in a 47-page report this week that the Energy
Department made ``a reasonable choice when evaluated against the
multiple objective route selection criteria.''
   However, the report also said, ``During the course of planning
the shipping campaign, the Energy Department did not have
well-developed operational guidelines for route selection.''
   Population exposure was not a significant factor in picking the
route, the report said.
   The Energy Department is 3{ years into a program to haul 300,000
pounds of damaged, radioactive fuel by train from the crippled TMI
Unit 2 reactor in Middletown, Pa., to an Idaho laboratory 2,400
miles away.
   Along the way, the fuel passes through Ohio, Indiana, Illinois,
Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska, Colorado and Wyoming. At the lab, the
material is analyzed by EG&amp;G Idaho, an Energy Department contractor
hoping to learn more about the 1979 TMI incident, the nation's
worst commercial nuclear accident.
   Twenty trips, each taking about five days, have been completed
by the Conrail and Union Pacific railroads. There are expected to
be two more, TMI spokeswoman Mary Wells said Thursday.
   The report noted that the Energy Department ``encountered
opposition to the route, which passes through several large cities
(Pittsburgh, Indianapolis, St. Louis and Kansas City). Most
concerns were from the St. Louis area, and to a lesser extent,
Pittsburgh areas and by the states of Kansas and Illinois.''
   The fuel, along with metal debris, is contained in canisters
secured inside layered stainless steel and lead casks designed to
withstand accidents.
   Because of its confidence in the casks, the Energy Department
did not use population exposure as a major determining factor in
choosing the route, DOT said.
   ``Since the best quality track is usually found on lines
connecting and traversing large population centers, the Energy
Department is generally forced to choose between using higher
quality track and avoiding high population areas,'' the report said.
   The DOT study was prompted by a request from Sen. John Danforth,
D-Mo., for an independent assessment of the route.
   While it found the safety risks acceptable, DOT said the public,
``influenced by the nature of the material, apparently perceives a
risk higher than that based on technical considerations.''
   However, DOT also said that Energy Department poorly documented
its route selection decisions and lacked proper guidelines.
   The Energy Department said in a news release that ``this lack of
documentation does not indicate non-compliance with regulations or
breach of public safety.''
   The shipments are part of the overall $1 billion cleanup of the
TMI reactor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-DrugNeighborhood     12-08 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Drug Neighborhood,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Returns to Playground Status After Bush Leaves Anti-Drug Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers shooting baskets at a northeast
Houston park remember how dope dealers and gun-wielding thugs took
over their play area.
   ``A year ago, we didn't come here because they might shoot us,''
said Dennis Williams, 12. ``There used to be a lot of trash
everywhere. It was bad.''
   Tyrone Smith, 16, also had stopped coming to the park, once
dubbed ``Crack In The Box.''
   ``Too many shootings,'' he said quietly.
   But on Thursday, the teens were showing off their basketball
prowess at Winzer Park and basking in the glow of what President
Bush said was a good example of the nation's ``thousand points of
light.''
   Bush, who sponsored a girls' softball team at the park in 1960,
praised the community's efforts in ridding the playground of drug
dealers, calling it ``a bright star in our nationwide battle''
against drugs.
   But once the cameras and the national press corps left,
neighborhood youngsters returned for a little roundball.
   ``A year to a year and a half ago, the kids wouldn't even come
out to play basketball,'' said Officer Roy Calderon, who patrolled
Winzer Park Thursday. ``They've really done a good job of cleaning
it up and getting rid of the drug dealers. It's better than it used
to be.''
   Erma Scales, president of the Acres Homes War on Drugs
Committee, told Bush the neighbors banded together to end drug
trafficking in the park, calling on police officers and making mass
strolls through the area.
   ``We have told users and dealers, `No more will you use this
park as a drive-through order for the purchase of illegal
narcotics!''' she said. ``Mr. Bush, this is only a small victory in
the war on drugs, but it is very important to us.''
   Calderon said the neighbors supported police.
   ``That helped a lot. Any time the officers get a pat on the
back, that gives you the initiative to try and help them crack
down,'' he said.
   Although an occasional drug deal may still be made in the park
or within several blocks of it, there is no comparison with the
activities that once took place there, Calderon said.
   ``Back then, every other person out here was selling drugs. Even
I'm surprised at the change,'' Calderon said.
   City Electrical Supervisor Donnie Battenfield said crews
frequently had to replace lights on the playing fields and
throughout the park because gangs would smash them.
   Work crews even required a police escort to the park in
daylight, he said. ``I would still always send two people out here
because it was just too dangerous,'' he said.
   But as Battenfield supervised cleanup crews at dusk Thursday, he
said the situation has changed dramatically.
   And the teen-agers noticed the change, too.
   ``I don't see them very much anymore,'' Smith said of the
dealers. ``Now it's people playing basketball and they mostly come
up here at night.''
   ``Most of them have moved to abandoned houses and other bad
areas now,'' said D'Juan Herbert, 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
