<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Cholesterol     12-08 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cholesterol,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Hears Cholesterol Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman says the government's
cholesterol education program may be encouraging widespread use of
unnecessary and possibly harmful drugs.
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said differing opinions on the
risks of high cholesterol by experts at a House health subcommittee
hearing Thursday ``raises some troubling questions.''
   Thomas J. Moore, a writer whose article in the September issue
of The Atlantic magazine raised concerns over anti-cholesterol
programs, said he questions the value of the National Cholesterol
Education Program.
   But Claude Lenfant, director of the National Heart, Lung and
Blood Institute, which helped develop the cholesterol program,
defended the guidelines and said they offer ``a clear opportunity
to improve the health of Americans.''
   The program's cholesterol guidelines recommend diet as the
treatment of choice. But if that doesn't work, the guidelines say
patients with high levels of cholesterol should seek treatment with
drugs.
   An estimated 60 million Americans are believed to have high
blood cholesterol, a fatty substance essential for life but which
in high concentrations that can clog arteries and contribute to
heart disease and heart attacks.
   Other characteristics associated with heart disease are high
blood pressure, obesity, smoking and lack of exercise.
   ``The central question is do we have effective medical treatment
that justifies putting 60 million people under long-term care of
their doctor,'' Moore said.
   Moore was joined by medical experts who agreed that all adults
should keep an eye on cholesterol and diets that are low-fat and
low-calorie.
   But they also said that although studies show high cholesterol
levels are a heart-disease risk for middle-age men, the evidence is
lacking for men over 65 and for women of all ages who have no
history of heart disease.
   They also maintain diet has been shown to have only a small
effect on cholesterol and that people generally don't stick to
special diets when they are not part of a closely supervised
medical study.
   Frustration with diets would lead many people to
cholesterol-reducing drugs, which they said have side effects that
include liver damage, cataracts and digestive difficulties.
   ``I am troubled by the prospect of subjecting many people to
lifelong dietary restrictions and potentially hazardous drug
treatment for the sake of health benefits that may never
materialize,'' said Dr. Alan M. Garber of the Stanford University
School of Medicine.
   Lenfant contended the evidence shows that women and the elderly
as well as middle-age men benefit from keeping cholesterol levels
down.
   He also noted that the guidelines recommend dietary changes as a
first step and said this can reduce cholesterol significantly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Dinobusters     12-08 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dinobusters,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Use `Dinobusting' Method to Help Dig Up Huge Dinosaur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A method developed to find buried toxic
waste is helping scientists dig up what may be the longest
fossilized dinosaur ever found, a 120-foot seismosaurus who died in
a river 145 million years ago.
   ``Something big in your neighborhood? Who ya gonna call?
Dinobusters!'' is the slogan inscribed on the T-shirt of Oak Ridge
National Laboratory researcher Alan Witten, who developed the
``dinobusting'' technique with about $500,000 from the U.S.
Department of Energy and the Army.
   The $1 million excavation is under way at a secret site
northwest of Albuquerque, N.M., where Witten's technique is used to
locate buried bones by making fuzzy pictures of them with sound
waves.
   ``What Alan is going to do is bring paleontology out of the 19th
century'' by making it faster, easier and cheaper to excavate large
fossils, said J. Wilson Bechtel, who supervises the dig with his
wife, Peggy. They direct the Southwest Paleontology Foundation in
Albuquerque.
   The Tennessee-based Witten discussed the dig and his technique
Thursday during the American Geophysical Union's fall meeting.
   Witten said the Energy Department and the Army's toxic materials
agency paid to develop the method so it could be used to find
buried toxic waste for cleanup, check the integrity of potential
toxic or nuclear waste dumps, and perhaps explore for coal seams.
   The method is similar to medical CT scans, which use X-rays and
detectors to make images of internal organs.
   To make images of buried seismosaurus bones, Witten said he
sends sound waves through the ground using ``an 8-gauge shotgun on
wheels, pointed down. It fires a soft metal slug that hits the
ground and flattens.''
   The sound waves are detected by a set of 29 microphones in a
nearby hole. The sound travels at different rates through rock and
bone. To make an image of one part of the dinosaur, the gun is
moved around and fired repeatedly, producing a two-dimensional
image of a bone's ``sound shadows.''
   The method is similar to that used to make holographs, Witten
said. The sound gun is a commercial kind used to search for oil by
studying the speed of sound waves bouncing off various underground
rocks, not by making an image, he added.
   Several tail vertebrae from the seismosaurus, a relative of
brontosaurus and diplodocus, were discovered by two hikers in 1979.
The exposed bones were excavated in June 1985 by David Gillette,
then paleontology curator at the New Mexico Museum of Natural
History and now Utah's state paleontologist.
   Gillette announced the find in August 1986, coining the name
seismosaurus, or ``earth shaker.''
   The seismosaurus lived in a hot, humid river delta much like
today's Mississippi, and ``probably laid down on a river sandbar
and was covered by sand rather rapidly'' after damming water
upstream, Bechtel said.
   The dinosaur's bones are still in the position where they were
when the animal died.
   Debate continues over whether the seismosaurus or a fossil
dinosaur found near Delta, Colo., is the biggest ever discovered.
Gillette said seismosaurus was at least 120 feet long and probably
longer, and Brigham Young University scientists have said their
dinosaur was at least 100 feet long and possibly 130 feet.
   Until the dinosaurs are excavated, ``it's all speculation,''
said Witten.
   Mrs. Bechtel said it will take at least one more year to
excavate the seismosaurus. So far, the team has removed the base of
the tail, vertebrae, pelvis and several ribs from beneath 8 feet of
sandstone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
