<FIRST>r i PM-Bulgaria     12-08 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Join Rally for Religious Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in the
capital and demanded that the Communist government to recognize
church weddings and reinstate Christmas as a holiday.
   The gathering was Bulgaria's first major rally for religious
freedom in more than four decades.
   Speakers at the Thursday rally called for a change in the 1947
law curtailing religious freedom, complete independence of church
and state and an end to the ``monopoly of the state on spiritual
education.''
   They also called for official recognition of church weddings and
reinstatement of Christmas and Easter as official holidays.
Bulgarians have worked on these holidays since 1944.
   Activists also read aloud the text of three petitions to the
National Assembly demanding religious freedom. About 3,000 signed
the papers.
   The protest was organized by the Society for the Defense of
Religious Freedom and Spiritual Values, an independent group.
   In recent weeks, Bulgarians have begum emulating the
pro-democracy movements sweeping other East bloc countries.
Bulgaria's longtime hard-line Communist Party chief Todor Zhivkov
was ousted on Nov. 10 and replaced by Petar Mladenov, who is
considered more moderate.
   Since then, the government has scrapped a law forbidding
dissent, dismantled a police squad that cracked down on human
rights activists and condemned the 1968 invasion of Czechoslovakia,
in which it took part.
   Despite those changes, the Bulgarian Orthodox Church hierarchy
has so far remained firmly under control of the ruling Communist
Party.
   One reason for the emigration of hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Turks from Bulgaria earlier this year has been official curbs on
exercising Islamic rites.
   Important changes in religious legislation are expected at a
National Assembly session starting Dec. 14.
</TEXT>
