<HEAD>U.S. Company to Build Polish Cable TV System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut company says it will build
Poland's first cable television system, likely enabling viewers in
Warsaw and Cracow to soon begin watching CNN, ESPN and MTV.
   Chase Enterprises of Hartford, Conn., said Thursday that it will
have a 70 percent stake in Polska Telewizja Kablowa, or PTK, a
cable television system it will build and operate along with
Poltelkab SA, a partnership comprising the Polish Postal Service,
Telephone and Telegraph Co., Polish Radio and Television
Productions Co., and the governments of Warsaw and Cracow.
   Poltelkab will have the remaining 30 percent interest.
   Company Chairman David Chase, a Pole who fled the Auschwitz Nazi
concentration camp at age 14 during World War II, said it is the
first communications-related joint venture established under
Poland's December 1988 joint venture law.
   ``We view this as only the first of many projects we will
undertake with Poland and in other economically emerging Eastern
European countries,'' Chase said in a statement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Judge Upholds Rule That Allows Apparel Work at Home</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled in favor of a Labor
Department regulation that allows working at home in five
apparel-related industries.
   U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard Gesell's ruling Thursday
rescinds a ban on home work in the industries making gloves and
mittens, handkerchiefs, buttons and buckles, some types of jewelry
and embroideries.
   Gesell said the Justice Department regulation represents a
``reasoned'' approach requiring firms seeking to institute home
work to come forward and seek certification from the government.
They would be subjected to monitoring by department inspectors.
   The International Ladies Garment Workers' union and two other
unions sued the Secretary of Labor last January, saying tens of
thousands of workers would be exploited by the rule and that the
working standards of other workers would be threatened.
   Gesell said the concerns of labor unions about workers being
exploited by home work ``are no doubt valid.'' A ban on home work
in seven industries was adopted by the Labor Department in the
early 1940s. Home workers in those industries are normally paid by
piece rate rather than hourly wages.
   ``The evidence is strong that the conditions present in the
1940s regarding the exploitation of home workers have not
disappeared,'' said Gesell.
   But the judge said the ``sole issue'' before the court is
whether the Labor Department ``provided a reasoned basis'' for
concluding that a certification system is a better means of
enforcing federal labor law than a total home work ban.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>New Rule Aims To Encourage Auto Defects Reporting</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal highway officials say a new rule
requires that automobile manufacturers include a government hotline
number in vehicle owner's manuals to encourage car buyers to report
defects.
   A spokeswoman for a consumers group that has been pushing for
the rule said Thursday that the action is a move away from the
agency's ``tombstone technology,'' which she said results in action
being taken only after deaths and injuries occur.
   The Auto Safety Hotline, in operation since 1975, receives about
a quarter million calls a year either requesting auto safety
information or reporting problems.
   ``This requirement will make it easier for consumers to contact
us to report a safety problem,'' said National Highway Traffic
Safety Administrator Jerry R. Curry.
   The rule proscribes three paragraphs that will have to be
included in manuals for any vehicle manufactured after next Sept.
1, including information about the safety agency's powers to order
defects investigations and recalls. But it will note that NHTSA
``cannot get involved in individual problems between you, your
dealer or manufacturer.''
   The toll-free hotline is 1-800-424-9393.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Lunch Meat Recalled For Possible Food Poisoning</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says a Sumter,
S.C., processor is voluntarily recalling a single 240-pound
shipment of luncheon meat distributed to nearby stores because some
of the product may be contaminated by food poisoning bacteria.
   Harvin Choice Meats Inc. sold the product _ ``Harvin Sliced
Luncheon Meat,'' packed in 6-ounce vacuum packages _ exclusively to
grocery and convenience stores in a 20-mile radius of Sumter,
officials said Thursday.
   The possible contamination involves Listeria monocytogenes,
bacteria that can cause severe illness, said Lester M. Crawford,
head of the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service.
   Consumers should return the packages where purchased. No other
product of the company is involved in the recall.
   Crawford said no illnesses have been reported as a result of
eating the suspected product. Cartons containing the packages carry
the production code 0318, and each carton and package bears a USDA
inspection seal with ``Est. 6592'' inside the seal.
   Food contaminated with the bacteria can cause listeriosis, a
rare but potentially serious disease, particularly for those with
weakened immune systems _ infants, the elderly and the chronically
ill.
   Consumers with questions about the recall can phone the
toll-free USDA meat and poultry hotline at 1-800-535-4555 from 10
a.m. to 4 p.m. EST, Monday through Friday. Callers in the
Washington, D.C., metropolitan area should call 447-3333.
