<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Violence-Feminism     12-08 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Violence-Feminism,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Montreal Massacre the Act of Atypical Madman, Scholars Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Massacre, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slayings of 14 women by a man who said
feminists spoiled his life should be seen as the deed of an
atypical madman, for most men understand feminism's benefits,
scholars said.
   ``I'd hate to say that the vibrant feminist movement in Canada
is the problem _ because the problem was his, not the movement's,''
said Ronnie Steinberg, a feminist-sociologist and professor at
Temple University in Philadelphia.
   Certainly, many men sometimes find feminism vexing, said Shawn
Johnston, a University of California-Davis forensic psychologist
who treats sex offenders, wife beaters and other violent criminals.
   ``There's no question that masculine insecurity has risen and
has been associated with the rise in feminism,'' Johnston said
Thursday. ``And you've certainly got a lot of crazy or damaged,
angry people out there.
   ``The terrible truth is that there is definitely a history of
violence toward women that really permeates our Western culture.''
   And that history came to a head Wednesday with the killings at
the University of Montreal.
   ``One encounters, even among men I would characterize as the
good guys, a sense of frustration sometimes, a transitory sense of
anger,'' Johnston said. ``But when decent men have some twinge of
frustrtion or anger, maybe because they've been passed up for a
promotion, it tends to be fleeting.
   ``My experience has been that most men are quite comfortable
with and also benefit from female liberation. Only a small
percentage of males is going to suffer from the kind of rage and
unsatisfied power needs, or a need to dominate, that we have in
this situation (in Canada).''
   Marie Wilson, executive director of the Ms. Foundation for
Women, countered that newspapers all too frequently carry stories
about violence against women.
   ``It's all about misogyny and anger, but it doesn't get reported
that way until 14 women get killed all at once,'' she said. ``It's
so much a part of our daily lives as women that even we ignore it;
if you faced it, it would make it hard to get up in the morning.''
   Ms. Steinberg echoed those concerns.
   ``Some of us have been concerned for quite a long time that
we're going to be charged with being male-haters because we've
developed a critical perspective on the treatment of women,'' she
said, citing ``a debate within the scholarship on domestic violence
that, as other forms of control become less effective, men
increasingly are resorting to violence.''
   ``Nobody gives up power without a struggle. You see the struggle
over sharing housework, comparable worth and affirmative action _
in all those struggles there is a tremendous backlash,'' she said.
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women,
observed: ``In any society, when any group tries to move into a
position of equality and is asking to share power, it's never given
willingly.''
   Lives sometimes are lost in such a struggle, she said.
   NOW and the National Coalition Against Domestic Violence are
lobbying to include female victims in a proposed ``Hate Crime
Statistics Act,'' which allows the collection of data about crimes
based on race, religion, sexual orientation or ethnicity.
   Meanwhile, said Ms. Steinberg, ``Within women's circles, we talk
about how to get our ideas across in such a way as to make it less
threatening to people.''
   ``Should feminists have to deal with an increase in masculine
insecurity?'' Johnston said. ``I suppose a trite, but nice, idea
would be for us to care a little more for each other.
   ``If men tried a little harder to struggle with the new roles of
women, it would be good. And perhaps, if feminists who are making
great strides forward took some time to reflect on some of the
anxiety it might cause their male counterparts, that would be good,
too.''
</TEXT>
