<FIRST>r a PM-SexDoctor     12-08 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sex Doctor,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Physician in Sex Case Dead; Suicide Suspected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician who solicited college
students to have sex with his wife in a purported research project
was found dead in his home in what police said was an apparent
suicide.
   Police were called to the home of Dr. Rodney Thorp Wood, 60,
about 1 p.m. Thursday, Southampton Village police Sgt. Lars King
said.
   Wood, dressed in casual clothes, was found in his second-floor
bedroom with a gunshot wound to the head. A 12-gauge double-barrel
shotgun was found near the body, said Southampton Village Detective
Sgt. David Betts.
   Betts said the death appeared to be suicide, although no note
was found.
   Wood and his wife, Nancy Steffen Wood, 44, were arrested in
September in Eugene, Ore., after allegedly offering to pay male
students at the University of Oregon to have sex with her.
   Both pleaded guilty Oct. 23 to prostitution, a misdemeanor, and
each was fined $2,500.
   The socially prominent Woods were listed in the Blue Book of The
Hamptons on Long Island, lived in a mansion and owned a yacht.
   Their lives changed when they were arrested Sept. 16 at a Eugene
hotel.
   Four students testified before a grand jury that they were asked
to have sex with Mrs. Wood. Police said at least one student had
sex with Mrs. Wood and that Wood photographed and tape-recorded the
encounter, for which the student was paid $30.
   Betts said it appeared no one else had been in the house at the
time of the shooting.
   A family spokesman, Ethan Geto, said he had been in contact with
Wood earlier this week. He said Wood ``was very distressed
throughout this whole episode, but I didn't detect that he was any
more distraught than he had been in the past.''
   ``When your name and reputation are dragged through the media
and your character and conduct are called into question and your
life's work is threatened, then clearly this is distressing,'' Geto
said.
</TEXT>
