<FIRST>r a PM-IowaReturn     12-08 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Return,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Captain Says Crew Deserves Recognition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of the USS Iowa, which lost 47
of its sailors in an April gun turret explosion, said his young
crew rebounded remarkably well from the tragedy.
   The battleship returned Thursday to the Norfolk Naval Station
after a six-month deployment that took its 1,500-man crew to the
Baltic, North Sea and Mediterranean. The crew had seven weeks to
prepare for the trip after the explosion that occurred during a
gunnery exercise off the coast of Puerto Rico.
   ``No other crew, in any navy, could overcome a tragedy like the
one April 19 and do what this crew has done,'' Capt. Fred P.
Moosally said.
   While the Iowa was at sea, the Navy released its report on the
explosion.
   It found the blast most likely was caused by a disgruntled
gunner's mate who sabotaged the huge gun and died in the explosion.
   That report is being challenged by many of the families of the
47 victims who believe the Navy is covering up equipment and
training failures aboard the World War II-era battleship.
   Congressional committees will hear testimony next week from Navy
officials and FBI experts.
   Navy investigators found that sabotage was the only explanation
for the explosion, but the FBI has declined to endorse that
conclusion because its tests and investigation failed to duplicate
the Navy's findings.
   Moosally is to testify Monday before the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
   He said the Iowa's record during the deployment and its ability
to respond in emergencies showed the worth of the battleship to the
country's defense.
   The Iowa's homecoming was vastly more cheerful than its return
to Norfolk in April four days after the explosion. This time there
were bands, welcome home signs, gaily colored balloons and cheerful
faces in the crowd of more than 1,000 who huddled in the cold,
blustery wind.
</TEXT>
