<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-Hispanics     12-08 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Hispanics,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Survey Finds Hispanics Heavier Than Other Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new survey finds that Hispanic Americans, on
the average, tend to be heftier than other Americans.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday a study
of Mexican Americans in the West, Cuban Americans in Miami and
Puerto Ricans in metropolitan New York found overweight problems
for Hispanics were ``substantially higher than those reported for
non-Hispanic Americans.''
   Among Mexican Americans, 30 percent of men and 39 percent of
women were overweight. Among Cuban Americans, 29 percent of men and
34 percent of women were overweight. And among the New York Puerto
Ricans, 25 percent of men and 37 percent of women were overweight.
   In another survey, the CDC said overweight men among
non-Hispanics accounted for 24 percent of whites and 25 percent of
blacks. Among women, it was 25 percent of whites and 44 percent of
blacks.
   The CDC said the three surveyed Hispanic groups account for
about three-fourths of the Hispanic population in the United
States. The survey was not a nationwide one, but it is a
scientifically based sample in those three areas, said Michael
Rowland, a researcher with the National Center for Health
Statistics, a branch of the CDC.
   Reasons for the trend are ``pure conjecture,'' said Dr. David F.
Williamson, a CDC researcher. He noted that Hispanic Americans, in
general, have lower income and education status than do white
Americans, ``and people at the lower end of socioeconomics are at
greater risk of being overweight _ this is an especially strong
pattern among women.''
   The term overweight, in the NCHS survey, was used for anyone
whose ``body mass index'' _ a measurement of height and weight _
was in the top 15 percent of men or women in their 20s.
   ``Severely overweight'' indicated the top 5 percent. That
designation applied to between 8 percent to 10 percent of
Hispanic-American men and 8 percent to 16 percent of
Hispanic-American women, compared with generally lower levels for
non-Hispanics.
   The Hispanic survey was conducted as part of the NCHS Hispanic
Health and Nutrition Examination Survey between 1982-84.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
