<FIRST>r p PM-Cuomo-Politics     12-08 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuomo-Politics,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Ready To Run For Re-Election as New York Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo is set to run for a third
term, saying there's nothing else he wants to do at this point in
his life.
   While side-stepping a formal announcement, Cuomo on Thursday
indicated that he had no plans to skip a re-election bid for New
York governor next year to prepare for a 1992 race for the
presidency.
   ``If I had to decide right this moment, I know exactly what I
would do,'' said Cuomo in a telephone interview that provided the
strongest signal to date about his plans. ``The logic is very
simple ...
   ``There's just nothing else I want to do. There's just nothing I
can do that's as important as this ... I don't have any
alternatives.''
   One of the few things that could convince him to change his mind
was failing health, Cuomo said, adding: ``I've never been in better
physical condition.''
   At an earlier news conference in his state Capitol office, Cuomo
had said he was in no hurry to announce his decision on running for
re-election. ``I'm going to use all the time I can. It doesn't make
sense not to,'' he said.
   Cuomo aides have said they expect him to run for re-election and
then, should he win, to consider running for president. He has said
he's yet to give any thought to a 1992 presidential bid.
   State Republican Party Chairman J. Patrick Barrett welcomed
Cuomo's comments. ``I really hope he does (run for re-election),''
said Barrett. ``I would really like us to have a good go at him.''
</TEXT>
