<HEAD>Snow Hits Arkansas, Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arkansas' first winter storm of the season dumped up to 3 inches
of snow, but much of the white powder was expected to melt today
with temperatures rising into the 30s and 40s.
   Snowfall was heavier in the West, where Story, Wyo., received 11
inches of new snow. Sheridan, Wyo., recorded 5 inches Thursday.
   Southern Kansas and Missouri also woke up to a snowy world
today, after a storm left more than a half-foot of powder.
   Over 4 inches of snow fell on Syracuse, N.Y., by 12:30 a.m.
today. The rest of the Northeast enjoyed generally clear skies.
   A winter storm warning was posted today over parts of Virginia,
West Virginia, Tennessee, Kentucky, Maryland, Delaware and North
Carolina.
   Snow advisories were in effect through this afternoon for much
of western and central Kansas, parts of Oklahoma and the Texas
Panhandle into the state's northern plains.
   Snow also was expected in south-central Ohio and in extreme
southern New Jersey.
   A high-pressure front was expected over central Illinois this
morning. Arctic air over the region should trigger another round of
very cold temperatures tonight.
   Showers and thunderstorms threatened to produce heavy rain over
the central Gulf of Mexico coast. Flash flood watches have been
posted over southern Louisiana and southern Mississippi.
   On Thursday, roads were ice-coated across the Texas Panhandle.
An inch of snow fell in Amarillo, Texas.
