<HEAD>Belgian Freighter Aids Burning Soviet Fishing Vessel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with casualties, other details of rescue;
no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freighters rescued 80 crewmen from a blazing
Soviet fishing vessel in the Bay of Biscay today, but survivors
reported that two crew members died, the British Coast Guard said.
   The Soviet factory ship Witauta Sputna was reported still
burning five hours after the emergency was reported by the crew of
the Belgian freighter Flamares, about 90 miles north of Cape
Finisterre in Spain, according to the Coast Guard rescue center at
Falmouth.
   The Coast Guard initially reported that the Flamares had taken
survivors aboard, but later it said that 55 Soviet seamen had been
rescued by the Danish freighter Elena and 25 aboard the Laurits
Tholstrup, registered in Singapore.
   The captain of the Witauta Sputna was among those rescued, and
he indicated that two of his men had died, the Coast Guard said.
