<FIRST>r a PM-AuntBee     12-08 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aunt Bee,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Took on `Aunt Bee' Role In Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINDY ROBERTS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILER CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances Bavier, best known as Aunt Bee
from ``The Andy Griffith Show,'' showed increasing fondness for her
television character in her final years, her attorney said.
   Early in her retirement, Miss Bavier sought to escape
identification with her television past, but in her later years,
she increasingly referred to herself as Aunt Bee and continued to
wear her hair in a bun, said J. Samuel Williams, her attorney and a
close friend for many years.
   Miss Bavier, who had a history of heart problems, died quietly
in her sleep at her stately Siler City home about 7 p.m. Wednesday,
just two days after her release from the local hospital where she
had been treated for almost two weeks in the coronary care unit,
authorities said.
   She would have turned 87 this month.
   Neither the attorney nor the hospital would release the cause of
death in keeping with her wishes.
   She became famous for her role in the popular show starring Andy
Griffith as a North Carolina sheriff. She portrayed the devoted
aunt, who was known for her Southern cooking and who helped raise
the widower Andy Taylor's son, Opie, portrayed by Ron Howard.
   ``She missed having family. She said she had no family because
she dedicated her life to the stage and the screen. And she
regretted that,'' Williams said.
   Dick Linke, manager for Griffith, who played Sheriff Andy Taylor
in the series, said Griffith wanted people to know that Miss Bavier
``was a fine woman, a wonderful actress and most of all, a
brilliant character actress.''
   Griffith did not plan to attend Miss Bavier's funeral, Linke
said.
   A native of New York City, Miss Bavier attended Columbia
University, was a graduate of the American Academy of the Arts and
had more than 20 years of stage experience.
   She did stints in vaudeville and on Broadway, where she appeared
in such productions as ``Kiss and Tell,'' ``Point of No Return''
and ``The Lady Says No.''
   But she became famous for her role of Aunt Bee, which she
continued in the series ``Mayberry RFD.'' She won an Emmy for the
role in 1967.
   When she settled in Siler City in 1972, her presence was more
felt than seen, said Al Resch, editor of the local newspaper The
Chatham News.
   He described her as a recluse brought on by her illness and her
love of privacy.
   The rare occasions Miss Bavier ventured out, it was usually in
the evening to buy groceries, Resch said.
   Williams would not comment on her will or the size of her estate
except to say she did not die penniless and that she made
arrangements for her 15 cats to be taken care of after her death.
   A private graveside memorial service will held at 2 p.m. Sunday
at Oakwood Cemetery in Siler City, Williams said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
