<FIRST>r w PM-Conflict-Lincoln     12-08 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Conflict-Lincoln,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Counsel Denies Conflict in Lincoln Ethics Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Keating-Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee's special counsel
investigating the five senators involved in the Lincoln Savings &amp;
Loan controversy has ties to developers with large loans from an
investment conglomerate linked to the thrift, The Washington Times
reported today.
   Robert S. Bennett denied in two telephone interviews conducted
by The Times on Wednesday that his firm's legal representation of a
Washington, D.C., developer in obtaining $65 million in 30-year
loans from a subsidiary of Dallas-based Southmark Corp. represented
a conflict of interest.
   Bennett last month excused himself as special counsel in another
Senate ethics case involving Sen. Alphonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and the
scandal at the Department of Housing and Urban Development. Bennett
said his law firm had clients in a federal housing matter and that
he wanted to avoid even the appearance of a conflict.
   Bennett denied any possible conflict in the investigation of the
five senators who intervened on behalf of Charles H. Keating Jr.
with federal banking regulators in April 1987 when his Lincoln
Savings and Loan of Irvine, Calif., was collapsing, The Times said.
   Government records show that when Lincoln went bankrupt earlier
this year, it held about $350 million in junk bonds issued by
Southmark and other entities. Southmark also had about $120 million
in loans for ``working capital'' and other investment purposes from
Lincoln, the records show.
   Bennett's firm represented Square 37 Partners, a real estate
venture headed by developer Joseph W. Kaempfer Jr., in the group's
successful effort to get $65 million in Southmark financing in 1984
to buy a luxury hotel and an office building in the nation's
capital, according to U.S. District Court records. The newspaper
also said District of Columbia records show that Bennett and
members of his law firm remain partners with Kaempfer in another
office building venture.
   ``I have done a thorough check and have been told there is no
conflict,'' Bennett told The Times.
   The five senators involved in the Lincoln controversy are Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz.; and Democrats Alan Cranston of California,
the majority whip; Banking Committee Chairman Donald W. Riegle Jr.
of Michigan; Governmental Affairs Committee Chairman John Glenn of
Ohio and Dennis DeConcini of Arizona.
</TEXT>
