<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosMurders     12-08 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Murders,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Refused To Answer Questions Regarding Alleged Slush Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In videotaped testimony, former Philippine
President Ferdinand Marcos refused in 1986 and 1987 to answer
questions on the alleged use of a slush fund to pay for the murders
of two anti-Marcos activists.
   The late ruler invoked the Fifth Amendment privilege against
self-discrimination in a video deposition shown Thursday in a
wrongful-death lawsuit filed by the families of Silme Domingo and
Gene Viernes. The two were shot June 1981 in the Seattle offices of
the Alaska Cannery Workers Union.
   The U.S. District Court lawsuit claims the murder plot
originated in Manila because the victims, who were officers of the
union, were involved in anti-Marcos activism.
   Three men were convicted of the murders on the theory that the
victims had crossed the killers by working to eliminate gang
influence on work assignments and gambling in Alaska fish canneries.
   But the suit claims an intelligence slush fund, administered by
the Mabuhay Corp., paid $15,000 for the murders. The company was
run by Dr. Leonilo Malabed of San Francisco.
   Marcos, who died last September, had acknowledged Malabed was a
friend, but invoked his privilege against self-incrimination when
asked for specifics of intelligence funding and the Mabuhay company.
   Among the key documents in the trial is one that plaintiffs
claim is a Mabuhay account sheet for the slush fund. Under a
heading for ``security projects'' is a May 17 entry for $15,000.
   The plaintiffs claim former cannery-union president Constantine
Baruso, whose gun was used in the killings, was in San Francisco on
that date to pick up the money. Baruso, who was never criminally
charged in the murders, also invoked the Fifth Amendment 75 times
during his testimony earlier in the lawsuit trial.
   Marcos gave depositions during two sessions after he fled to
Hawaii following the February 1986 overthrow of his government.
   Marcos, his widow, Imelda, the Philippines government and others
are defendants in the suit, which seeks $30 million in damages.
   Marcos also would not answer whether the Philippines National
Bank was used to channel money to the United States for
intelligence operations in the late 1970s and 1980s, and whether
funds were provided ``to conduct acts of physical violence against
the anti-Marcos opposition ... including and up to the use of
murder, political assassination and summary execution.''
   Viernes had visited the Philippines shortly before his death and
met with anti-Marcos trade unionists. Marcos was not asked
specifically whether he knew of Viernes but said he was concerned
about leftist influence on Philippine trade unions.
   ``We were aware of the efforts of the leftists or the communists
to influence labor and use some of the unions as their fronts,'' he
said.
   But he denied labor organizers were arrested or ``disappeared''
for their activities.
   ``There were no political detainees in my opinion,'' he said.
``We never jailed anybody just because of their political
opinions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
