<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-Leonard-Duran     12-08 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Leonard-Duran,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leonard Wins Unanimous Decision Over Duran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No more ``no mas.''
   In a battle of two old adversaries, Sugar Ray Leonard bored the
crowd but won the judges Thursday night to score a lopsided
decision over Roberto Duran and retain his super middleweight
boxing title.
   Nine years after he forced Roberto Duran to quit in the eighth
round in what is known as the ``No Mas'' fight in New Orleans, the
33-year-old Leonard was at it again, mugging and dancing and
jabbing circles around a fighter who suddenly looked very much his
38 years of age.
   ``It was deja vu,'' Leonard said. ``It had been nine years since
we've been together and it was deja vu.''
   Leonard was so dominant that one judge didn't give Duran a
round. Another gave him only the 12th round.
   Leonard picked up at least $15 million and Duran $7.6 million
for the fight, which was televised on pay-per-view and to closed
circuit locations across the country.
