<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China     12-08 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentence Given To Two For June 4 Murder Of Policeman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beijing court today sentenced two men to death
and another to life in prison for the murder of a policeman during
the June military crackdown on Beijing.
   The official Beijing Evening News said the court's verdict
reflected the government's bid to ``severely attack the
counterrevolutionary element's criminal activities and safeguard
the state's safety.''
   The government, meanwhile, expressed its ``utmost indignation''
over U.S. measures to allow Chinese students fearing persecution at
home to extend their stays in the United States.
   Sentenced to die were Meng Duo, an unemployed worker, and Zhou
Jiguo, a restaurant employee. Chen Yong, a worker from the
northeast city of Tangshan, received a life sentence.
   They were charged with the murder of Li Guorui, a 20-year-old
member of the People's Armed Police, in an attack at 5 a.m. On June
4, at about the same time the military was moving into Tiananmen
Square after a bloody all-night thrust through the streets of the
capital.
   The court said Meng attacked Li with the handle of a shovel
while Zhou kicked and beat the young policeman and clubbed him with
a stick. Chen whipped the stricken Li with a belt.
   Li was then thrown off the Fuchengmen bridge located southeast
of the square, according to earlier reports.
   Li was one of several soldiers and policemen killed during the
June 3-4 fighting who was hailed by Chinese leaders and the
official press as a national martyr who laid down his life to put
down what the government called a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion''
   Dozens of wreaths of white, yellow, pink and blue paper
chrysanthemums were hung from the bridge and a photo of Li was
draped in black ribbons. Offerings of fruit and drinks were laid
before it.
   The government claims that 300 people were killed when the
military stormed Beijing to end the student-led pro-democracy
demonstrations, and most of them were soldiers.
   Unofficial Chinese and foreign estimates of the number of deaths
range up into the thousands, with almost all the casualties being
unarmed citizens killed by soldiers firing into crowds.
   At least seven other participants in the Beijing demonstrations,
all workers, were previously put to death for rioting. At least 11
others in Shanghai and Chengdu have also been executed for rioting
during the political turmoil of June.
   Those receiving the death sentence have the right to appeal, but
appeals are almost always rejected and executions, by a bullet to
the back of the head, normally take place within a few days of
sentencing.
   The protest against the U.S. decision to allow students to
remain in the United States was delivered by Vice Foreign Minister
Liu Huaqiu to U.S. Embassy Charge D'Affaires Lynn Pascoe.
   It was the third official protest China has made to the United
States in the past three weeks.
   Liu said allegations that Chinese studying abroad might be
persecuted upon their return home was ``utterly groundless.''
   He said he hoped the United States would cease all actions that
``undermine bilateral educational exchanges and bilateral
relations.''
   President Bush on Nov. 30 announced a veto of a congressional
bill that would permit Chinese students to change their visa status
and remain in the United States if they feared persecution at home.
   Bush, however, said he was taking administrative steps that
would guarantee Chinese students the same rights of abode as
prescribed by Congress.
</TEXT>
