<HEAD>Shiites Battle Through Beirut Alleyways</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE death toll to 10; picks up 3rd
pvs: One of...</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MOHAMMED SALAM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sniper fire killed four children as rival
Shiite Moslem militias battled for dominance in densely populated
residential districts in west Beirut, police said today.
   The four children were among 10 people killed and 20 wounded in
the clashes that began Thursday and raged through the night, a
police spokesman said.
   One of the dead children, 7-year-old Hassan Hamdan, was shot in
the head by a sniper as he switched on his bedroom light in the
district of Mossaitbeh, a stronghold for the mainstream Shiite Amal
militia.
   All of the children were shot in their homes, said the
spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Snipers hugging the rooftops opened fire on major intersections
on both sides of a 1-mile confrontation line that separated
Syrian-backed Amal fighters from combatants of the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The thuds of exploding rocket-propelled grenades accompanied by
the crackle of machine gun fire echoed across Beirut early in today
as the two warring factions battled for control of five slum
districts in west Beirut.
   Stray bullets shattered glass and scarred the walls and
balconies of residential buildings as civilians huddled in
basements and bomb shelters.
   Amal and Hezbollah fighters battled in the rain all night
despite three cease-fire accords called by a security committee
comprising representatives of the principal militias in Lebanon.
   Schools closed throughout west Beirut, reflecting fear that the
clash might spread to other districts, especially the
Shiite-populated slums on the city's southern edge.
   The command of a Syrian army contingent in charge of security in
west Beirut sent patrols of helmeted troops around the
confrontation region to prevent the clashes from spreading.
   ``They are firing at random. They direct their rifles at the
other side, empty a clip and take cover again,'' said Ahmed Itani,
a resident of Mossaitbeh. ``God knows what the bullets hit ...''
   The clash broke out around noon Thursday in the Khandaq
al-Ghamiq district. Both Amal and Hezbollah blamed each other for
provoking the confrontation.
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, issued a statement
urging both groups to ``put an immediate end to this destructive
fighting and to have mercy on the innocent civilians.''
   A police spokesman said tension was high in other Shiite
populated districts in Beirut and the city's southern slums.
   ``Both sides are massing fighters in their respective areas of
influence,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations.
   The Shiite confrontation broke out two days after Hezbollah
smashed Amal in the western sector of the Syrian-policed Bekaa
valley, destroying its five major centers in the area.
   By police count, 17 people were killed in that confrontation, 16
Amal fighters and one Hezbollahi. Forty-two others were wounded.
   The two groups have been fighting intermitently since May 1987
for dominance of the 1.2 million Shiites, the largest community in
among Lebanon's four million people.
   By police count, 552 people have been killed and 1,532 wounded
in the previous Amal-Hezbollah battles.
   The violence is in addition to the 14-year-old civil war between
Moslem militias and Christian forces.
</TEXT>
