<FIRST>r a PM-SoupKitchens     12-08 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soup Kitchens,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Privately Run Soup Kitchens and Food Pantries on Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soup kitchens and food pantries in New York City
have multiplied 20 times in eight years, and their clients say
sky-high rents and a shortage of unskilled jobs are reasons why, a
published report said.
   ``A lot of people have jobs, but the rent man takes it all,''
said Raymond Frazier, 39, over a plate of pork and beans at the
Community Food Resource Center on West 116th Street.
   According to a Food and Hunger Hotline survey on emergency food
programs in the city, the number of soup kitchens and food pantries
has jumped from about 30 in 1981 to about 600, New York Newsday
said in today's editions.
   Hotline Director Christina Walker said the government is not
addressing hunger adequately, and that the existence of privately
run food programs may be helping the government get away with it.
   ``We're like enablers, allowing the government to continue its
horrible, destructive behavior,'' said Walker.
   People in line for handouts attribute the problem to high rents,
a shortage of unskilled jobs and red tape in getting food stamps
and other government assistance, Newsday said.
   The hotline, a non-profit group that tells callers where they
can find food, said the majority of people seeking food are not
homeless but rather the elderly, the disabled, the unemployed, the
working poor, women on welfare and their children.
</TEXT>
