<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0480 12-08 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Leaders Accuse De Klerk of Cover-up in Death Squad
Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with anti-apartheid church leaders
accusing de Klerk of trying to cover up inquiry; picks up 8th pvs: Three
former... Minor editing to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid church leaders
today criticized President F.W. de Klerk for rejecting an
independent inquiry into allegations of police death squads.
   The president's decision ``is a further license for the police
to carry on killing,'' said the South African Council of Churches.
``The de Klerk government has denied the people justice.''
   De Klerk on Thursday night brushed aside opposition demands for
an independent inquiry into charges that police took part in death
squads that killed opponents of the white-led government.
   He said such a special investigation would take too long and
that country's regular legal system would do the job just as well.
   ``A judicial inquiry can take months, if not years, to reach its
final conclusions,'' de Klerk said. ``In the meanwhile, a climate
of suspicion and distrust could develop, something the country can
ill afford at this stage in its history.''
   Several police officers, some active and some retired, will be
investigated and five have requested suspension from duty until
investigations or legal proceedings are completed, de Klerk and
Adriaan Vlok, the law and order minister, said in statements
released early today.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said two former security
policemen whose allegations prompted the inquiry would be
prosecuted. One of them awaits execution for an unrelated murder,
and the other has fled the country.
   ``The government has full confidence that the tried and
respected prosecution mechanisms of the state will be sufficient to
bring the accused before the court, impartially and objectively,''
de Klerk in response to opposition demands that the investigation
be conducted outside the law enforcement establishment.
   South Africa's national police have been criticized for failing
to solve dozens of killings of anti-government activists since
1978. Anti-apartheid leaders say many people believe security
personnel help plan, participate in, or cover up such actions.
   The council said de Klerk's claim that a judicial inquiry would
be too lengthy was ``cynical and spurious.''
   ``How long did the victims of the death squads have to wait
before the South African government was forced by present
revelations to even make a pronouncement on the matter?'' the
statement asked.
   Three former security policemen have said in recent newspaper
interviews or sworn affidavits that they participated in death
squad operations on orders of superiors, many of whom still occupy
high positions in the police.
   The former policemen, two black and one white, said they were
involved in bombings, arson, kidnapping, robbery and murder in
South Africa and neighboring countries.
   One, Almond Nofomela, is awaiting execution. The others have
fled, but one is reported held by authorities in Botswana.
   Vlok's statement about what would be investigated mentioned only
Nofomela's allegations. He said ``a team of senior detectives''
would work with the attorneys general of Natal and Transvaal
provinces.
  
</TEXT>
