<HEAD>Solzhenitsyn's Citizenship Could be Restored, Says Official</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Subs last graf to CORRECT that Rostropovich a musician, sted
author.</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Alexander Solzhenitsyn and other exiled
Soviets could have their citizenship restored if they request it, a
Soviet lawmaker said in an interview with the government newspaper
Izvestia.
   Alexei Yeliseyev, chairman of the Supreme Soviet's Commission on
Citizenship, said in the interview published Thursday that it was
not necessary for exiles to return to the Soviet Union in order to
get their citizenship restored.
   ``We are ready to solve positively some of the cases right away
if we have personal applications of those deprived of their
citizenship,'' he said.
   Asked if Solzhenitsyn could be among those granted restoration
of citizenship if he requested it, Yeliseyev said, ``yes.''
   Solzhenitsyn, who was stripped of his citizenship and expelled
from the country in 1974, has not requested that his citizenship be
restored.
   The author, who now lives in the U.S. state of Vermont, wrote
extensively about the bloody terror of Stalin's rule from 1924 to
1953. His best known works include ``Gulag Archipelago,'' ``One Day
in the Life of Ivan Denisovich'' and ``Cancer Ward.''
   Yeliseyev said there had been some suggestions that Solzhenitsyn
and other exiled Soviets have their citizenship restored by decree.
``It would be unfair to restore their citizenship without asking if
they want it or not,'' he said.
   In saying that many exiles could have their citizenship
restored, Yeliseyev said, ``we have to adapt to civilized
standards.''
   Several deputies in the Supreme Soviet have asked that
Solzhenitsyn's citizenship be restored, but no official action has
been taken.
   Earlier this year, the Soviet Writers' Union restored the
membership of Solzhenitsyn and Mstislav Rostropovich, a musician.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
