<FIRST>r i PM-'89MassKillings 1stLd-Writethru a0412 12-08 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-'89 Mass Killings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>1989: A Year of Mass Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to CORRECT spelling of Sonoma. SUBS last item
to UPDATE with name of gunman.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Canada-Massacre, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of mass killings in 1989:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 17 _ Patrick Purdy, a troubled 24-year-old drifter, attacks
a Stockton, Calif., schoolyard firing an AK-47 semi-automatic
assault rifle and other weapons. Five children are killed and 29
others and one teacher are wounded. Purdy then turned a pistol on
himself.
   APRIL 14 _ Seven people die during a murderous rampage in Sonoma
County, Calif. Ramon Salcido, a former winery worker, is accused of
killing his wife, his two daughters, his mother-in-law, her two
daughters and a co-worker, and attempting to kill three other
people. Salcido was captured in Mexico five days after the slayings
and allegedly confessed to Mexican authorities. He pleaded innocent
to charges in California and will be tried in January.
   JULY 12 _ In a two-hour killing spree, a French farmer drives
around the village of Verne, France, shooting at everyone he sees.
Christian Dornier, described as strange and brooding by fellow
villagers, kills 14 people, including his mother and sister, and
injures 10. Dornier was wounded in a shootout that ended the spree.
   SEPT. 14 _ A disgruntled ex-employee armed with semi-automatic
weapons stalks workers in a printing plant in Louisville, Ky.,
killing eight and wounding 12. The gunman, Joseph T. Wesbecker, a
47-year-old pressman who was placed on permanent disability leave
from the company in 1988 because of mental illness, killed himself.
   DEC. 6 _ Fourteen women are killed and 13 other people wounded
when a man who said feminists ``spoiled my life'' storms into the
University of Montreal engineering school and opens fire with a
semi-automatic assault rifle. The gunman, Marc Lepine, then
committed suicide.
</TEXT>
