<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Party, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Central Committee to Hold Plenum Saturday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with government comments on plenum,
move up reference to Lithuania. Pickup 6th graf, `Harry Tiido...' Adds
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's Central Committee will hold
an extraordinary meeting Saturday to set the agenda for the Soviet
Union's parliament next week, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
today.
   Journalists said the committee will discuss economic problems
and possibly the growing challenges to party authority, including a
vote in Lithuania that revoked the Communists' constitutionally
guaranteed monopoly on power.
   Although the policy-making body recently began announcing dates
of its meetings in advance, the official media carried no word of a
Saturday session.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev said it was
traditional for the Central Committee to meet before the convening
of the Soviet Congress of People's Deputies ``to discuss matters
pertaining to the Congress.''
   The 2,250-member Soviet parliament opens the second session in
its history Tuesday. The Central Committee also met before the
inaugural session of the Congress in May to consider its agenda.
   A plenum of the Central Committee is used to consider specific
questions or to make personal changes. The body is empowered to
remove members of the ruling Politburo, but there was no indication
that was in the works.
   Harry Tiido, a commentator on official Estonian radio, said the
Baltic republic's party leader, Vaino Vyalas, told Estonian
television Thursday ``he was going to Moscow, and that questions of
the economy would be discussed.''
   Tiido, speaking by telephone from the Estonian capital, Tallinn,
said some Communists there believed the Central Committee would
also consider the Lithuanian Supreme Soviet legislature's vote
Thursday to revoke the Communist Party's constitutionally
guaranteed monopoly on power.
   By its vote, Lithuania became the first of the 15 constituent
Soviet republics to replace the traditional legal guarantee of
Communist supremacy with a system of multiple parties.
</TEXT>
