<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths Sub a0494 12-08 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, Sub, a0494,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS grammar in lead of final obit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Karl Bauman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl R. Bauman, a longtime newsman with The
Associated Press, who President Johnson once said was ``as much a
part of the White House as the press room itself,'' died Thursday
from cancer complications at age 87.
   Bauman was a 38-year AP employee. He worked for 32 years in the
news service's Washington bureau, covering major federal trials and
the U.S. Supreme Court before moving onto the White House, where he
covered the Kennedy administration and Johnson's 1964 campaign.
   Johnson sent Bauman a letter on his retirement, noting his
three-decade career in the nation's capital.
   Bauman's departure from the press corps was marked with ``the
biggest retirement party of anyone in Washington I ever knew in the
news business,'' recalled Frank Cormier, a former AP White House
correspondent who joined Bauman at the White House in 1962.
   Bauman's wife, Frances, died in 1984.
</TEXT>
