<HEAD>Developments in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATE East Germany to add latest developments.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, PM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the latest developments in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY _ Prosecutors today announced the filing of
criminal charges against former party leader Erich Honecker, former
Premier Willi Stoph, and three other ousted leaders accused of
corruption and abuse of power.
   The Communist Party agreed Thursday to rewrite the constitution
and hold free elections in May as it prepared for a crucial party
congress tonight expected to alter the party's structure.
   In a detailed program, the party called for ``an alternative
democratic socialism'' and admitted its role in the current
political crisis.
   It also recognized the role of the church.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA _ New Premier Marian Calfa met with opposition
leaders today to discuss forming a coalition government. The
opposition threatened to hold a general strike Monday if
non-Communists are not given a bigger share of power. Dissident
Vaclac Havel said he would serve as president if asked.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION _ The Communist Party Central Committee scheduled
an extraordinary session Saturday, at which it will likely set the
agenda for a party congress next week. A journalist said the
committee also may discuss the growing challenge to the party's
authority.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BULGARIA _ Thousands of people rallied in the capital, Sofia, on
Thursday to demand the Communist government reinstate Christmas as
a holiday and recognize church weddings. It was the first major
demonstration for religious rights in Bulgaria in more than four
decades.
