<FIRST>u w PM-Unemployment 3rdLd-Writethru a0533 12-08 0958</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unemployment, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0533,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jobless Rate Edges Up to 5.4 Percent in November</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead; inserts 5 grafs after 3rd graf, The civilian,
with market and analysts reax; picks up at pvs 4th graf, The highest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unemployment rate edged up from 5.3
percent to 5.4 percent in November even though the economy added
210,000 new jobs and manufacturing employment fell for the eighth
consecutive month, the government said today.
   The Labor Department report showed job growth last month was far
greater than most analysts expected. But the government also
revised downward sharply the number of new nonfarm jobs created in
October, from 233,000 to 93,000.
   The civilian unemployment rate climbed 0.1 percentage point as
more than 6.7 million Americans were looking for jobs but unable to
find them. That data comes from the department's household survey,
which also showed that 117.7 million people held jobs in the
civilian economy.
   The stock market reacted favorably to the report, taking the
evidence of sluggish growth as a sign the Federal Reserve Board
would move to further relax its credit policy and thus lower
interest rates.
   Analysts, however, were split on whether or when such a
reduction would come, and at odds as well over whether the economy
was on the verge of recession.
   ``I don't think these numbers suggest further easing,'' said
Washington economist Michael Evans. ``The economy is moving along
in second gear. It's not very weak and it's not very strong.''
   But Allen Sinai, chief economist for Boston Co. Economic
Advisers, said the manufacturing sector was clearly in a recession
and appeared to be having a spillover effect on certain services
industries that could bring a full recession.
   ``I think this is it,'' Sinai said. ``This economy is at or near
some sort of recession.'' He predicted the Fed would reduce
interest rates but said it was unclear whether the central bank
would move immediately or wait until its year-end meeting in 10
days.
   The manufacturing slump has contributed to the overall slowdown
in the economy as the year draws to a close, and today's report
provided further evidence that the sector's lackluster performance
continues.
   The average manufacturing work week fell from 40.8 to 40.7 hours
and overtime was unchanged at an average of 3.7 hours a week.
   The department said the dramatic revision of October's job
growth number resulted from overestimating new hiring in state and
local educational institutions, which is difficult to measure as
the school year begins.
   With that revision taken into account, the government said the
average month-to-month gain in jobs during the second half of 1989
has been about 160,000, well below the average monthly gain of
270,000 posted in the past 2{ years.
   Virtually all of the growth in the past year has been in the
service sector, and November was no exception.
   Wholesale and retail trade posted job gains of 18,000 and
33,000, respectively, last month and business and health services
also reported significant payroll expansions.
   But the outlook in the goods-producing sector, particularly
manufacturing, was not as good.
   Mining and construction reported modest employment gains last
month, adding 7,000 and 17,000 positions, respectively.
   Exacerbating the decline in manufacturing was another bad month
for automobile manufacturing, which reported a decline of 15,000
jobs in November after losing 10,000 from September to October.
   That decline caused overall employment in the durable-goods
sector of manufacturing to slip by 24,000 jobs last month.
   The Labor Department said manufacturing employment has declined
by 165,000 since March, with auto and electrical equipment
accounting for 100,000 of the lost jobs.
   Analysts had predicted the report would show about 150,000 new
jobs last month, and the larger figure would appear to indicate
that the economy is strong enough that the Federal Reserve need not
reduce interest rates further.
   The sharp October job revision, however, and the continued slump
in manufacturing could give the Fed policymakers enough evidence
that the slowdown has reached a dangerous point and that lower
interest rates might help spark more robust growth.
   The central bank's chief concern about easing interest rates
centers on inflation, and today's report contained somewhat
encouraging news on that front.
   Average hourly earnings were unchanged in November, and average
weekly earnings declined by 0.4 percent. Over the year, hourly
earnings have increased by 3.6 percent and average weekly earnings
by 3.0 percent. Both of those gains lag well behind consumer
inflation, which has been in the annual range of 4.5 percent.
   The 5.4 percent civilian jobless rate was the highest since it
was 5.4 percent in January. For the past six months the rate had
been either 5.3 percent or 5.2 percent.
   The rate increased despite the moderately strong addition of
210,000 nonfarm jobs because the labor force _ those with jobs or
actively seeking them _ expanded by 410,000 people last month after
growing by just 65,000 from September to October.
   The unemployment rates among major demographic groups changed
little for the most part in November, although joblessness for all
teen-agers shot up from 14.9 percent to 15.5 percent.
   The rates among other groups were:
   _Adult white men, 4.0 percent, up from 3.8 percent in October.
   _Adult white women, 4.0 percent, unchanged.
   _White teen-agers, 11.2 percent, up from 10.4 percent.
   _All blacks, 12.1 percent, up from 11.8 percent.
   _Adult black men, 10.7 percent, up from 10.3 percent.
   _Adult black women, 10.4 percent, up from 10 percent.
   _Black teen-agers, 32.6 percent, down from 36.1 percent.
   _Hispanics, 7.8 percent, down from 7.9 percent.
   In a separate calculation of unemployment that counts members of
the armed forces stationed in the United States, the Labor
Department said the November unemployment rate was 5.3 percent, up
from 5.2 percent in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
