<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NAACPPlans     12-08 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP Plans,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Plans Push in Racially Torn County</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Clyburn in 6th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONWAY, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP is planning to march and to mount
political, economic and educational efforts in a racially torn
South Carolina county, the national chairman of the group said.
   ``We're going to put all the NAACP's resources in this,'' said
Dr. William F. Gibson, a Greenville dentist who chairs the
organization's board of directors.
   Racial tension has been rising in Horry County, which includes
the resort city of Myrtle Beach, since last summer, when a black
high school football quarterback was replaced with a less
experienced white player.
   Black players have boycotted the team since Aug. 22, and the
Horry County school board has fired the Rev. H.H. Singleton, a
Conway Middle School teacher who led the boycott. Singleton also is
president of the local chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
   The state Human Affairs Commission has said there is evidence
that blacks are discriminated against in the Horry (pronounced
Or-ee) County school system.
   Human Affairs Commissioner Jim Clyburn said that during the last
10 years, Horry County schools have awarded 22 promotions, none of
them to blacks.
   The commission has filed a legal brief on behalf of Conway High
School band director Leslie McIver, who was passed over for a white
applicant for the job of district arts coordinator.
   The commission said McIver was more qualified than the white
person who got the job.
   The events prompted the NAACP to meet this week. Among the plans
the group settled on was to lead a protest march before the end of
the year, Gibson said. He added that he will meet with the Rev.
Jesse Jackson this week to discuss the march.
   Gibson also is planning a concentrated voter-registration drive
in the black community.
   The NAACP is planning to create an Economic Enhancement
Committee, which will encourage the hiring and promoting of blacks
and contracts for black-owned businesses.
   And the group is planning ``Freedom Schools,'' where black
students will be tutored after school in their regular academic
subjects as well as black history and the meaning of the Civil
Rights movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     12-08 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mediator Optimistic About Next Round of UMW-Pittston Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mediator is optimistic negotiations next
week between Pittston Co. and the United Mine Workers will lead to
a settlement of the 8-month-old strike, his spokesman said.
   But striking coal miners said they were preparing for a
Christmas without jobs and opened an indoor rally site Thursday,
Camp Solidarity II, to demonstrate their resolve.
   Negotiators for the union and company are planning to resume
mediated contract talks Monday at a motel conference room in
Arlington, said Herbert Fishgold, an associate of mediator William
Usery, former labor secretary under President Ford.
   Usery ``is optimistic that this set of talks will be the one
that leads to a settlement of this dispute,'' Fishgold said
Thursday.
   The union and company representatives held eight straight days
of negotiations, with sessions lasting from 10 to 17 hours, before
recessing Nov. 20, Usery said. They met again last Thursday and
Friday before taking a break this week.
   Usery and the negotiators needed the break to evaluate the
proposals that came forth and the complex issues involved, Fishgold
said. ``It was a time for everyone to step back and digest what
happened.''
   Citing a news blackout each party agreed to, Fishgold, Pittston
spokeswoman Susan Copeland and UMW spokesman John Duray refused
Thursday to say anything substantive about the bargaining or the
issues.
   Fishgold characterized the talks as ``amicable, forthright and
meaningful. Mr. Usery is satisfied with the way the talks have
gone, the cooperation and the obvious interest on part of both
parties to resolve this dispute.''
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole appointed Usery on Oct. 25 as a
``super mediator'' to help solve the dispute. He runs a labor
relations firm in Washington and was national director of the
Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service from 1973 to 1976.
   The strike began April 5 and directly involved Pittston's 1,695
union employees in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky and
indirectly involved hundreds of laid-off miners.
   ``We're not going to get our hopes up and then get a big
letdown,'' said Buzz Hicks, a UMW local president from Cleveland,
Va., who was coordinating activity at Camp Solidarity, a campground
in rural Russell County. ``Personally, I don't look for anything
over the holidays.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
