<FIRST>r a PM-AgentsKiller     12-08 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agents Killer,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life Term for Man Convicted of Drug Agent Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese man convicted in the
slayings of two federal drug agents posing as heroin buyers has
been sentenced to life in prison without possibility of parole.
   Prosecutors had urged Judge Gilbert Alston to impose the death
penalty on 20-year-old Wei Wen Wang, but Alston instead chose the
life term recommended by a Los Angeles County Superior Court jury.
He handed down the sentence Thursday.
   The government had dropped a federal indictment against Wang
because there was no federal death penalty at the time of the
crimes. The case was instead pursued in a state court because
California allows capital punishment.
   Wang was convicted of the first-degree murders of U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration agents Paul Seema, 52, and George
Montoya, 34, the attempted murder of agent Jose Martinez, 25, and
robbery.
   The jury also had found special circumstances of multiple murder
and murder during a robbery, which made the death penalty a
sentencing option.
   The Feb. 5, 1988, shootings occurred during an investigation of
heroin dealers in the San Gabriel Valley. Evidence at the trial
indicated that the agents were killed as part of a scheme to rob
them of $80,000 they had agreed to pay for two pounds of heroin.
   Two other alleged participants in the robbery and murders died
in an ensuing shootout. Wang, a native of Taiwan who lived in
Hacienda Heights, was shot in the cheek, shoulder, chest, pelvis,
forearm and thigh, but survived.
   Su Re ``Michael'' Chia, who was in on the plot but not at the
shootout, was convicted in February on two counts of first-degree
murder, attempted murder, robbery and conspiracy. He was given 62
years to life in prison.
   Former President Reagan signed a law last November allowing
federal judges to impose the death penalty for drug dealers
convicted of murder, but it did not apply to crimes committed
before it was enacted.
</TEXT>
