<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Benin     12-08 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Benin,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Benin Renounces Communism in Face of Strikes, Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTONOU, Benin (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership of this West African
country, facing popular discontent and massive debt, has denounced
communism and promised to undertake constitutional reforms next
year.
   The ruling People's Revolutionary Party said Thursday it will
abandon the Marxist-Leninist ideology that has guided it for 14
years, ever since President Mathieu Kerekou declared a one-party
Marxist state.
   The announcement follows weeks of protests by civil servants and
teachers, who haven't been paid since October, and street
demonstrations by students demanding more democracy.
   The reforms will focus on a greater division of power, including
the creation of the post of prime minister. A new Constitution will
give greater powers to the 196-member National Assembly, guarantee
human rights, liberalize the economy and encourage private
enterprise.
   One of the first measures will be to abandon the formal
salutation ``comrade.''
   It was not clear whether the illegal Front for the Liberation
and Rehabilitation of Dahomey, which tried to unseat Kerekou in a
1977 coup, would be legalized or whether other opposition parties
would be permitted.
   The nation of 4.2 million people is one of the poorest in
Africa, with a per capita annual income of $310 and foreign debt of
$920 million.
   The principal sources of foreign exchange are cotton, cocoa and
oilseed.
   Benin achieved independence from France in 1960 as the
Independent Republic of Dahomey. A military regime headed by
Kekerou took power in 1972 and renamed the country the People's
Republic of Benin in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
