<SECOND>AM-BRF--Opera-Americans,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Opera Singers Booed at La Scala</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American opera singers Chris Merritt and
Cheryl Studer drew boos and generally negative reviews after their
performance in the opening of La Scala's season.
   Merritt, a tenor from Oklahoma City, and Studer, a soprano from
Midland, Mich., performed the main roles of Arrigo and Duchess
Elena in Giuseppe Verdi's ``I Vespri Siciliani,'' an opera set in
Sicily.
   Although they received some applause during the first part of
the opera Thursday night, they were showered with derisive whistles
and boos in the final act. The disapproval was so strong that
security guards were called to appease the crowd during one of
Merritt's solos.
   Milan newspapers reported Friday that many felt the Americans
where too ``cold'' and too ``un-Mediterranean, and unconvinced of
their role.'' The daily Il Giornale criticized Studer for a lack of
``fire and vigor,'' and said Merritt was ``unsuited for the role.''
   Verdi's work was conducted by the Italian maestro Riccardo Muti,
who was cheered by the audience throughout the five acts.
   The audience at the gala opening of the La Scala season is
notoriously hard to please.
</TEXT>
