<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Border     12-08 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Border,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Border Crossing Opens, Sign Of Political Upheaval</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KITTSEE, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Czechoslovak-Austrian border
crossing opened Friday in another sign of the fast-moving political
changes in Czechoslovakia.
   Austria suspended its visa requirement for Czechoslovak citizens
as of Dec. 4, provisionally until Dec. 17.
   Until Wednesday, the road toward Czechoslovakia ended at the
village of Kittsee, and Czechoslovak construction teams had to
remove earth and debris for the Jarovce station on the Slovak side
to become operational.
   Barbed-wire fencing, rolls of wire and other barriers were
removed over a distance of about 1,650 feet on either side of the
road.
   A high barbed wire fence remained elsewhere, but all other
border fortifications were being dismantled, and more is likely to
come down soon.
   The new border crossing is designed to help manage the growing
influx of Czechoslovak tourists in Austria.
   The Czechoslovak state news agency CTK reported Friday that in
the first four days since Austria decided to suspend visas for
Czechoslovak citizens more than 40,000 crossed the border at the
Petrzalka-Berg checkpoint near Bratislava.
   The Jarovce-Kittsee border crossing is only about three miles
away.
   Tens of thousands also have crossed into Austria at other
checkpoints.
</TEXT>
