<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Space,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmonauts Begin Reactivating Space Laboratory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmonauts repositioned a module at their Mir
space station as they prepared to reactivate the laboratory and
resupply vessel, Tass said Friday.
   The 40-ton Kvant 2 space module is fitted out as a laboratory
and is equipped with a ``space motorcycle'' that allows the
cosmonauts to work more comfortably and safely in open space. It
also carries a shower and a sink.
   ``Once reactivated, the Kvant 2 resupply module will
considerably improve the working conditions and life of the
cosmonauts and expand possibilities for research and experiments on
board Mir,'' the official news agency said.
   The module was separated from the space station and redocked at
an airlock in maneuvers performed by engineers at the Mission
Control Center and aboard the space station by cosmonauts Alexander
S. Viktorenko and Alexander A. Serebrov, Tass said.
   Problems with a guidance system had prevented the module from
docking on Dec. 2, but the maneuver was successfully completed
Wednesday.
