<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Soviet     12-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Soviet,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea, Soviet Establish Consular Relationship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and South Korea
established a consular relationship Friday in a first step toward
formal diplomatic ties.
   Foreign Minister Choi Ho-joong said the consular ties, although
limited, would help the two former adversaries to strengthen
relations in economic and other fields.
   After a series of consulations in Moscow and Singapore, the two
countries agreed to establish ``consular departments'' in their
semi-official trade offices opened this year, a ministry statement
said.
   The ``consular departments'' will operate as part of the trade
offices but will be staffed by officials from the two coutnries'
foreign ministries, the statement said.
   Vice Foreign Minister Hong Soon-young said Seoul had to agree on
the new form of consular ties because of Moscow's close alliance
with North Korea, which is South Korea's bitter adversary.
   ``Most of all, the announcement reflects a rapid change in
progress in economic and other fields between the two countries
and, in the long run, it shows that the chances of formal ties are
not remote,'' Hong said.
   He said Seoul's improved relations with the Soviet Union would
positively affect South Korea's efforts to establish formal
relations with China and other socialist countries.
   Valeriy Nazarov, chief of the Soviet Trade Office in Seoul,
welcomed the decision, saying, ``It is a result of growing ties
between the two countries in the fields of trade, sports and
culture.''
   He said, however, that the two countries would not establish
formal ties in the near future.'
   Nazarov said the Soviet Union has to honor its friendly
relations with North Korea. The Soviet Union backed North Korea
during the 1950-53 Korean War and continues to supply arms to the
Pyongyang government.
   Since World War II, Seoul has regarded the Soviet Union as an
enemy country.
   There have been many recent non-political contacts between the
two countries. The Soviet Union attended the 1988 Seoul Olympics,
and the two swapped trade offices this year.
   South Korea also has improved relations with other socialist
countries: Hungary and Poland formally recognized South Korea this
year; Yugoslavia is expected to do so later this month; and
Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria have exchanged trade offices with Seoul.
   Trade between South Korea and the Soviet Union reached $432
million in the first 10 months of this year, up 156 percent from
the corresponding period last year.
   Korean exports to the Soviet Union quardrupled from $25 million
to $101 million during the 10-month period. Korea's imports from
the Soviet Union in the same period rose from $144 million to $331
million.
   South Korea's major exports include textiles, electronic
appliances, steel and ships. It imports coal, timber, fish and
agricultural products from the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
