<HEAD>Snow Falling From Kansas to Washington; 10 Dead in Traffic Accidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with at least 10 fatalities sted eight; today's
developments, federal office and school closings. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snowstorms today stretched from Kansas to the nation's capital,
closing schools and paralyzing rush hour traffic, while ski resort
workers in West Virginia danced in anticipation of busy slopes.
   Heavy snow in Arkansas, Missouri and Oklahoma made roads
treacherous, and police said at least 10 people were killed in
accidents Thursday and today.
   A winter storm warning was posted today for parts of Virginia,
West Virginia, Tennessee, Kentucky, Maryland, Delaware and North
Carolina.
   Schools were closed in parts of Indiana, West Virginia and in
Washington, D.C., where snow was falling heavily and up to 8 inches
was forecast. The federal government dismissed its workers early
under a staggered-release plan in order to avoid traffic tieups.
   In West Virginia, Snowshoe Ski Area in Pocahontas got 5 inches,
Beckley, 3 inches, and Charleston, 2 inches, this morning, and up
to a foot was expected in some places by evening, the National
Weather Service said.
   ``I have my snow boots on, and I've been doing snow dances on
the counter,'' said Lisa Thompson, a clerk at a ski shop at the
WinterPlace ski resort near Beckley.
   North Carolina's first major winter storm pelted the northern
mountains early today with snow and dumped sleet and cold rain on
the rest of the state.
   In northwestern Arkansas alone, seven people were killed. The
latest victim was a pregnant woman who was killed about 7 a.m.
today on Interstate 540 at Fort Smith.
   Two 16-year-olds and a 10-year-old died in one wreck Thursday on
U.S. 71 just south of Fayetteville, state police said. The accident
occurred when the car in which they were passengers went off the
road after skidding and colliding with two trucks.
   The 16-year-old driver of the car was being treated for injuries
at a Fayetteville hospital, police said.
   Three other people died in three separate accidents in Arkansas.
   About 4 inches of snow was on the ground by early today in some
sections of the state. Warmer weather today was expected to melt
much of the snow.
   In Missouri, police said slick roads caused dozens of traffic
accidents, including one in which a couple was killed when their
car slid out of control on Missouri Route 43 in Barton County and
slammed head-on into another car.
   An 18-year-old man died when his car slid off a road and struck
a tree five miles north of Branson.
   Up to 6 inches of snow had fallen in the state by today.
   ``Troopers were just going from one accident to another,'' said
Glenn Jarvis, an inspector with the highway patrol. ``The roads are
snow-covered from here to Oklahoma.''
   Several trucks jackknifed trying to make it up a steep grade on
Interstate 44 outside Springfield, Mo., backing up traffic for one
mile.
   In southern Kansas, more than 6 inches of snow fell, while Enid,
Okla., reported 3 inches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
