<FIRST>r i AM-China-Vice     12-08 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Vice,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 10,000 Punished in Anti-Vice Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have ``punished'' nearly 11,000
people in Beijing since October in an anti-vice campaign against
the ``six evils,'' a newspaper reported Friday.
   The Legal Daily quoted the a municipal group as saying 10,964
people had been punished and it had seized 50,000 pornographic
books, 1,630 videotapes, 1,203 gambling implements and the
equivalent of $73,000 in gambling money.
   The campaign is part of the conservative leadership's drive
against Western tendencies, and has targeted the ``six evils'' _
prostitution, gambling, drugs, pornography, superstition and the
selling of women and children.
   The report did not say how many of those ``punished'' were
arrested, but noted that 40 percent were under the age of 25
``which means the health of the youth is being seriously corroded.''
   It said prostitution, gambling and pornography were the three
most common vices in Beijing and that some managers, factory
directors and leaders ``are shielding, conniving at and sometimes
even organizing'' illegal activities.
   It cited one case of a company director caught having sexual
relations with a woman manager while watching pornographic
videotapes.
   Prostitution involving foreigners has become widespread and more
open, it said, reporting the case of one woman who carried a
``beeper'' so her customers could contact her more quickly.
   On Thursday, the Communist Party said any members involved in
prostitution would be expelled from the party.
   The Legal Daily also said gambling and the kidnapping and
selling of women and children are rampant in China's most populous
province of Sichuan.
   It said 359 people were detained for gambling in one two-day
campaign in the Sichuan city of Xichang. The campaign also netted
16 traders in women and children and rescued 10 infants.
   The provincial capital of Chengdu caught 30 prostitutes and 27
of their customers in a 15-day period in November, it said.
</TEXT>
