<HEAD>China Lodges Protest Over Student Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China filed a third protest Friday expressing its
``utmost indignation'' over Washington's actions to allow Chinese
students fearing persecution at home to extend their stays in the
United States.
   The protest, delivered by Vice Foreign Minister Liu Huaqiu to
U.S. Embassy Charge D'Affaires Lynn Pascoe, was the third given to
the United States in the past three weeks.
   ``The U.S. action undermines the educational exchanges between
the two countries and Sino-U.S. relations as a whole, and I am
ordered to express our utmost indignation and lodge a strong
protest with the U.S. government,'' the official Xinhua News Agency
quoted Liu as saying.
   Allegations that Chinese students might be persecuted upon their
return home was ``utterly groundless,'' Liu said.
   President Bush on Nov. 30 announced a pocket veto of a
congressional bill that would permit Chinese students to change
their visa status and remain in the United States if they feared
persecution at home.
   Bush, however, said he was taking administrative steps that
would guarantee Chinese students the same rights of abode as
prescribed by Congress.
   Also on Friday, the State Education Commission said Bush's
actions violated a 1987 bilateral agreement requiring Chinese
students to return home for at least two years following the
completion of their studies in the United States.
   ``Due to U.S. violation of the Sino-U.S. agreement on
educational exchanges and its obstruction of normal student
exchanges, the State Education Commission of the People's Republic
of China has to make necessary responses, and the U.S. will be held
responsible for all the consequences arising therefrom.''
   The statement did not say whether ``necessary responses'' might
include a halt in sending students to the United States. Nearly
half of the estimated 80,000 Chinese studying abroad are in the
United States.
   On Nov. 19, China protested the congressional legislation,
eventually shelved, that would have toughened economic sanctions
imposed by the White House after the military crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators in June.
   The next week, Pascoe was called into the Foreign Ministry to
receive a protest over the passage in Congress of the bill on
student visas.
   Relations between the two countries are at their lowest point
since the normalization of diplomatic ties in 1979. Both sides have
expressed hopes that problems can be overcome, while at the same
time insisting that the other side act first in remedying the
conflict.
   China has accused the United States of meddling in its internal
affairs by imposing sanctions and coming to the defense of Chinese
who advocate democratic reforms.
   Thousands of Chinese students in the United States and other
countries joined pro-democracy demonstrations and protested
Beijing's violent suppression of dissent.
   Australia said Friday it will allow Chinese nationals in the
country illegally, including students who have finished their
studies, to stay until at least Jan. 31, 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
