<FIRST>u i PM-Canada-Ships 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 12-08 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Ships, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews of Two Ships Caught on Fierce Seas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with authorities now saying no survivors
or bodies found. CORRECTS spelling of ship name to Capitiane. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers found no sign today
of 39 crew members from two large container ships that disappeared
after sending out distress signals while battling a fierce storm in
the Gulf of St. Lawrence.
   A coast guard vessel, battling two-story seas and high winds,
picked up two empty life rafts and the wreckage of a third near the
area where the ships ran into trouble. It did not see either ship
or any survivors.
   ``There is wreckage,'' said Lieut. Jeff Agnew, a search and
rescue spokesman. ``Hopefully, we'll find a lifeboat yet.''
   Roy Jones, chief engineer of the Sir Wildred Grenfell coast
guard ship, said earlier that at least two bodies were seen
floating in the gulf, but Agnew said that was based on an
inaccurate report from a search plane.
   The 280-foot Johanna B, carrying a crew of 16, disappeared off
radar screens on Thursday night.
   The 23-member crew of the Capitiane Torres abandoned ship and
took to an enclosed rubber life raft before their 375-foot ship
capsized or sank.
   Winds blowing up to 80 mph hampered rescue efforts. Earlier,
Capt. Patrick Phelan of the Halifax search and rescue center had
said rescuers spotted survivors inside the raft. But that turned
out to be inaccurate, too.
   ``We're talking like 30-foot seas, heavy winds, freezing spray,
possibility of some snow,'' a rescue spokesman said. ``Visibility
is about a quarter of a mile.''
   Rescuers had lost radio contact with the Johanna B, a
Panamanian-registered vessel carrying a cargo of steel ingots. The
ship declared a mayday after reporting that it was taking in water
Thursday night about 120 miles northeast of Summerside, Prince
Edward Island, Phelan said.
   Officials were unsure where the ship was headed when it ran into
trouble.
   The 375-foot Capitiane Torres sent out the rescue call after the
ship's cargo shifted and some containers slid overboard, causing it
to list badly. It had been en route to Taiwan with general
container cargo.
   The vessel either capsized or sank, said a Coast Guard spokesman
monitoring the rescue effort in Sydney, Nova Scotia.
   The nationalities of the crews were not known.
   The Sir Wilfred Grenfell was manned by striking crewmen who
returned to work for the rescue effort. The crewmen had been on
strike a month.
</TEXT>
