<FIRST>u a PM-LiverTransplant 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 12-08 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liver Transplant, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0548,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Begin Nation's Second Liver Transplant From Living Donor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Jones' surgery proceeding
smoothly, tentative schedule for total procedure; Picks up 13th graf, `She
is staying....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgery to remove part of a liver from a man who
is donating it to his 15-month-old daughter was ``going very
smoothly'' today in the nation's second such transplant, a doctor
said.
   The operation on 20-year-old Robert Jones began at about 7.30
a.m. at the University of Chicago Medical Center and the transplant
for his daughter, Sarina, was expected to begin late in the
afternoon, said Dr. Peter Whitington, the hospital's pediatric
liver specialist.
   A team led by Dr. Christoph Broelsch performed the first such
procedure in the United States on Nov. 27 for a 21-month-old girl
from Texas who continued ``doing well'' at the hospital today,
Whitington said.
   Before the operation 11 days ago, the transplant had been done
only three times _ in Brazil, Australia and Japan, according to the
university. One child died.
   Today's procedure involving Jones, a dry-wall installer and
contractor from Millington, Tenn., near Memphis, and his daughter
was expected to last as late as midnight, Whitington said.
   No problems had arisen in the morning surgery, he said. Broelsch
was proceeding cautiously and ``taking his time.''
   ``It's going very smoothly at the moment,'' Whitington said.
   Sarina was flown to Chicago a week ago, but the surgery was
postponed because she was recovering from an infection.
   She suffers from biliary atresia, a usually fatal congenital
disorder that blocks liver bile ducts and causes a backup of bile
in the bloodstream and liver. It is the leading cause for liver
transplants involving children.
   Sarina is at a more advanced state of the disease than Alyssa
Smith, the Texas girl who last month received a transplant from her
mother, Teresa, 29.
   Mrs. Smith, a schoolteacher from Schertz, Texas, near San
Antonio, left the hospital Thursday with ``a big smile on her
face,'' hospital spokeswoman Mary Fetsch said.
   She is staying at the Ronald McDonald House, used by families
who have children in the hospital. Sarina's mother, Michelle, also
is staying at the house.
   The Medical Center hopes to perform 20 living-donor liver
transplants in the next 12 months, partly in an effort to offset
the shortage of donor organs.
   One-quarter to one-half of the youngsters who need liver
transplants are expected to die without them, because too few
organs are available from cadavers.
   Broelsch pioneered the technique of transplanting part of adult
livers into youngsters, whose abdominal cavities are too small to
accommodate whole adult organs. Partial livers grow in size as the
child grows, and the living donors regenerate the liver tissue they
have lost, doctors say.
</TEXT>
