<SECOND>PM-Drug Summit,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Still Hopes to Attend Drug Summit in Colombia, But Trip Being
Re-Studied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush still hopes to attend a drug summit
in Colombia in February, but top aides are re-evaluating the trip
plans because of continuing violence there, federal drug policy
director William Bennett said today.
   ``You have to be concerned with everybody's safety in Colombia
these days. It's really very, very rough,'' Bennett told reporters
aboard Air Force One. He was traveling with the president, who is
wrapping up a two-day, three-state trip to participate in anti-drug
rallies and to help raise funds for Republican candidates.
   Bennett said ``I haven't seen any hesitation'' on Bush's part in
terms of going to Cartagena for the summit.
   ``But you don't want to be foolhardy. You don't want to be
reckless,'' Bennett said.
   He said he was sending his chief of staff, John Walters, to
Colombia early next week to evaluate the situation. Asked why the
president wants to go to the violence-torn country, Bennett said
it's because Colombian Virgilio Barco ``wants him to come.''
   ``Barco is brave and courageous. George Bush is brave and
courageous. George Bush just admires the hell out of Barco. ...I
know that if Barco says it's important for the president to be
there, the president's going to do it unless it doesn't make
sense,'' Bennett said.
   The drug policy official added, however, ``one of the things you
have to consider is not just the security of the president but the
security of a whole lot of people who go where the president goes.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the summit still is
tentatively planned for Colombia in February. ``At the moment, we
think security could be provided and there are still tentative
plans to go,'' he said.
   But, Fitzwater added, ``we keep analyzing the situation.''
   Colombia has been wracked with drug-related violence, including
a truck bomb explosion this week that killed 52 people.
</TEXT>
