<FIRST>r a AM-BlackPanthers     12-08 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Panthers,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Black Panthers Start New Oakland Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther Party leaders who
were reunited at the funeral of slain party co-founder Huey P.
Newton have formed a community group to help people affected by the
Oct. 17 earthquake.
   The program announced Thursday by Bobby Seale, David Hilliard
and one-time fugitive lawyer Stephen Bingham is similar to the
Black Panthers 1960s program that sought improvements in housing,
jobs, education and health care.
   The former revolutionaries and community organizers charged the
Federal Emergency Management Agency and the American Red Cross with
doing more to assist white, upper-income neighborhoods than to help
blacks living in West Oakland, where the Cypress section of
Interstate 880 collapsed in the quake.
   They said they will work to overcome ``environmental racism,''
which they defined as a system of subjecting blacks and poor people
to health dangers and shabby living conditions near freeways and
industries.
   Seale said he plans to return from Philadelphia to his native
Oakland.
   Hilliard, a longshoreman who lives in Oakland, said residents of
West Oakland ``see the Red Cross as a double cross. They have
turned a deaf ear to the cries of the people of West Oakland.''
   Both the Red Cross and FEMA have denied similar allegations
repeatedly.
   The new group, which held a news conference to announce its
formation, said it would join several other community organizations
in calling for free medical treatment for Cypress area residents.
   They will also call for rerouting the Cypress section of I-880
away from the neighborhood, and for immediate FEMA relief and
low-cost housing for city residents left homeless by the quake.
</TEXT>
