<FIRST>r a AM-CrossBurning     12-08 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cross Burning,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Testify in Alleged Cross Burning Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three inmates testified that they saw county
sheriff's deputies burn a cross in a jail that housed black street
gang members.
   Daryl Ransom, Raye Simmons and Mark Harris also told a Los
Angeles County Civil Service Commission hearing Thursday that
officials failed to respond to complaints of the cross burning for
a year.
   Former deputies Brian Kazmierski and Richard Bolks are appealing
their discharges for allegedly setting fire to a makeshift cross in
a prison control booth at the Men's Central Jail sometime between
Dec. 26, 1987, and Jan. 11, 1988.
   Ransom testified that he saw Kazmierski wrap toilet paper or
tape around a cross possibly composed of mop handles, sprayed
disinfectant on the object and set it afire.
   Ransom, a murder convict who described himself as a former
member of the Crips gang, said he helped circulate a petition
signed by more than 400 gang members that reported the cross
burning. Nothing was done about the complaint for a year, he said.
   Simmons, a Crips member, said that on another occasion deputies
played loud heavy metal music over the intercom for several hours
before he saw Bolks place a small cross against a window. He
testified that Kazmierski sprayed the cross, which he thought might
have been made of toilet paper, and set it afire.
   Harris, also a Crips member, also mentioned that heavy metal
music was played before the cross burning, adding that someone
yelled racial slurs over the intercom.
   Attorney Richard Shinee, representing the two deputies, said a
cross was never burned and that the incident had been exaggerated
by gang members ``to get the deputies in trouble.''
   Sheriff Sherman Block revealed in June following an internal
investigation that there had been two cross burning incidents at
the jail.
