<FIRST>r w AM-US-Tibet     12-08 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Tibet,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Doctor, Lawyer Report Torture by Chinese in Tibet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. doctor and lawyer say they have
notarized statements from Tibetans tesifying that they were
tortured in Chinese prisons in 1987 and 1988.
   ``The most common pattern is repeated interrogation sessions
accompanied by severe beatings and electric shock. ...,'' the
Americans wrote.
   ``Torture techniques include hanging prisoners by their wrists,
thumbs or ankles for prolonged periods, submerging prisoners in
tubs of cold water or dousing them with water,'' they said.
   The Americans' story, ``The Suppression of a People: Accounts of
Torture and Imprisonment in Tibet,'' was published earlier this
month. The authors are Dr. Blake Kerr, a resident at New York's St.
Vincent Hospital, and John Ackerly, a lawyer in Washington for the
International Campaign for Tibet.
   The authors note that the ``China Daily'' of Feb. 24 this year
carried a statement from Chinese delegates to the U.N. Commission
on Human Rights, calling allegations of torture absurd and
fabricated.
   They were in Tibet for 10 weeks in the summer and fall of 1987
and say they saw three demonstrations against Chinese rule,
witnessing the death of three demonstrators on Oct. 1. As many as
19 Tibetans were reported shortly afterwards to have been killed in
that riot.
   They also went to northern India where thousands of Tibetan
refugees live under the authority of their spiritual leader, the
Dalai Lama.
   In India they interviewed 17 Tibetans. Eight of the 17,
including five Buddhist monks, said they had been arrested, beaten
and tortured. notarized.
   One interview quoted Yoden Choedak, a 29-year-old nurse, as
saying:
   ``I cried as my clothes were being ripped off, with the help of
Chinese women police. Then I was beaten all over my body with the
electric stick, many times on my breasts, mouth and head. ...
   ``Ever since, I have had difficulty remembering things and
learning new words. I think this is from the electric sticks.''
</TEXT>
