<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     12-08 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Agree to Exchange Agricultural Teams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union agreed
Friday to exchange agricultural experts in the next two years.
   The agreement calls for the exchange of teams in the field of
forestry, agricultural economics, agricultural science and food
processing, according to U.S. Undersecretary of Agriculture Richard
T. Crowder.
   The protocol renews and expands an agreement signed in 1973 on
cooperation between the United States and the Soviet Union in the
field of agriculture.
   Crowder, who is also negotiating a renewal of the U.S.-Soviet
long-term grain agreement, said the Malta summit between President
Bush and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev had helped in finalizing
the agriculture agreement.
   ``The good will and spirit of cooperation established in this
historic meeting has inspired our negotiations to even greater
cooperation in the field of agriculture,'' he said.
   He said the breakthroughs at Malta underscored U.S. support for
Gorbachev's attempts to revitalize the economy of the Soviet Union,
which is suffering from widespread shortages of food, fuel and
consumer goods.
   ``President Bush has targeted the June 1990 summit for
completion of a bilateral trade agreement between the United States
and the U.S.S.R., which is a prerequisite to granting Most Favored
Nation status to the Soviet Union,'' Crowder said.
</TEXT>
