<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-08 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Killed in Shiite Militia Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four children slain by snipers were among
10 people killed in a second day of Shiite Moslem militia battles,
including a 7-year-old shot when he switched on the light in his
bedroom, police said Friday.
   They said all the children were under age 8, and most of the
other casualties, including 20 people wounded, were civilians hit
by snipers or stray bullets in their homes.
   Hassan Hamdan, 7, was shot in the head when the light in his
bedroom shone through the rain and revealed him to a sniper in
Mossaitbeh, a low-income residential district of Moslem west Beirut
controlled by the mainstream Shiite militia Amal.
   Militiamen of Amal, which Syria supports, and the pro-Iranian
fundamentalist Hezbollah began fighting at midday Thursday. They
have battled sporadically since May 1987, in west Beirut and south
Lebanon, for supremacy among the 1.2 Shiites, Lebanon's largest
sect.
   Syrian soldiers took up positions along a deserted boulevard on
the mile-long confrontation line Friday. A police spokesman, whose
name was withheld in keeping with regulations, said the fighting
abated, ``but the militiamen remain in their positions.''
   Soon after the Syrians moved into the Bourj Abu-Haidar district,
civilians emerged from bomb shelters to inspect their damaged
apartments and gutted cars. They scurried to safety again at the
sound of sniper fire.
   Cables dangled from power poles and smoke billowed from the
wreckage of cars hit by rocket propelled grenades.
   Militiamen battled in the rain all night and most of Friday,
ignoring repeated cease-fire appeals from a security committee that
includes representatives of Lebanon's main militias.
   Schools closed for the day in west Beirut and the predominantly
Shiite southern slums, reflecting fear the confrontation would
spread to all Moslem neighborhoods.
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, urged both groups to
``put an immediate end to this destructive fighting and have mercy
on the innocent civilians.''
   Fighting began in west Beirut two days after Hezbollah crushed
Amal's forces in the western sector of the Syrian-occupied Bekaa
Valley, destroying its five major bases.
   By police count, 17 people were killed in that confrontation _
16 Amal fighters and one from Hezbollah _ and 42 were wounded.
   Police say 552 people were killed and 1,532 wounded in previous
Amal-Hezbollah battles dating to May 1987.
</TEXT>
