<HEAD>Vietnam Crime Crackdown Nets More Than 8,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam authorities have arrested more
than 8,600 people in the first four days of a major crackdown on
crime, Hanoi Radio has reported.
   The crackdown, which began Sunday, was carried out in 44
provinces and cities, and was directed against ``all kinds of
criminals,'' the radio reported Thursday. A text of the report was
seen in Bangkok Friday.
   ``Within four days more than 8,600 criminals of all kinds have
been arrested throughout the country, including 521 who had been
the objects of police searches, 558 slated for reeducation centers,
and 1,028 condemned to forced labor,'' the radio said.
   ``Nearly 200 criminal gangs have been busted and more than 500
dangerous elements detained,'' it said.
   In Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, authorities ``launched
fierce attacks on hideouts of criminals, clearing out many meeting
places of criminal elements and arresting 1,830 susppects,'' the
radio said.
   ``They have also broken up 62 gangs of professional killers and
robbers, detaining 229 of their members,'' it said.
