<FIRST>r a PM-Medfly 1stLd-Writethru a0476 12-08 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medfly, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medfly Infestation in California Termed Serious</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf, `Rather than...' to add Arizona
taking measures. Picks up 7th graf, `The panel....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The infestation of Mediterranean fruit
flies in Los Angeles and Orange counties is serious and could
threaten California's agricultural economy, according to a science
panel.
   ``In summary, the panel agrees unanimously that this Medfly
problem is large, very serious and will probably increase,'' said
Roy Cunningham, a U.S. Department of Agriculture research services
official from Hilo, Hawaii.
   The panel Thursday proposed expanding the aerial spraying of the
pesticide malathion and said the need for spraying would likely
continue through April and possibly longer.
   Isi Siddiqui, assistant director of the California Department of
Food and Agriculture, endorsed the panel's recommendation and said
he expected it to be approved by the department today.
   The Medfly, which can infest more than 250 kinds of fruit and
vegetables, has been under attack in Los Angeles County since
summer. Siddiqui said spread of the Medfly could cost the farm
economy $200 million a year indefinitely.
   Rather than shrink, the infestation has spread to part of Orange
County and now encompasses some 250 square miles. The infestation
is presently confined to urban areas but could threaten
California's agricultural economy if it spread to farm country.
   Arizona authorities began stopping cars at the state line on
Thursday to prevent any fruit not certified as Medfly-free from
entering, said state entomologist Ivan Shields.
   Trucks and commercial vehicles already were subject to
inspection on entering Arizona but car inspections had been halted
in July to save about $250,000 a year. The state also has set fly
traps.
   The panel announced its recommendation at a news conference that
also drew spraying opponents who contend malathion is poisoning
people.
   The accepted method of attacking an infestation has been to
deliver a dose of malathion to the targeted area and then follow up
with the release of millions of sterile Medflies each week through
two generations of the insect's life cycle.
   However, the entire infested area would require 300 million to
400 million flies, and a government laboratory in Hawaii can only
reliably produce 100 million flies, Siddiqui said.
   The panel recommended that malathion be sprayed in each area at
least once every three weeks during the winter's coldest periods
when it takes flies longer to reach sexual maturity.
   As weather warms into spring, malathion should be applied every
two weeks and then as frequently as every seven to 10 days. Weather
conditions such as rain immediately after an application would
require re-spraying.
   During the news conference, several protesters from a fledgling
anti-malathion movement challenged the panel.
   ``Who gave the Department of Agriculture the right to poison
people?'' said one woman.
   Siddiqui responded that the department has studied the health of
people in previous spray areas and has found no ill effects from
the tiny dose of malathion spread over each acre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
