<FIRST>r a PM-SeaLevel 1stLd-Writethru a0507 12-08 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sea Level, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Pack Up Your Beach Chairs Yet _ Sea Level Rise Will Be Modest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Meier and...' with one graf to add that study
assumed doubling of carbon dioxide in atmosphere by 2050.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal flooding should be less severe than
expected during the next century because sea level will rise only
about 14 inches instead of 39 inches if Earth's atmosphere gets
warmer, scientists say.
   ``We have destruction along our coasts now even with modestly
rising sea level. There are going to be more and more problems, but
they won't be as bad as we thought a few years ago,'' said
glaciologist Mark Meier, director of the Institute of Arctic and
Alpine Research at the University of Colorado, Boulder.
   The revised and still-uncertain estimate of sea-level changes
was issued Thursday during the American Geophysical Union's fall
meeting by scientists who conducted nine studies on how
pollution-caused global warming will affect the oceans, glaciers
and ice sheets.
   Glaciologist Charles Bentley of the University of Wisconsin at
Madison, said his study found the sea level won't rise as much as
expected largely because the the south polar ice sheet will get
bigger, instead of melting as commonly believed.
   That is because a warmer atmosphere carries more moisture and
will dump more snow on Antarctica. The polar ice cap contains about
70 percent of Earth's water.
   A 1985 National Academy of Sciences report concluded global
warming would cause about a 39-inch rise in sea level by about the
year 2050 _ enough to allow storm surges to devastate low-lying
areas along the U.S. Gulf Coast, Florida, Bangladesh and the
Maldives, Meier said.
   But the studies led to a new consensus that the sea-level rise
will total about 14 inches, although a great deal of uncertainty
remains. That means the sea level could do anything from dropping 2
inches to rising as much as 30 inches.
   Meier and others emphasized their new forecast, which assumes a
doubling of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere by 2050, may not hold
true past that year and that rising sea levels could become more
severe after that.
   Every 12-inch rise in sea level means low-lying shorelines
retreat inland by 100 feet, Meier said.
   Modest sea level increases also may destroy wetlands and let
saltwater ruin fresh water aquifers and kill plants and animals in
coastal estuaries.
</TEXT>
