<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalArt     12-08 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Art,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoppers To Paint Murals For Soviet, African And Other Foreign Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Christmas shoppers at a mall will
get a chance next week to paint murals sending a message of love to
hospital patients in the Soviet Union and elsewhere around the
world.
   Artist John Feight, who has designed thousands of murals for
hospitals over the last 15 years, said Friday that he expects 4,000
people _ 1 percent of the shoppers expected at the Lenox Square
mall next week _ to stop and color in a section of the 116 murals
he has designed for the project.
   Sixteen of the murals _ identical pictures of the word ``love''
in Russian and English joined by a heart _ will end up in hospitals
in the Soviet Union, the 49-year-old founder of The Foundation For
Hospital Art said.
   The rest _ various pictures of butterflies, flowers and jungle
scenes _ are destined for display in hospitals in Bangladesh,
Italy, Portugal, Austria, Zaire, Liberia and Kenya, as well as
Georgia Baptist Hospital in Atlanta, Lake Charles Memorial Hospital
in Louisiana and Feight's place of birth, Joel Pomerene Memorial
Hospital in Millersburg, Ohio.
   At the mall next week, Feight and volunteers will ask passersby
to take a few minutes to help fill in the colors on the 4-by-6 foot
loose canvas murals.
   Sometimes it's not easy to get non-artists to take brush to
hand, he said.
   ``They're so innocent,'' he said. ``I go up to someone and say,
`Will you hold this please.' It's a cup of paint. And then I say,
`Now that you have this in your hand, why don't you paint this
space?' And they protest, `I can't paint. I can't draw a straight
line. I haven't taken any lessons.'
   ``But once they get into the idea that we're helping people in
hospitals, they get into it. They don't care. It's more than art.
It's love.''
   The canvasses featuring ``love'' in English and Russian were
inspired by Feight's visit in April 1988 to the Moscow Research
Institute of Eye Microsurgery. The patients there and staffers from
the U.S. Embassy helped Feight paint 37 murals on the walls of the
hospital.
   ``I did one mural that had the word `love' in Russian,'' Feight
recalled. He said that prompted the hospital's director, Dr.
Svyatoslav N. Fyodorov, to remark: ``That's what we need more of
around here, love.''
   That comment led to his latest project, Feight said.
   He said he plans to take the 16 murals to Moscow personally in
early April. From there, Fyodorov will distribute the murals to
various hospitals in the Soviet Union.
   While in Moscow, Feight said, he will direct the painting of
similar murals by Moscow residents. Those murals will be displayed
at Lenox Square in April before going to various U.S. hospitals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
