<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today predicted a `new kind of
peace'' between the Soviet Union and United States, again striking
a positive tone in the wake of skeptical comments by aides and
advisers.
   In a spech at a political luncheon here, Bush did not repeat his
more negative comments of the night before in Houston, when he said
that Soviet activities with Cuba and Nicaraga ``weigh heavily'' on
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``Our mission to Malta was about peace,'' the president said of
his summit last weekend with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
``Not the kind of uneasy peace we've known for the last 40 years _
hard and cold _ but about the new kind of peace we aspire to. One
that is rich with the promise of permanence.''
   ``Yes there were differences at Malta,'' he said. ``We can
express them in an agreeable and forceful way without being
disagreeable.''
   At today's fund-raiser for Rep. Hank Brown, a Colorado
Republican running for the Senate, Bush said he envisions the
coming decade ``filled with optimism, hope and a sense of new
beginnings.''
   He heralded ``new beginnings as democracy blooms behind what
used to be called the Iron Curtain.''
   His statements came following remarks by aides voicing
skepticism about Gorbachev's ability to succeed with his reforms.
   One senior official had characterized Gorbachev's economic views
as ``simplistic.'' White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater,
while disavowing that term, said it would be difficult to integrate
free-market systems into the Soviet Union because the Soviets do
not have experience or knowledge about such sophisticated economic
matters.
   Earlier in the week, Vice President Dan Quayle threw a wet
blanket on the post-summit rosiness by saying the Soviet Union was
still a totalitarian state and that Gorbachev had yet to prove he
was scaling back on international adventurism.
   But Bush today seemed anxious to again stress his hopes for ``a
new American-Soviet relationship. We took our first step toward the
next decade and the new world that is taking shape _ a new world of
security and freedom.''
   He also issued a written statement noting the massive earthquake
that devastated Soviet Armenia a year ago Thursday.
   Recalling the assistance provided by U.S. government and private
groups, and the Soviet offer of help after this year's San
Francisco-area earthquake, the president said, ``As we look to a
new era in U.S.-Soviet relations, we can take hope from these
examples of humanitarian cooperation between our two countries.''
   After the fund-raiser speech, headed to Denver's John F. Kennedy
