<FIRST>r i AM-India-Kidnap     12-08 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Kidnap,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Separatist Militants Kidnap Government Minister's Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separatist militants kidnapped the
daughter of a powerful government minister Friday and demanded the
release of five jailed colleagues as ransom, police said.
   Police said armed members of the Kashmir Liberation Front seized
Rubaiya Mufti, daughter of Home Minister Mufti Mohammed Sayeed,
after flagging down the van in which she was riding with about nine
other people.
   The group demands secession of Jammu-Kashmir state from India
and its assimilation into Pakistan.
   Ms. Rubaiya, 22, was abducted by three men armed with AK-47
rifles as she headed home from work, according to police officials,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. They fled with Ms. Rubaiya in
a car and did not harm the other people in the van, they said.
   In a telephone call to Sayeed's Srinagar residence, members of
the group demanded freedom for five jailed militants in exchange
for Ms. Rubaiya's release.
   The five were arrested in the past year and are in custody in
various jails in Jammu-Kashmir state. None has been convicted or
charged, but they have been held under the anti-terrorism act,
which provides for detention for up to one year without charges.
   Three were identified as Hamid Sheikh, Ghulam Nabi Butt and
Sabir Shah, all believed to be top leaders of the militant
movement. The names of the other prisoners were not known.
   Sayeed, who is in New Delhi, was not available for comment. He
was named to head the home ministry on Tuesday as part of the new
government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh.
   The home minister is responsible for internal security, which
includes police, paramilitary units and domestic intelligence
agencies.
   Jammu-Kashmir is India's only Moslem majority state. Militants
have been agitating for secession from India, claiming Moslems are
discriminated against by the majority Hindus.
   Moslems form 11 percent of India's 880 million people and Hindus
make up 80 percent.
   Sayeed is a Moslem, and his appointment as home minister was
seen as an attempt to answer the allegations of discrimination.
   Jammu-Kashmir state is claimed by both Hindu-majority India and
Moslem-dominated Pakistan. The two countries have fought three wars
over the territory since they gained independence from Britain in
1947.
</TEXT>
