<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Drugs     12-08 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Drugs,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Traffickers Laundering 2 Billion Dollars In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain is regarded in the United States and
Canada as ``an offshore banking system'' because drug traffickers
have laundered at least $1.9 billion in the country, a
parliamentary committee says.
   The House of Commons Home Affairs Committee said in a report
published Thursday that this amount could pose ``a significant
threat to the well-being of Britain's financial institutions.''
   Home Office Minister David Mellor told the Commons on Friday
that international drug traffickers are trying harder than ever to
bring drugs into the country.
   The committee said the drug laundering could have a particularly
destabilizing effect on smaller financial institutions whose
deposits were cut by successful detection and confiscation of drug
profits.
   The report said urgent reforms were needed to increase the
effectiveness of the 1986 Drug Trafficking Offenses Act, which was
introduced to combat international drug trafficking through the
seizure and confiscation of the proceeds.
   Between January 1987 and May 1989, it said, police and customs
officials had obtained confiscation orders for only $17 million.
   Barry Price, head of the National Drugs Intelligence Unit at
Scotland Yard, said in the report that his department was handling
a case where $74 million from drug trafficking had passed to or
through Britain.
   Traffickers wanted to invest in politically and financially
stable countries, he said.
   ``It is a natural consequence of having that sort of environment
within our business world that people are going to deposit money
there,'' Price said.
   The committee urged the Bank of England to examine the scale of
the threat to the financial community posed by money laundering,
which disguises the proceeds of criminal activity.
   Mellor said that between Jan. 1 and Dec. 5, 680 pounds of heroin
was seized by customs, compared with 464 pounds for all of 1988.
   During the same period, the amount of cocaine impounded was 862
pounds, compared with 581 pounds last year, he said.
   ``This year the figures show more of an attempt being made by
international drug traffickers to bring drugs into this country
than ever before. It's an inescapable fact,'' he said.
</TEXT>
