<FIRST>r a AM-BankFraud     12-08 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Fraud,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Businessman Sentenced to 7 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Argentine financier who produced the
Oscar-winning film ``The Official Story'' was sentenced Friday to
seven years in prison for his role in a $38 million bank fraud.
   Jacobo Finkielstain, 51, of Buenos Aires and New York, also was
ordered to pay back $34.7 million even though he claims he has no
assets remaining.
   Finkielstain pleaded guilty Aug. 17 to five counts of conspiracy
and bank fraud. He admitted to two schemes which defrauded the
Central National Bank of New York of $38 million.
   Finkielstain was the 99 percent owner of the federally insured
bank, which was closed and placed into receivership in September
1987.
   At sentencing, U.S. District Judge Michael M. Mukasey attached
the $34.7 million restitution as a condition to three years
probation, which will follow his seven-year prison sentence.
   Mukasey said Finkielstain must make restitution as funds become
available. The judge also imposed a $250,000 fine.
   Finkielstain admitted to fraudulently negotiating a series of
repurchase agreements valued at more than $31 million. Instead of
the normal agreements, whereby bonds are sold in return for an
understanding to buy them back at a specific time for a specific
price, Finkielstain diverted the funds into personal accounts.
   The second scheme involved more than $6 million in fraudulent
loans that Finkielstain obtained from the banks in the names of
shell corporations.
   Among Finkielstain's holdings is a movie production house that
made the 1986 film ``The Official Story,'' awarded an Oscar for
best foreign film.
</TEXT>
