<DOCNO> AP891208-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Walters     12-08 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Walters,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomat Speaks Out on Unification, Crumbling Iron Curtain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow's views on German reunification
cannot be ignored, but it would be hard to ``say no'' to a decision
made freely by the East German people, said Vernon Walters, U.S.
ambassador to Bonn.
   In an interview Thursday, the veteran of Cold War diplomacy also
showed delight about his front-row seat as the Iron Curtain's
battered remains come tumbling down.
   ``I think I'm so lucky I can't even believe it. Most of my
contemporaries are driving golf carts around Florida,'' joked
Walters, 72.
   Walters reached into a drawer of his enormous desk and pulled
out a large chunk of the Berlin Wall.
   ``I got myself a good hunk of it,'' he beamed, proudly holding
his personal remnant of the concrete barrier that once symbolized
Europe's impenetrable divisions.
   Being in the middle of the action as Europe's divisions crumble
has a special meaning for Walters, who has made a career out of
nudging it along.
   The retired Army general held crucial NATO posts in the
alliance's early years, was U.S. military attache in Paris and
Rome, served as interpreter and foreign-relations trouble-shooter
for several presidents, occupied the No. 2 post at the CIA, and has
served as U.S. ambassador-at-large and ambassador to the United
Nations.
   He has rubbed elbows with every imprtant figure from the Cold
War era _ from Dwight Eisenhower to Nikita S. Khrushchev, from
Charles de Gaulle to Marshal Tito, from John F. Kennedy to Fidel
Castro.
   And now, the barriers Walters saw going up after World War II
are being knocked down by the seemingly unstoppable democratic
euphoria sweeping Eastern Europe.
   ``The winds of freedom are blowing, and they're blowing from the
West. And anyone (Communist officials) who doesn't understand this
is going to be gone with the wind,'' Walters said.
   He was among the first U.S. officials to say German
reunification could very well occur because of the democratic
fervor toppling Communist governments across Eastern Europe.
   He said that however changes unfold in Eastern Europe, Moscow's
interests cannot be ignored.
   ``Stability is the key to the ability of the process to go on,''
Walters said. ``And I think things have to proceed in such a way
that they (the Soviets) don't feel humiliated.''
   Walters said if after free elections the East Germans decide to
``pursue a certain path, it will be very hard for people to say
no.''
   But he pointed out recent assertions by President Bush that if
unification occurs, it must come through free choice and peacefully.
   ``Peacefully means with the agreement of the Soviets,'' Walters
said. ``After all, they have 17 divisions in East Germany, and you
can't do it without their agreement.''
   The Kremlin recently softened its hard opposition to even
discussing the possibility of German reunification, and Walters
says one can't exclude the possibility of Moscow eventually
supporting the idea.
   ``I think they (the Soviets) may come to see it as being in
their own interest at some point,'' said Walters, ``especially if
we are successful in talks on reduction of conventional forces.''
   The Soviets have been worried that German reunification could
result in a major change in Europe's military balance.
   Walters also said if there were reunification, he believes the
German people would opt to stay with NATO rather than become
neutral.
   He also said he believes NATO will continue to be an
indispensible element for security in Europe.
   ``Whatever happens, there is still going to be a large, powerful
Russian state on the eastern boundaries of the European community.
And I think very few people want us to go away and leave them,''
said Walters.
   Walters has been ambassador in Bonn since earlier this year and
has been busy monitoring the historic events and keeping Washington
informed.
   ``I've met the Soviet ambassador here, and I met with the Soviet
ambassador in East Berlin. And I have the NATO ambassadors to
dinner from time to time,'' said Walters.
   Walters was in Berlin just after the wall opened and witnessed
the euphoria as East Germans streamed into the West for the first
time in their lives.
   ``I made sure I was there,'' Walters said.
   Walters said he had foreseen great changes occurring, knowing
that Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms would eventually take root in
Eastern Europe.
   ``But I'll be honest with you, the speed of the events is faster
than I had anticipated.''
   Walters said he hopes Eastern Europeans getting their first
taste of freedom don't become impatient and expect events to occur
faster than possible.
   ``We think it's moving at colossal speed, but a lot seem to
think it's moving too slowly and that some of the changes aren't
deep enough,'' he said.
   ``But I think most have enough good sense to see the long shadow
of freedom is falling across them, and the sun hasn't been out in
40 years.''
</TEXT>
