<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Exams     12-08 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Exams,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Postponed After Fraud in U.S. University Admission Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests scheduled Saturday to gain entry
to U.S. universities were canceled following reports of widespread
cheating when the last exams were given in October, an education
administrator said.
   ``Someone somewhere is doing nasty and dirty things,'' Sushil K.
Liddle, director of the Institute for Psychological and Educational
Measurement, said Thursday.
   Liddle refused to give details, but a well-placed source said
copies of the October exam were sold in advance for $300 apiece to
hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Indian students who took the test.
   The institute, in Allahabad about 360 miles southeast of New
Delhi, administers the Graduate Record Examinations on behalf of
Educational Testing Service of Princeton, N.J. The test is taken
primarily by college students to enter graduate school.
   Another source, who works at the Allahabad institute, said he
was told some packets containing blank October test papers had been
opened before they arrived at testing centers in several Indian
cities. The staffer, like the first source, spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The test papers are mailed directly from Princeton to testing
centers in India, the staffer said. He said the packets were opened
after they arrived at airports and before they reached testing
centers.
   Liddle, contacted by telephone from New Delhi, said examinations
scheduled Saturday at 30 testing centers were postponed until
January.
   ``It is a very, very serious matter and we are very concerned,''
said Liddle, who has been director of the Allahabad institute since
it was founded in 1979.
   An estimated 3,500 to 4,000 students were to take the test this
month.
   The Princeton testing service invalidated the tests of
two-thirds of the Indian students who took the October exam. The
invalidations affected 2,744 people who took the tests at 17 of
India's 30 test centers.
   The Allahabad sources said the fraud was discovered when
students at some centers scored far higher than those at other
centers.
   ``That was just a doubt, but soon we heard reports that the
question papers were known beforehand at the centers where students
did extremely well,'' one of the sources said.
   Testing service spokesman Ray Nicosia said it was not known how
many students bought tests or from whom.
   Cheating is common during exams in India. Newspapers routinely
publish notices from universities to inform students their final
exams have been disqualified because of cheating.
   One of the Allahabad sources said the Institute for
Psychological and Educational Measurement learned of the October
fraud after receiving anonymous letters mailed in the south Indian
city of Hyderabad. The letters claimed some people had offered to
sell the test papers to students before they reported for the exam,
the source said.
   Some of the test takers also wrote to Princeton complaining
exams were being sold, said Nicosia.
   Liddle said two types of tests were administered in India for
students seeking admission to American graduate schools.
   Students must pay $50 for the general test. If a second test in
a specific subject is required, the fee for both tests is $85.
   Liddle said students whose tests were invalidated could get a
refund or take the test again free of charge.
   There have been reports of cheating in other tests.
   The administration of the Test of English as a Foreign Language
examination was canceled at five centers in the south Indian city
of Bangalore on Oct. 28 because of alleged fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0140 </DOCNO>
