<FIRST>r a PM-NuclearTest     12-08 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Test,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Nuclear Device Tested with Underground Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British nuclear weapon was detonated
under the Nevada desert today, the Energy Department said.
   The 7 a.m. blast caused ripple motions in highrise buildings in
Las Vegas, 105 miles away.
   It registered 5.4 on the Richter scale at the National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.
   It was the 21st British test conducted at the Nevada site under
an agreement with the United States, said Jim Boyer, an Energy
Department spokesman.
   ``The situation appears normal,'' Boyer said moments after
detonation. ``I don't see anything but smiles on the faces of the
controllers. That would indicate to me another successful test.''
   It was the 11th underground nuclear weapons test of the year at
the Nevada site and the 698th announced test since the government
began testing in Nevada in January 1951. Boyer said the test drew
no protesters, as some have.
</TEXT>
