<FIRST>u w PM-LincolnS&amp;L 1stLd-Writethru a0439 12-08 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investor Describes Land Swap With Lincoln; Keating Appearance Delayed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops 8 grafs new on testimony; picks up 5th graf pvs, The regulator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge delayed Charles H. Keating
Jr.'s scheduled court appearance today to hear testimony about a
land swap regulators claim was used to siphon funds from Keating's
savings and loan association.
   A Phoenix investor, Phillip Gordon, who also is vice chairman of
the Phoenix Planning Commission, testified that he sold a 135-acre
parcel to Lincoln Savings and Loan Association's holding company
last Jan. 28 for a price $1.5 million above its appraised value.
   The next day, Gordon said, he used the $1.5 million to make a 25
percent down payment on the purchase of 445 acres of desert land
west of Phoenix that was owned by a land development subsidiary of
Lincoln.
   Lincoln's chief government regulator had testified Wednesday
that the pair of transactions enabled Lincoln to record a phony
$4.4 million profit on its sale of the desert land.
   In turn, Lincoln's parent company siphoned off $1.8 million from
the thrift's coffers in the form of a future tax liablity on the
phony profits, the regulator told U.S. District Court Judge Stanley
Sporkin.
   Sporkin is holding hearings on government motions to dismiss a
suit Keating filed last May against federal regulators. In the
suit, Keating is asking the court to undo a decision by the
regulators last April to seize control of Lincoln as the worst of
more than 560 thrift failures since mid 1987.
   The government expects the thrift failures to cost taxpayers
more than $160 billion in covering the losses of federally-insured
deposits to a combination of poor investments, insider deals, fraud
and lax regulation. The cost to taxpayers of Lincoln's losses alone
is put at $2.5 billion.
   Keating had been scheduled to appear today but Sporkin on
Thursday told attorneys for Keating and the government that he
wanted to hear testimony today only from the regulator who
recommended the seizure of Lincoln last April and three Phoenix
businessmen.
   The regulator, Kevin O'Connell, deputy director of the Treasury
Department's Office of Thrift Supervision, testified Thursday that
Lincoln's owner used ``sham'' transactions with the three
businessmen to siphon off millions of dollars in deposits.
   O'Connell faced cross-examination today by Lincoln's attorney in
the suit, Charles Stern.
   Keating, who contributed $1.3 million to the political causes of
five senators in a campaign to thwart regulators, was the last of
eight witnesses the government has scheduled in seeking dismissal
of his suit.
   Keating and his attorneys allege Lincoln was being operated
soundly and that the government's takeover of the Irvine, Calif.,
thrift was ``capricious and arbitrary.''
   The target of a criminal investigation by a federal grand jury
in Los Angeles, Keating has refused once to testify in response to
a subpoena. Last month, he invoked Fifth Amendment protection
against self-incrimination before the House Banking Committee.
   Asked if Keating would again claim a constitutional right not to
testify in the court case in his suit, his personal attorney, John
Quinn, said Thursday, ``I'm not at liberty to discuss that.''
   O'Connell testified that Lincoln and its parent company,
American Continental Corp. of Phoenix, claimed $15.5 million in
phony profits from two bogus land transactions to justify $5.8
million in tax collections from Lincoln that were never paid the
government.
   Those two deals, involving some 1,500 acres of desert land
outside Phoenix plus a stock transaction and the tax arrangement,
are ``literally just the tip of the iceberg,'' James P. Murphy, an
attorney for the government, told Sporkin.
   O'Connell testified American Continental, of which Keating is
chairman, collected $94.8 million in deferred taxes from the thrift
from 1984 through 1988 _ much of it on phony profits from real
estate deals.
   Lincoln's attorneys say the tax-sharing arrangement under which
American Continental bundled the taxes owed by both it Lincoln were
approved by federal regulators in San Francisco.
   O'Connell, however, said Lincoln had ``misrepresented'' its
nature to the San Francisco officials. Federal regulations, he
said, allow a holding company only to act as a collector of current
taxes owed by a thrift subsidiary, not deferred taxes.
   He said Keating's tax-sharing arrangement amounted to an
interest-free loan from Lincoln to its holding company, which is
prohibited by federal law.
   Asked how much of the $94.8 million went to pay taxes, O'Connell
said, ``Our best estimate is zero.''
   The regulator said that four months before Lincoln was seized,
the government ordered American Continental to repay Lincoln $60
million of the tax payments it had collected from the thrift.
   But American Continental declared bankruptcy last April 13, one
day before the government seized Lincoln and before any of the
money was refunded, said O'Connell.
   Meanwhile, thrift regulators said Thursday that 16 S&amp;Ls were
permitted to sell $3 billion in uninsured debt to their retail
customers, the same practice that cost many depositors at Lincoln
their life savings.
   Some 22,000 investors, many of them elderly pensioners and
widows, lost an estimated $250 million by purchasing subordinated
debt in American Continental in 1987 and 1988. Despite that, the
same practice was permitted at other S&amp;Ls, including seven which
received permission for sales this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
