<FIRST>r a AM-LeotaTrial     12-08 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leota Trial,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Blasts Misdemeanor Conviction in Son's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Beverly Todd, angered by the
misdemeanor negligent homicide conviction of the man who killed her
son, wants legislators to make the crime a felony.
   Todd held a news conference Friday to denounce the verdict
returned in the case of John Tavo Leota, who was charged with
second-degree murder in the death of her 18-year-old son, Malik
Smith, of Los Angeles.
   Smith's head hit the floor when Leota struck him at a dance club
March 18. He died two days later.
   A 3rd District Court jury Thursday found Leota, 19, guilty of
the lesser offense, a misdemeanor punishable by up to one year in
jail. He will be sentenced next month.
   ``The defendant admitted his guilt. The action of hitting Malik
_ a hit, by the way, that was powerful enough to lift our son six
inches into the air _ Malik died as a result of that hit and the
defendant got is what is tantamount to a slap on the hand, a
misdemeanor,'' said Todd, flanked by Smith's father, television
director Kris Keiser.
   Todd said she had asked state Rep. Joanne Milner to introduce a
bill that would make negligent homicide a third-degree felony,
punishable by up to five years imprisonment. Milner said she would
sponsor the bill next month.
   The incident happened at a teen disco in West Valley, where
Smith had gone while on a Utah ski vacation.
   Leota testified that Smith showed off on the dance floor and
embarrassed him. He said he did not mean to kill the man when he
hit him once and kicked him in the face.
   Todd has appeared in such movies as ``Clara's Heart,'' ``Lean On
Me,'' ``Baby Boom,'' and ``Roots.''
