<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TimesPoll-Cranston     12-08 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times Poll-Cranston,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Approval Of Alan Cranston Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public approval of Sen. Alan Cranston has
plummeted since he and four other U.S. senators have come under
fire for intervening on behalf of collapsed Lincoln Savings,
according to a poll published Friday.
   The Los Angeles Times Poll showed that Cranston's approval
rating has undergone a turnabout since an October poll in which 56
percent of the respondents had a favorable view of him and 32
percent saw him unfavorably.
   The latest poll found 58 percent had an unfavorable impression
of Cranston, as opposed to 32 percent favorable. An overwhelming 79
percent said it was time to give someone else a chance to run for
California's senatorial seat.
   For the five-day telephone survey ending Dec. 6, calls were made
to 2,046 people, 1,594 of whom were registered voters. The poll's
margin of error is plus or minus 3 percentage points.
   Forty-one percent of those answering the poll said Cranston
should step down, as opposed to 37 percent who believe Cranston
should remain as majority whip of the U.S. Senate.
   Only 14 percent of those surveyed said Cranston has performed
his duties well enough to be re-elected.
   Cranston has come under fire for accepting $850,000 in donations
from Charles H. Keating Jr., owner of the defunct Irvine-based
thrift, and then apparently bargaining with federal regulators on
behalf of Lincoln Savings. The donations went to three voter
registration groups Cranston supported.
   A majority of those polled, 79 percent, said Cranston acted
improperly in the Lincoln controversy; only 8 percent said he acted
properly.
   Investigators believe Keating may have used contributions to
gain favor among powerful politicians to protect Lincoln Savings.
The taxpayer bailout of Lincoln Savings is expected to cost up to
$2 billion, the most expensive thrift failure in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
