<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Art     12-08 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Art,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Considered Selling Off Museum Collections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia has suggested selling off some of
its museum collections for hard currency, an auction house official
said Friday.
   At Czechoslovakia's invitation, three officials from Christie's
auction house visited museums and galleries in Prague and
Bratislava in September to discuss possibly selling mainly
unwanted, non-Czechoslovak items, said legal adviser David Allison.
   ``We were taken around _ nothing was offered,'' Allison said in
an interview. ``We only know that they tell us they have a lot of
stuff in their basements.''
   Allison said the proposed sale ``hasn't been dropped _ we've
left it to them to come back to us.''
   But because of the political turmoil in Czechoslovakia, ``it
won't be a very high priority. It will be some time before the
project is reviewed, if it ever is.''
   Allison said the State Jewish Museum of Prague was included in
their itinerary, prompting criticism from Jewish groups. He
insisted Christie's would not be interested in auctioning
``anything that has a doubtful title or that would raise a protest
from any section of the public.''
   The Los Angeles-based Simon Wiesenthal Center said Friday that
the Jewish museum's collection ``should remain intact and
transferred to Israel as part of the normalization of relations
hoped for as a result of current developments within Czechoslovakia
and Eastern Europe.''
   ``If the collection is sold, then monies raised clearly belong
to the Jewish community in Czechoslovakia,'' said Shimon Samuels,
the Wiesenthal center's European director.
   Allison said the Czechoslovak parliament had suggested in the
fall that state museums ``wishing to sell off unwanted items would
be allowed to do so.''
   ``Most museums have things in their basement, and all are
desperately in need of money with which to buy other items or, as
in the case of Czechoslovakia, to buy small things like
humidifiers,'' he said. ``They are very much starved of funds.
   ``The Czechoslovak government felt one way around this would be
to sell off some items'' through Christie's and ``be paid through
hard currency,'' Allison said.
   But the state agency Art Centrum, responsible for museums and
galleries, made it clear that ``items with Czechoslovak
dimensions'' would not be offered for sale to avert protests from
the country's heritage lobby.
   Prague has much European art that escaped destruction in both
world wars. Once a cosmopolitan center, it became ``very rich in
works of art from all over Europe,'' Allison said.
   He visited the National Gallery, the Museum of Technology and
the City of Prague Museum, as well as the main gallery in
Bratislava, where he said officials told him that ``only 0.5
percent of the works of art they've got is on display and the rest
is in store and in not very good condition.''
   ``Things they've got are literally rotting away'' in damp store
rooms, he said.
</TEXT>
