<FIRST>r a AM-EatingOnCredit     12-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eating On Credit,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent Angry Over School Lunch Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a high school student is
angry over a school policy in which cafeteria workers are told not
to feed students whose parents have outstandings bills for food.
   Joan Bowe of Campbells Creek said she learned of the policy when
her daughter came home hungry one day last month.
   ``That meant our children were in school all day long hungry and
none of us parents were made aware of it,'' Bowe said.
   Bowe's daughter and a friend had slipped out of the lunch line
after witnessing other students with outstanding bills being denied
lunch.
   ``She knew she'd be embarrassed because I hadn't sent the lunch
bill. It was just an oversight of mine,'' Bowe said.
   Unpaid bills for cafeteria meals totaled about $12,000 at DuPont
High School alone, said Principal Jimmie Compton. The debts led him
to crack down this year on students eating on credit. Parents owed
the school about $5,000 as of two weeks ago when Compton began
denying lunch to students whose lunch payments were delinquent.
   ``I can't operate a cafeteria with a deficit like that,'' he
said. ``I can't pay the bills.''
   A computerized payment system was enacted at DuPont and other
area schools last year so students who received free or reduced
lunches could not be distinguished from other students.
   Each student has a number, which a cashier punches into a
machine. Parents receive bills monthly.
   The system has worked well in most areas, although schools in
the eastern part of the county, such as DuPont, have a higher rate
of non-payment, said schools spokesman Mike Bell.
   Compton said the school informed parents who owed money that
their children would be unable to charge meals at the cafeteria if
outstndings debts were unpaid by the 15th of each month.
   Bowe said she received no notice until this week when she
received a two-month bill for about $25.
</TEXT>
