<FIRST>r a AM-People-Mason-Specter     12-08 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Mason-Specter,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pa. Senator Meets Borscht Belt Comic _ And Survives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even before they sat down for lunch, U.S. Sen.
Arlen Specter realized the possible political implications of his
Friday get-together with comedian Jackie Mason.
   ``Jackie's speaking for himself. I'll deny everything Jackie
says,'' joked Specter, R-Pa., shortly after shaking hands with
Mason before their luncheon date at Elaine's on the Upper East Side
of Manhattan.
   Mason, of course, created problems for GOP mayoral hopeful
Rudolph Giuliani earlier this year with his remarks about Jewish
voting habits and a perceived slur against blacks. While Jackie was
apologetic about the remarks at the time, he was back to his
boisterous self on Friday.
   ``Nobody claims I cost Giuliani votes. It was a fiction, a bum
rap by a couple of people at a couple of papers. ... When I joined,
Giuliani was down 20 percent. He lost by 2 percent,'' Mason said
with a shrug.
   ``It's the same jokes I told on Broadway for two years. I got a
Tony Award for those jokes,'' said Mason.
   Specter didn't appear fazed by his Mason's political past; the
pair wound up posing for dozens of pictures together with an
assortment of celebrities at the event, which was not a fund-raiser.
   Specter, who lives in the land of the cheese steak, even laughed
at Mason's Borscht Belt wisecracks.
   ``All my life I heard there was no such thing as a free lunch.
But whenever I see a senator eating, he's eating for free,'' said
Mason.
   Specter said he and Mason had met last year in Washington for
lunch _ ``I still have the receipt in my pocket,'' the senator
cracked _ and they have stayed in touch since then. Mason said the
Friday lunch was aimed at creating a higher profile for Specter,
who runs again in 1992.
   ``The truth of the matter is I love the guy,'' said Mason. ``I
want to give him all the support I can and get him re-elected.''
</TEXT>
