<DOCNO> AP891208-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-S&amp;Ls     12-08 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-S&amp;Ls,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush at Head Table With Developer Whose Company Under Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush shared the head table at a
Republican fund-raiser Friday in Denver with Larry Mizel, a
Colorado developer whose company is one of several at the center of
federal investigations into the savings and loan industry.
   Larry Mizel, owner of MDC Holdings Inc., was chairman of a
luncheon for Rep. Hank Brown, a Republican a hoping to succeed Sen.
William Armstrong, R-Colo. Bush's speech was the main attraction at
the $250-to-$1,000-a-plate event, expected to raise between
$500,000 and $1 million.
   The president, before launching into his talk, referred to many
of the guests at the head table but did not mention Mizel, a
prominent Republican who raised $1 million for Ronald Reagan's 1984
campaign.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president had no
say in Mizel's involvement, adding, ``He's involved here through
the Brown campaign. We just have no control over it.''
   Mizel's company, along with Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association, of Irvine, Calif., and Silverado Banking, Savings and
Loan Association, of Denver, are the focus of an investigation by
thrift regulators, according to M. Danny Wall, director of the
Office of Thrift Supervision.
   The office is looking at series transactions in which MDC,
Lincoln, Silverado and San Jacinto Savings Association, Bellaire,
Texas, swapped junk bonds and loans among themselves, Wall said.
Such ``daisy chains'' have been used by S&amp;Ls to hide questionable
credits from regulators.
   According to a September 1988 letter released by the House
Banking Committee, S&amp;L regulators in Dallas were concerned with the
``apparent unhealthy lending relationships'' among the institutions
and MDC.
   The failure of Lincoln has been the focus of lengthy hearings
this fall before the committee, which plans to examine other S&amp;L
collapses, including the December 1988 failure of Silverado.
   The Lincoln case is under scrutiny because five senators _ Alan
Cranston, D-Calif.; Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.; Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John Glenn, D-Ohio, and John McCain, R-Ariz. _
met with regulators on Lincoln's behalf in April 1987.
   Silverado has attracted attention because of its links to Mizel
and to Neil Bush, the president's 34-year-old son, who served on
Silverado's board from 1985 until August 1988.
   Regulators attributed the failure of Silverado to ``substantial
dissipation of assets due to alleged violations of laws, rules and
regulations.'' The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is examining the
case to determine whether to file a civil suit against Silverado's
officers and directors.
   James Moroney, a former examiner at the Federal Home Loan Bank
of Topeka, has alleged in interviews that Silverado was in trouble
as early as 1986, but regulators did not crack down because of the
institution's ties to Neil Bush and Mizel.
   Wall, on Thursday told reporters his agency looked at Moroney's
allegation and found it invalid. Neil Bush has declined to comment
on Silverado except to say he is cooperating fully with
investigations of the institution.
   Also attending the Brown luncheon was Bill Walters, another
Denver developer. Walters, who defaulted on $41 million in real
estate loans from Silverado, owned the Cherry Creek National Bank,
which extended a $1 million line of credit to Neil Bush's oil and
gas company, JNB Exploration.
   Walters was one more than 50 co-chairmen of the luncheon, who as
part of accepting the title promised to sell at least 10 $1,000
tickets to the event.
</TEXT>
