<SECOND>AM-Poland-Lenin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Local Government Calls For Moving Monument</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT that statue should be moved
by early next week, sted within a month; pickup graf 5 pvs `Government
officials...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A monument to Vladimir I. Lenin that has
been a rallying point for violent anti-Soviet protests should be
moved next week, local officials said Friday.
   Protesters have tried to destroy the statue during
demonstrations in the last two weeks. They have clashed with
police, who used water cannons and tear gas to disperse them.
   The Solidarity-led national government has said it won't
tolerate more violence, and mediators have called on local
officials to remove the monument so that order can be maintained.
   On Friday, the steering committee of the Krakow district council
unanimously called on the president of the panel _ in effect the
mayor _ to take steps to move the monument by Tuesday, the PAP news
agency reported. It was not clear where the statue would be moved.
   Government officials have said residents should decide the fate
of the statue to the founder of the Soviet state that dominates a
square in the Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta, built in the 1950s as a
model socialist industrial city.
   Youthful demonstrators have created a delicate problem for the
government of Prime Minister Taduesz Mazowiecki, formed of former
opposition forces who now must maintain relations with the Soviet
Union.
   The police action Nov. 29 apparently was the first large-scale
use of force against demonstrators since Solidarity took over the
government in August.
   The government said Thursday that ``hooliganism'' won't be
tolerated and the police will be forced to take ``firmer steps in
order to prevent such dangerous excesses.''
   The pro-Solidarity Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper reported Friday
that one of the participants in the disturbance, a 19-year-old
worker at the Lenin steel mill, said he and his cohorts will
continue to riot even if the statue is moved.
   Not freely elected, the people's councils that form local
governments have not yet been subject to the reform sweeping the
central government, and they are still dominated by Communist Party
members.
</TEXT>
