<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     12-08 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opponents Say de Klerk in Cover-up on Death Squads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church groups and political
opponents said Friday that President F.W. de Klerk was attempting a
cover-up by rejecting calls for an independent inquiry into
allegations of police death squads.
   Police also announced that de Klerk, three other Cabinet
members, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, and the Rev. Allan
Boesak, president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches, were
on a hit list found with a weapons cache after five members of a
far right-wing organization were arrested.
   ``It would seem that President de Klerk's political courage has
failed him at a crucial time on a crucial issue. ... The process
from here onwards can only be a farce,'' the South African Council
of Churches said in response to de Klerk's announcement the police
and provincial attorneys general would investigate allegations that
police hit squads had killed opponents of the white-run government.
   The Dutch Reformed Church, the largest white denomination in
South Africa, which frequently disagrees with the South African
Council of Churches on political issues, sent a letter to de Klerk
saying the need for an independent and public inquiry into police
assassination units is ``blatant.'' De Klerk is one of the few
Cabinet members who is not a member of the church.
   De Klerk, in his first substantive statement on the death squad
controversy, said Thursday night, ``A judicial inquiry can take
months, if not years, to reach its final conclusions. In the
meanwhile, a climate of suspicion and distrust could develop,
something the country can ill afford.''
   The national police force has been assailed for failing to solve
dozens of killings of government opponents since 1978.
Anti-apartheid leaders say many people believe security personnel
helped plan, take part in, or cover up such actions.
   The Council of Churches, headed by prominent anti-apartheid
clergymen such as Tutu and Boesak, said: ``It is clear the issue of
the death squads is going to be covered up.''
   It suggested that initial prosecutions could begin as the
judicial inquiry proceeded.
   ``How long did the victims of the death squads have to wait
before the South African government was forced by present
revelations to even make a pronouncement on this matter?'' the
church council said.
   Jannie Momberg, a parliamentary representative of the
anti-apartheid Democratic Party said de Klerk's decision was his
first major mistake and ``a tragic blunder,'' which would explode
in his face after the expectations raised by his enlightened
speeches about reform and change in South Africa.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said two former security
policemen whose allegations prompted the inquiry would be
prosecuted. One of them, Butana Nofemela, awaits execution for an
unrelated murder, and the other, Dirk Coetzee, is believed to have
fled abroad.
   The justice minister did not specify what charges would be
brought against Coetzee if he is extradited, but said Nofomela
would be prosecuted for the 1982 murder of Durban attorney
Griffiths Mxenge.
   Coetzee, Nofomela and a third former security policemen have
said in newspaper interviews or sworn affidavits that they took
part in death squad operations in the early and mid-1980s on orders
of superiors, many of whom still occupy high positions in the
police.
   Several police officers will be investigated, and five have been
suspended from duty until inquiries or legal proceedings are
completed, de Klerk said.
   Also Friday, Maj.-Gen. Jaap Joubert of the detective branch said
there was a plan by the right-wingers arrested Tueaday to attack de
Klerk, Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, Defense Minister Magnus
Malan, and Foreign Minister Pik Botha to create ``chaos in the
country.''
   He said police had been monitoring the five, who had broken away
from the neo-Nazi Afrikaner Resistance Movement. Joubert said
charges pending against the five include murder, armed robbery, and
violations of the arms and explosives acts.
   He did not specify who the group may have murdered, but a
pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, said Thursday police were
investigating the possibility that blacks had been killed as
practice for attacks on the political targets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
