<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Prison     12-08 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Prison,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Prisoners Reported Killed in Riots in Northern Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of prisoners rioted in four
prisons Friday and killed at least four fellow inmates after
legislators refused to broaden a new amnesty to include repeat
offenders, state media reported.
   The worst riot, at Czarne Prison housing 1,500 hard-core
prisoners on the Baltic Coast, began Thursday evening after the
Sejm, or lower house of parliament, turned down a Senate proposal
to the amnesty approved Nov. 16.
   Disturbances also were reported in three other northern Poland
prisons, said Jerzy Rybarczyk, spokesman for the Central Board of
Penitentiaries in Warsaw.
   In all, 4,350 inmates were involved, state TV said. All the
affected facilities are maximum-security prisons.
   Justice Minister Aleksander Bentkowski, appearing on the evening
TV news, said he ordered ``extraordinary measures,'' and added, ``I
think there will be order in our prisons soon.''
   At the Czarne Prison, prisoners learned of the Sejm decision on
the TV news Thursday and immediately ``started destroying
equipment, set warehouse facilities on fire and attacked prison
guards who tried to get the situation under control,'' the state
PAP news agency said.
   Three battered and stabbed prisoners later were dumped at the
main gate of the prison by inmates, officials said. Two were dead
and the third died en route to the hospital. A fourth Czarne inmate
died later, state TV said.
   ``It is suspected that the situation was used to settle accounts
among the prisoners,'' PAP said.
   Inmates wrapped in blankets gathered on the fire-damaged prison
roof as flames shot through the windows of the brick buildings.
   ``Why are we doing it? Because we don't agree with the verdicts
that were handed out in the 1980s,'' said one prisoner, his eyes
bandaged.
   The situation inside Czarne was out of control Friday, with
about 1,000 prisoners attempting at one point to force open the
main gate, PAP said.
   Heavily armed guards and police surrounded the prison, PAP said,
quoting district prison commissioner Col. Tadeusz Judycki.
   Besides Czarne, according to TV, about 1,000 prisoners rebelled
at the Goleniow Prison near Szczecin in northwest Poland, where
inmates seized two cellblocks and set a fire. About 1,000 rioted at
Kaminsk, near Olsztyn in north-central Poland, and 850 inmates
rioted at Nowogard, also near Szczecin, TV said.
   Parliament Deputy Edward Mueller, a Solidarity representative
from Slupsk, went to Czarne Prison to try to calm the inmates, but
no formal negotiations were under way.
   The Sejm aproved a limited amnesty Nov. 16. The Polish Senate
urged broadening it to include multiple offenders, those convicted
of major thefts, and those convicted of vehicular manslaughter
under influence of alcohol.
   The proposal aroused widespread debate among Poles who feared it
would lead to a release of criminals.
   The amnesty passed Nov. 16 suspends sentences of under two years
for unpremeditated crimes and under three years for premeditated
crimes.
   Death sentences were reduced to 25 years in prison, 25-year
terms were reduced to 15 years, and other sentences were reduced by
one-third to one-half.
   The amnesty applied to crimes committed before Sept. 12, the day
the Solidarity-led government took control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
