<FIRST>r a AM-EscalatorAccident     12-08 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escalator Accident,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Children Injured in Escalator Accident at Train Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escalator in a subway station suddenly
stopped Friday, injuring 23 schoolchildren on an outing, a Transit
Authority spokesman said. It was the third escalator mishap this
week in the subways.
   One child had a possible broken ankle and another had a possible
broken leg, said Jim Walsh, spokesman at Bellevue Medical Center.
The other children brought to the hospital were being treated for
bumps and bruises. All were ages 9 to 11, he said.
   Sixty children were on the escalator when the accident occurred,
said Bob Previdi, a TA spokesman.
   ``We are all a little bit anxious and concerned,'' said James
Mazza, deputy superintendent of District 3 in Manhattan, which
oversees the school the students came from, P.S. 191 in Manhattan.
   Some students returned to school, where a crisis center was set
up.
   On Monday, 13 people were injured during mishaps on an escalator
about three minutes apart.
   Two people were injured during the evening rush hour when some
young people ran down a crowded up escalator in a station on
Manhattan's East Side.
   Three minutes later, the TA began to unload a train because of a
fire uptown from it. The line was more crowded than usual because
other lines were out because of a water main break.
   The platform became crowded, and transit police said people
couldn't get off the escalator and fell backward. In the ensuing
pandemonium, 11 people were injured.
   The TA is investigating its procedures to determine how the
congestion could have been avoided.
</TEXT>
