<HEAD>Developments in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Friday's developments in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party holds a historic, emergency party congress
to elect a new leadership and debate the party's proposed new
program that calls for free elections in May and broad cooperation
with opposition groups.
   Prosecutors announce the filing of criminal charges against
former party leader Erich Honecker, former Premier Willi Stoph, and
four other ousted leaders accused of corruption and abuse of power.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders offer to surrender their shaky control over
the government for the first time since 1948 and accept a minority
role in a coalition Cabinet. Opposition leaders threaten to hold a
general strike Monday if the government fails to enact reforms.
   Communist President Gustav Husak issues an amnesty aimed at
meeting opposition demands to release all political prisoners.
Federal prosecutor Jan Pjescak resigns.
   Czechoslovakia suggests selling off some of its museum
collections for hard currency, Christie's auction house says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET UNION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party Central Committee prepares for an
extraordinary session Saturday amid rumors of Kremlin personnel
changes, an impending general strike, a growing split in the party
and the first crack in its total dominance of Soviet life.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BULGARIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party expels more of the old guard from its
leadership, leaving the ruling Politburo with only three members
who were there when Todor Zhivkov was fired as party chief Nov. 10.
Ousted were four full and two non-voting candidate members of the
Politburo and 22 full and four candidate members of the
policy-making Central Committee. Zhivkov was among those losing
seats on the Central Committee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government began a series of talks with opposition parties
and other groups on the date of general elections, the economy and
engaging the new political parties in the decision-making process.
Initial reaction from the opposition was negative.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Officials say a monument in Krakow to Vladimir I. Lenin that has
been a rallying point for violent anti-Soviet protests should be
moved next week. Protesters have tried to destroy the statue during
demonstrations in the last two weeks. They have clashed with
police, who used water cannons and tear gas to disperse them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ELSEWHERE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _ In Washington, a Pentagon official says some Soviet military
forces in East Germany have raised their alert status, but it's
apparently just to protect their bases and nuclear weapons.
   _ In Bonn, West Germany, U.S. Ambassador Vernon Walters said in
an interview that Moscow's views on German reunification cannot be
ignored, but it would be hard to ``say no'' to a decision made
freely by the East German people.
   _ In Strasbourg, France, where leaders of the European Community
met, Dutch Premier Ruud Lubbers said the economic summit would
culminate in sending ``a message of encouragement to those people
(in Eastern Europe) who are the driving forces of reform ... it is
a revolution without violence.''
</TEXT>
