<FIRST>r i AM-China-Army     12-08 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Army,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing Mayor Says People Must Love The Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Beijing opened a national defense
education center Friday with an appeal for people to love the army
and a warning against the threat of anti-Communist foreigners.
   People must be educated to love and understand the People's
Liberation Army and create a better social environment for them,
hard-line Mayor Chen Xitong was quoted as saying by the official
Xinhua News Agency.
   The army is the guardian of China's socialist system, he said.
   ``The anti-government riots earlier this year showed that
foreign anti-Communist forces have never given up their plot to
subvert the proletarian dictatorship in China for even a single
day,'' he said.
   Chinese leaders and the official media have heaped praise on the
army for its role in the violent suppression of pro-democracy
demonstrators in Beijing on June 3-4.
   It has said the student-led movement was a
``counterrevolutionary rebellion'' aiming to overthrow the
government and backed by foreign agitators. The government has
never identified the alleged foreign backers, although about a
dozen people were arrested as spies for Taiwan.
   Chen said education in national defense, generally on the wane
in China since the late 1960s when Mao Tse-tung called for mass
preparations to fight what was thought to be an impending Soviet
invasion, will unite the country politically and be economically
productive.
   Such education, he said, is essential in the present domestic
and international situation.
   Despite an intense propaganda campaign, the reputation of the
army was tarnished by the June attack on Beijing in which hundreds,
and perhaps thousands, of Beijing residents were shot by soldiers.
   The Communist Party's People's Daily this week published
instructions on how local governments should praise the army so the
masses will love it.
   Military training also has been stepped up. The entire
first-year class at Beijing University, one of the centers of
student activism this spring, has been ordered to undergo a year of
schooling at a camp in a city outside Beijing.
</TEXT>
