<FIRST>r a AM-MasonTrial     12-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mason Trial,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mason Drug-Murder Case Winds Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of Howard ``Pappy'' Mason neared its
conclusion Friday with prosecutors saying the accused drug kingpin
ordered the murder of a police officer to seal his position as a
drug world leader.
   ``He did something that only someone impressed with his own
power would do. He could have cared less which police officer was
killed,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Leslie Caldwell in bringing
her case to a close. ``You lose respect, you lose control.''
   Mason, 31, is on trial in U.S. District Court facing
racketeering and conspiracy charges that include ordering from his
jail cell the Feb. 26, 1988, murder of Officer Edward Byrne.
   Following instructions from U.S. District Judge Edward R.
Korman, the panel was expected to begin deliberating later Friday
afternoon.
   Four of Mason's associates were convicted earlier this year of
killing the 22-year-old rookie as he sat in his patrol car guarding
the home of a witness in a drug case in the neighborhood in the
borough of Queens where Mason's drug ring, the Bebos, operated.
   ``When Pappy Mason gave the order to kill a police officer it
was like pushing a button'' and four workers ``did it without
questioning why,'' Caldwell said.
   Mason, jailed on a state weapons charge, continued his courtroom
boycott. Court officials have hooked up a closed-circuit TV to
allow the defendant to watch the proceedings from a courthouse
holding cell.
   Mason's lawyer, Harry C. Batchelder Jr., said the government had
not come close to proving beyond a reasonable doubt that Mason had
ordered the slaying.
   Repeating his earlier arguments, Batchelder told the jury the
prosecution had produced only ``hearsay evidence'' that Mason
ordered the slaying. He said the government's witnesses _ a
collection of admitted murderers, drug addicts and thieves given
deals for their cooperation _ were absolutely incredible.
   ``When you make a pact with people like this they will sing the
French National Anthem backwards to you to save their skins,''
Batchelder said.
   In a bit of courtroom melodrama, the brawny lawyer waved before
the panel a plea agreement in which a witness had promised to tell
the truth, likening the lies he said it contained to Judas'
betrayal of Christ.
   ``This piece of paper is the equivalent of 13 pieces of silver.
This piece of paper is the guarantor of nothing,'' Batchelder said.
``It's an agreement: `If you'll dance to my tune I'll pay for it.'''
   Mason, who allegedly began dealing crack and cocaine about five
years ago in South Jamaica, Queens _ one of the city's most
notorious drug battle grounds _ went to trial 10 days ago on an
11-count federal drug conspiracy indictment. If convicted, he faces
mandatory life imprisonment.
   Most of the other members of his violent drug ring have either
been convicted or have pleaded guilty to drug charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
