<FIRST>r a AM-RubyGun 1stLd-Writethru a0670 12-08 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ruby Gun, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Deadline in Jack Ruby Gun Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `A probate ..., to make it Oswald, sted Harvey.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heirs of Jack Ruby, embroiled in a
decades-long battle over ownership of the gun Ruby used to kill Lee
Harvey Oswald, now are fighting the IRS over claims to the weapon.
   A probate judge Friday gave the Internal Revenue Service until
Jan. 15 to prove its claim to proceeds from the sale of the
.38-caliber Colt Cobra that Ruby used to kill Oswald two days after
the assassination of President Kennedy.
   Ruby's brother, Earl, has until Dec. 22 to demonstrate to the
court his and other heirs' contention that they have a better claim
to profits from the estate, said Dallas County Probate Judge Robert
E. Price.
   Price plans to rule on the IRS claim by Jan. 25.
   Ruby died in 1967, four years after he shot Oswald in the
basement of the Dallas City Jail.
   At the time, Ruby owed the IRS $17,000. The back-tax bill, plus
penalties and interest, has grown to $86,010, the IRS said in court
documents. The state of Texas also is seeking $1,227 in back taxes
from the estate.
   Earl Ruby long has contested executor Jules Mayer's right to the
gun, which Mayer keeps in a safe deposit box. Earl Ruby claims his
brother, from his deathbed, told Earl that Mayer had been
instructed to tear up the will that made him executor.
   Mayer and Earl Ruby have accused each other of seeking to sell
the gun for personal gain. Mayer contends proceeds from the sale
are needed to pay off Ruby's debts.
   He has estimated the gun might bring at least $125,000 on the
historical artifacts market.
   A jury in 1964 convicted Ruby of murder and sentenced him to
death in the electric chair. But the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals overturned the conviction, citing reasons that included
failure to move the trial from Dallas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
