<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-VideotapedKilling     12-08 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Videotaped Killing,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Continue Probe Following Indictments in Videotaped Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Mark Ramsey was being buried
Friday in North Carolina, investigators were trying to unravel the
bizarre sequence of events that led to his videotaped killing by a
would-be assassin.
   Ramsey, 19, a onetime bartender from Wilmington, N.C., was tied
to a tree and shot to death in early October. tree. His body was
found in early November after a young woman confessed to shooting
him to prove her credentials as an assassin, police say.
   Police said the suspect, 20-year-old Diedre Hunt, also told them
that Ramsey had been tied to a tree for the same reason _ he was
trying to prove his credentials as a hit-man to pool hall owner
Konstantinos Fotopoulos.
   Fotopoulos and Ms. Hunt were formally charged by a grand jury
Wednesday in Ramsey's death. Authorities said they were trying to
determine Friday wheter the pair were responsible for other
slayings.
   According to authorities, Ramsey and Ms. Hunt worked at one time
as bartenders in Fotopoulos' pool hall on the Daytona Beach
Boardwalk.
   Investigators say Fotopoulos hired two hit men in early November
to kill his wife, Lisa, and then allegedly shot one of them to
death in his home after his wife was wounded.
   The Ramsey slaying was unrelated to the plot to kill Mrs.
Fotopoulos, police say. But after Ms. Hunt was arrested in the
plot, authorities say, she confessed to the earlier slaying of
Ramsey.
   Police said Ms. Hunt told them that Fotopoulos had told Ramsey
that to join his ring of assassins, Ramsey had to keep from jumping
while Fotopoulos fired live bullets at his feet. Ramsey agreed to
be tied up to be sure he wouldn't jump, Ms. Hunt said. Then she
shot him.
   Ramsey's body was found, still tied to the tree, shortly after
Ms. Hunt confessed following her arrest on Nov. 8. Later, police
and prosecutors searched Fotopoulos's garage and back yard and
found an 8mm videotape of the slaying, along with the weapon
believed to have been used to shoot Ramsey.
   Assistant State Attorney David Damore, who spent four hours
explaining the case to a grand jury, said later, ``We're hoping the
seal of approval from the grand jury is the first step toward the
successful prosecution.''
   Mrs. Fotopoulos, who said she has fully recovered from a bullet
wound fired by one of her would-be assassins, said she knew Ramsey
had worked at her husband's business.
   ``He seemed like a nice boy,'' she said. ``It's a shame what
happened.''
   Fotopoulos also faces charges in his wife's shooting. Fotopoulos
told officers he had gunned down a burglar, Bryan Chase, 18, who
had broken into his home and shot his wife Nov. 4.
   When police decided that Fotopoulos had masterminded a
murder-for-hire plot, they arrested him, Ms. Hunt, Teja James, 17,
and Yvonne Henderson, 20. James told police he had tried to kill
Mrs. Fotopoulos twice but failed. Ms. Henderson told police she
knew of the plan.
   Besides the murder indictments against Fotopoulos and Ms. Hunt,
the grand jury charged all four with conspiracy to commit murder
and attempted murder and Fotopoulos, Ms. Hunt and Ms. Henderson
with soliciting to commit murder.
   All four remain in the Volusia County Jail without bail.
</TEXT>
