<DOCNO> AP891208-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     12-08 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Government Talks With Opposition To Avert Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government began talks with
opposition parties and other groups Friday to negotiate a peaceful
transition to democracy and avert economic collapse, but initial
reaction from the opposition was negative.
   ``There was no agreement on anything, there are major
differences of opinion,'' said Peter Toelgyessy of the League of
Free Democrats. ``It was all right if we just view it as an
opportunity to exchange views.''
   Topics discussed were the economy; a date for general elections,
which will turn Hungary into a full-fledged parliamentary democracy
for the first time since the Communist coup in 1948, and how the
new parties can become involved in the decision-making process.
   Government spokesman Zsolt Bajnok made it clear there was no
discussion on transforming the present Cabinet into a coalition
government.
   ``The idea was not even raised,'' he said.
   Friday's talks opened a three-day series.
   Toelgyessy told reporters, ``Every time the government is in
trouble it talks about involving the opposition. In no way are we
going to assume even partial responsibility for this economic
fiasco.''
   While not thinking in coalition terms, the government was
hoping, Bajnok said, for ``political legitimation of government
decisions.''
   Bajnok told reporters the opposition parties assured Premier
Miklos Nemeth it would not exploit Hungary's difficulties for
short-term political gain and ``several promised to support the
government in its hard decisions.''
   Nemeth told them his government is not using the talks as a
device to save itself. ``The situation is much too serious for such
games,'' Bajnok quoted him as saying.
   Hard decisions that lie ahead include an austerity budget to be
submitted to Parliament this month and possible bankruptcy
proceedings against unprofitable enterprises, which will abruptly
boost unemployment.
   Major debate also centered on a general elections date.
   The governing Hungarian Socialist Party, which has disavowed the
Communist monopoly on power and even changed its name, favors Feb.
28. The big opposition parties favor March 11 or 18. Many smaller
parties want Parliament to go full term, until June. Some even
proposed early fall to give them more time to prepare.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bulgaria 2dLd-Writethru a0673 12-08 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0673,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgarian Old Guard Dismissed From Party Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf `Among those' to CORRECT spelling of final name
to Papazov</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party expelled more of the
old guard from its leadership Friday, leaving the ruling Politburo
with only three members who were there when Todor Zhivkov was fired
as party chief Nov. 10.
   Removed were four full and two non-voting candidate members of
the Politburo and 22 full and four candidate members of the
policy-making Central Committee. Zhivkov was among those losing
seats on the Central Committee.
   The changes were made at an unannounced meeting of the Central
Committee, which also struck from the record of the Nov. 10 meeting
a passage expressing thanks for Zhivkov's leadership.
   Zhivkov ran Bulgaria in a rigid, Stalinist fashion for 35 years
and is under investigation for corruption.
   Among those losing their jobs were Pencho Kubadinski, chairman
of the Fatherland Front; Ivan Panev, first secretary of the Sofia
party organization; Yordan Yotov, chief party ideologist, and Nacho
Papazov.
   They were purged one day after the Federation of Democratic
Forces was established to press for economic and political reform,
including free elections.
   It includes 10 independent groups that arose recently and have
called for sweeping reforms in several mass demonstrations that
would have been unthinkable under Zhivkov.
   Still on the Politburo from the Zhivkov days are Petar Mladenov,
who was foreign minister and replaced Zhivkov as party chief;
Premier Georgi Atanasov and Defense Minister Dobri Dzhurov, who is
said to have played a crucial role in Zhivkov's downfall.
   The Politburo now has eight members, compared with 10 under
Zhivkov. The Central Committee has 185 full and 145 candidate
members.
   At a meeting Nov. 16, after Mladenov had replaced Zhivkov as
party leader, the Central Committee removed three members of the
ruling Politburo in favor of more liberal Communists.
   On Friday, Alexander Lilov, 56, was made a Politburo member and
secretary of the Central Committee, as was 57-year-old Belcho
Belchev, a former finance minister.
   Lilov had been a Politburo member and party secretary in
1974-83. Official media said he was dismissed in 1983 because of
his ``criticism of the personality cult'' of Zhivkov.
   Belchev lost his job as finance minister when Zhivkov abolished
the ministry two years ago, and became Bulgarian ambassador to
Yugoslavia.
   The Federation of Democratic Forces includes the independent
Society for Human Rights, environmental group Eco-Glasnost, trade
union Podkrepa, Society for Religious Freedoms, Club of the
Prosecuted, Independent Society of Students, Civic Initiative,
Bulgarian Social Democratic Party and Nikola Petkov, a a farm group.
   A statement issued Thursday in Sofia said it wanted ``to
coordinate efforts of individual associations in order to speed up
the processes of democratization.''
   It called for a multiparty system, the rule of law and a market
economy, equality of all forms of ownership, a new labor and social
law, independent unions, a law on strikes and a democratic
constitution.
   Other demands included free elections; removing the Communist
Party from the army and militia; political rehabilitation of those
unjustly prosecuted; a free, independent press, and a new approach
to the ethnic religious minorities.
   The federation is led by a council made up of three
representatives of each member group.
   Zheliu Zhelev, chairman of the Club for Supporting Glasnost and
Perestroika, is chairman of the council, and Petar Beron, a senior
member of Eco-Glasnost, is its secretary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
