<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     12-08 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombing Death Toll Rises to 59</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers found seven more bodies in
rubble left from the bombing of the federal investigative police
headquarters, raising the death toll Friday to 59 from the
terrorist attack blamed on drug lords.
   Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, commander of the investigative police,
said Pablo Escobar and Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, two chiefs of the
Medellin cocaine cartel, were responsible for the bombing that
shattered a block of buildings in downtown Bogota.
   Hospital authorities said Friday 800 people were seriously
injured in Wednesday's explosion and scores of others suffered
minor injuries.
   The death toll was expected to rise with work crews finding
other bodies under the debris and some of the critically injured
dying.
   Maza told a news conference Thursday it is believed that Escobar
and Rodriguez Gacha had contracts with Spanish terrorists to
organize Wednesday's attack and the Nov. 27 bombing of a Colombian
jetliner that killed all 107 people aboard.
   He said one Spanish terrorist, suspected of being a member of
the Basque separatist group ETA, entered Colombia recently through
the port city of Cartagena. He did not identify the suspect or say
if the man was still in Colombia.
   ETA has been waging a violent battle, including hundreds of
bombings, for about two decades to win autonomy for the Basque
provinces in northern Spain. ETA in an acronym in the Basque
language for Basque land and liberty.
   Maza said police also have identified others suspects who loaded
a bus with more than 1,100 pounds of dynamite and detonated it in
front of the police headquarters. He did not elaborate.
   Maza was in his ninth-floor office at the time of the explosion
and escaped injury, but more than 50 policemen were among the
people killed or wounded.
   The bombing was the most deadly since the government began a
campaign against the traffickers in August after the killing of a
presidential candidate was blamed on drug lords.
</TEXT>
