<FIRST>r w AM-ThornburghTrip     12-08 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh Trip,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General to Visit Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will leave
Saturday for a six-day European trip to meet with law enforcement
officials in four nations about drugs and terrorism, the Justice
Department said Friday.
   ``One of my primary goals will be to urge our European partners
to take swift action to ratify the United Nations Convention
Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotics Drugs,'' Thornburgh said in a
statement.
   ``With the threat of increased drug problems in Europe, it is
important that the European community move swiftly to join us in
carrying the provisions forward to implementation.''
   Thornburgh will also discuss international efforts to combat
terrorism.
   The attorney general, who will be accompanied by FBI Director
William S. Sessions and Jack Lawn, head of the Drug Enforcement
Administration, will attend a conference of European law
enforcement officials in Paris.
   Beginning Monday, Thornburgh will meet with officials in
Ireland, Luxembourg, Britain and France. He will speak to members
of the British House of Commons during his stop in London on
Wednesday, the department said.
   On Friday, he is scheduled to meet with officials of TREVI, the
European community's organization of law enforcement agencies.
