<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-08 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wintry Storm Hits Central Atlantic States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A snowstorm covered the mid-Atlantic states and the nation's
capital on Thursday, entangling motorists on slush-slickened roads
and forcing officials to close schools and offices early.
   The band of snow mixed with sleet and freezing rain stretched
from Arkansas through North Carolina and Kentucky and into
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. Most accumulations were fewer than 5
inches.
   The storm was expected to linger into Saturday and could leave
up to a foot of snow across much of central Virginia, southern
Delaware and Maryland, and 8 inches in the Washington, D.C., area,
according to the National Weather Service.
   At 3 p.m. EST the snow cover near Washington included 5 inches
at Salisbury, Md., 3 inches at Baltimore and 2 inches at Andrews
Air Force Base and Washington National Airport.
   In Washington, the Office of Personnel Management told nearly
400,000 federal workers to go home early, sending waves of
employees home at 30-minute intervals throughout the afternoon.
   It was the first time the federal government has used the plan,
which is designed to help avoid traffic tie-ups.
   ``Traffic is moving more slowly because people are being
cautious, but we're not hearing of any real problems,'' Tara
Hamilton, a spokeswoman for Washington's public works department,
said during evening rush hour.
   The snow was the first of the season in Arkansas, where schools
closed Friday and utility crews worked to restore electricity to as
many as 24,000 people after ice and snow covered highways and
powerlines.
   Up to 3 inches of snow accumulated in parts of northern
Arkansas, and authorities said at least seven people died in
accidents on snow-covered highways.
   Snowfall over western Pennsylvania included 5 inches at Mount
Morris and Ohiopyle, 4 inches at Waynesburg and Marianna, and 3
inches at Somerset, Uniontown, Bedford and Johnstown.
   With up to 3 inches covering the Philadelphia area, secondary
and elementary public school students were sent home early, as were
students in Maryland and Delaware.
   In West Virginia, snowfall by midday included 4 inches at
Huntington, 3 at Charleston and 3 to 5 inches at Elkins. In
southern New Jersey, midday totals had reached 2 inches at the
Atlantic City Airport.
   Snow also extended over eastern and southern Ohio, eastern
Kentucky, western Tennessee and from northeast to south-central
Arkansas and northwest Louisiana. Snow was also scattered over
northwest Iowa.
   At noon, freezing rain extended from southeast Arkansas into
southwest Mississippi and over central Tennessee, western North
Carolina and southern Virginia.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 3.1 inches at Apalachicola, Fla., 2.1 inches at Savannah,
Ga., 2 inches at Ft. Stewart, Ga. and 1.6 inches at Beaufort, S.C.
   Cold temperatures moved into the northeast portion of the
nation. The low temperature for the nation Friday morning was 18
degrees below zero at Saranac Lake, N.Y.
   Reno, Nev., reached 66 degrees by midday, tying a 74-year high
temperature record for Dec. 9.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees at Caribou, Houlton and Limestone in Maine to 83 at West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
