<DOCNO> AP891208-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Ships     12-08 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Ships,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>39 Seamen Missing After Two Ships Sink</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFA, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Search vessels struggled through a
savage storm in the Gulf of St. Lawrence on Friday but found none
of the 39 seamen missing since two cargo ships sank in raging seas.
   Coast guard officials said the 400-foot Capitaine Torres and
270-foot Johanna B disappeared Thursday night in towering seas,
high winds and bitter cold about 120 miles apart and north of Cape
Breton.
   It said all of the 23 crewmen aboard the Capitaine Torres and 16
on the Johanna B were foreigners, including many Filipinos.
   Lt. Jeff Agnew at the search center in Halifax said the coast
guard ship Sir William Grenfell, battling waves as high as a
two-story building, had recovered two empty life rafts and the
wreckage of a third in the area where the Capitaine Torres
disappeared.
   Agnew reported, ``The captain of the Grenfell says he is
convinced he did see some people ... two or more'' on one of the
rafts ``but the wave action on the raft was severe. He saw it take
a few severe hits.
   ``When he managed to get alongside ... it was empty.''
   The Capitaine Torres ship had sent a distress call saying the
cargo had shifted, causing it to list badly, and its crew was
abandoning ship in enclosed rubber rafts about 36 miles north of
Cape Breton. The vessel carried two such rafts and two wooden life
boats.
   It was en route to Taiwan with container cargo and the crew
included French, Fijian, Dutch, Filipino and Vanuatu seaman,
according to maritime officials.
   The coast guard lost contact with the Panamianian-registered
Johanna B shortly after it sent out a mayday signal late Thursday
from a point 120 miles northwest of the Capitaine Torres.
   An agent in Sorel, Quebec, for the Johanna B said the ship had a
cargo of iron ingots and all of the crewmen were Filipinos.
   An Armed Forces' rescue aircraft dispatched to the zone where
the Capitaine Torres disappeared was diverted to the smaller
Johanna B with a pump. Military spokesman said the plane was
believed to be about 10 minutes away from the sinking ship when the
signals ended and it could find no traces of the vessel.
   The plane turned back when navigational aids began failing
because of an ice buildup.
   ``They didn't see anything,'' said Capt. Claude Tardif of
Canadian Forces Base Summerside. ``The visibility was about a
quarter of a mile in severe turbulence and icing conditions.''
   ``It was as bad a day as we've had this fall,'' said Wallace
Meade, owner of a 66-foot fishing trawler in Port aux Basques,
Newfoundland, the nearest port to the lost ships. ``I wouldn't have
gone out in that in a 500-footer.''
   Maritime officials said the Capitaine Torres, carrying cargo
from Portage, Ind., radioed a distress call after some containers
slid overboard in a violent shift of cargo. They said the Capitaine
Torres was built by Hyundai of South Korea in 1978 and flew the
flag of Vanuatu, but was owned by a company in New Caledonia, a
South Pacific island.
   The Johanna B was loaded with 4,600 tons of pig iron and en
route to Darrow, La.
   Crew members of the Grenfell and other coast guard ships
returned to work in spite of a month-old strike by civilian
employees of federal government ships.
   The strikers had said they would respond to emergencies.
Civilians in the Grenfell crew left the picket line beside the ship
and went aboard when the distress calls came in, said union
spokesman Larry Welsh.
</TEXT>
