<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-American     12-08 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-American,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Examination of Jailed American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Friday ordered prison
authorities to allow an American tourist facing drug charges to
confer with his lawyer privately and be examined by a psychologist.
   Judge Shaik Daud Ismail of the High Court was responding to
applications by Kerry Lane Wiley, 37, of Sacramento, Calif.
   Wiley was charged Nov. 12 in Magistrate's Court with trafficking
in more than a pound of cannabis _ the plant family of hashish and
marijuana _ at a house in the Damansara Heights district.
   On Dec. 1, the Magistrate's Court rejected Wiley's applications
on grounds it had no jurisdiction to order prison authorities to
allow an examination by Kenneth A. Moselle, an American
psychologist practicing in Malaysia.
   Defense lawyer Karpal Singh submitted the applications on
Wiley's behalf. He said his client taught computer programming at a
college in Hawaii and was arrested while visiting a friend in Kuala
Lumpur.
   Singh said it was it was imperative the psychologist examine
Wiley so he could use the report at his trial if necessary.
   Wiley is the first American charged with drug trafficking in
Malaysia, which is punishable by death.
   The charge is described as ``tentative'' until the attorney
general decides on the actual section of the law to apply.
   Since Parliament passed the tough drug law in 1975, 244 people
have been sentenced to death. Eighty-one have have been hanged,
including two Australians and a Briton, and the others await
appeals or execution dates.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad describes the drug problem as
the country's ``No. 1 enemy.''
   Malaysia has 140,000 registered drug addicts in a population of
17 million, but officials say only 20 percent or fewer of all
addicts are registered.
</TEXT>
