<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Torture     12-08 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Torture,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Group Deplores Use of Torture in Turkey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City bar association said in
a report released Friday that torture has been commonly used in
Turkish police stations and the Turkish legal system failed to
respond to it.
   The 111-page report said torture remained widespread despite
Turkey's ratification of the European Human Rights Convention and
the U.N. Convention against Torture, as well as prohibitions
against torture in Turkish law.
   The findings, ``Torture in Turkey: The Legal System's Response''
were prepared by a delegation of four lawyers from the
association's Committee on International Human Rights.
   Turkey had no immediate response. In the past, government
officials denied torture was practiced systematically, saying there
were only isolated incidents described as police brutality.
   The delegation said it visited Turkey from May 28 to June 8 and
met judges, government officials, prosecutors, lawyers, former
prisoners and detainees.
   The report said torture is often used during the 15-day period
in which prisoners can be held incommunicado after arrest.
   The bar association said forms of torture used include beating
detainees on the soles of their feet, hanging them by their wrists,
hosing them with cold water, applying electric shocks, punching and
kicking, yanking people by the hair, assaults with truncheons,
rolling the detainee inside a tire, and sexual and psychological
abuse.
   The delegation said it was told 84 people died in custody in a
military prison in southeastern Diyarbakir province during 1980-84,
reportedly as a result of torture, but only one police officer was
prosecuted.
   The report also accused the United States of failing to
recognize the seriousness of the human rights problem in Turkey.
The two countries, both NATO members, have a defense accord.
</TEXT>
