<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Shootings 3rdLd-Writethru a0720 12-08 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Shootings, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0720,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Against Women Lamented in Shooting Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS eight grafs with neighbors' comments on gunman's lifestyle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts expressed concern Friday that the
rampage by a man who shot to death 14 women might not be an
isolated case of such attitudes toward females, and especially
feminists.
   Television talk shows and newspaper editorials focused on the
massacre Wednesday, the worst in Canada's history. Thirteen people
remained hospitalized Friday. All were expected to recover.
   The gunman, identified by police as Marc Lepine, 25, emerged as
a loner who blamed women for his troubles in life. Lepine shot
himself to death after his assault at the University of Montreal's
engineering school.
   All the victims were between the ages of 21 and 31, and all but
one were students. A joint funeral for 10 victims was scheduled
Monday at Montreal's Notre Dame Cathedral.
   ``The tragedy should persuade us to look intensely at the ground
in which hatred takes root,'' Toronto's Globe and Mail, which
describes itself as Canada's national newspaper, said in an
editorial. ``It is time for men to talk with men about their
continuing oppression of women. Sadly, it is still a time when
women have reason to be afraid.''
   Michael Kaufman, a political scientist, blamed the incident in
part on society.
   ``It was both aberrant and not aberrant,'' Kaufman said on the
CBC's ``Midday'' program. ``These attitudes are bred so young. ...
Boys learn to solve conflicts through violence.''
   A conflict recently attracted national attention at Queen's
University in Kingston, Ontario, when female students staged a
```No' means no'' campaign against date rape. Male students
responded by posting sarcastic signs as ```No' means more beer.''
   Witnesses to the attack Wednesday quoted Lepine as screaming ``I
want the women!'' and ``You're all a bunch of feminists! I hate
feminists!''
   Six women died in one classroom after Lepine separated the men
from the women and opened fire on the women.
   A three-page handwritten letter found on Lepine's body blamed
women for much of his unhappiness.
   Jacques Duchesneau, a senior police investigator, said that when
things weren't going well with a woman, ``he would just stop the
relationship right there and never come back to the person he was
talking with.''
   Duchesneau said Lepine had taken chemistry courses apparently in
hopes of entering the engineering school, although no indication
exists that he applied. ``He said feminists have always ruined his
life, that he wasn't too happy in life particularly in the last
seven years,'' Duchesneau said.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and his wife, Mila, were among the
visitors Thursday night to the engineering school, which closed in
mourning and postponed final examinations for four days.
   ``This man singled out women in a completely criminal and
insensitive fashion,'' he said. ``It is an isolated incident, but
it raises questions about violence in our society and about
violence against women.''
   Police said Lepine had been obsessed by war movies and
apparently browsed regularly at gunshops. He bought his weapon, a
.223-caliber semi-automatic rifle, at a hunting shop Nov. 21.
   Lepine lived in a second-floor apartment on a narrow,
working-class street in central Montreal.
   Neighbors described him as a man always in a hurry.
   ``He was always running up and down the stairs,'' said Gerard
Claveau, 67, who lives with his wife next door to the Lepine
apartment.
   ``He didn't strike me as a normal person. He had these strange
eyes, sort of cold.''
   Another neighbor, Chantal Dumais, said she often had the feeling
someone in the Lepine apartment was watching her through a window.
She said once when she was changing in her bedroom she realized
someone was peering into her room from Lepine's apartment. She said
she then heard someone ``laughing like crazy.''
   Neighbors said Lepine lived with another man who apparently
moved out of the three-story building about a month ago.
   Claveau said Lepine's mother, who lives nearby with his sister,
used to visit her son's apartment a couple times a month.
</TEXT>
