<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Lennon     12-08 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Lennon,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students at `Lennon Wall' Ask Leaders to `Give Peace a Chance'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people jammed the
narrow streets of Prague's old quarter Friday on the anniversary of
John Lennon's death to ask Communist leaders to ``give peace a
chance.''
   While party officials drew up a list of future government
officials in talks with the opposition across town, 5,000 young
people gathered for the annual ceremony honoring the former Beatle,
who was shot to death Dec. 8, 1980, outside his New York City
apartment house.
   Candles and sparklers shone in the frosty, clear night while
Lennon's lyrics echoed under the archway of beautiful Charles
Bridge: ``All we are saying, is give peace a chance.''
   Speakers read letters from throughout the country supporting the
peaceful democratic revolution that has embraced Czechoslovakia
since mid-November.
   The anniversary observance, illegal until last year, is held at
the ``Lennon Wall,'' a stretch of concrete once covered with
slogans extolling peace and the pop star.
   ``We believe Lennon was a fighter for freedom and that is what
we are doing here, too, is fighting for freedom,'' said 17-year-old
Madla Vacklova, whose little sister accompanied her.
   She said she believed in expressing her political beliefs ``and
this is something we can do here now.''
   Reforms taking place in Czechoslovakia are due in large part to
the young. A peaceful student demonstration Nov. 17 that ended in
police violence shocked the nation and inspired mass protests that
forced the Communist Party to negotiate with the opposition.
   The Lennon celebration has special meaning for young Czechs. It
was one of the first expressions of a desire for change by those
born after a Soviet-led invasion crushed the Prague Spring of
reform in 1968.
   On Friday, the mood was by turns festive and subdued. Dozens of
young soldiers could be seen, in groups of two or three, among
students in pastel parkas and wool coats.
   ``Last year on Lennon day, we were forbidden to leave the
barracks,'' said a 20-year-old sergeant, who would not give his
name. ``Also, to tell you the truth, this was under surveillance
and they were guarding the streets.''
   His comrade said: ``This year, it's all different. We want to
come with all the others to show our support for change.''
   On the bridge, above the crowd, small groups of people sang
Beatles songs, often accompanied by guitars.
   On the old King's Road, other young people sang Christmas carols
a cappella, as they have for as long as anyone can remember.
</TEXT>
