<FIRST>u a AM-CorporateSpy 1stLd-Writethru a0677 12-08 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corporate Spy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Claims Japanese Car Company Spied on American Family's Buying
Habits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Nissan denying claims. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, `The lawsuit ...; INSERTS 1 graf after 10th, `The newspaper...,'
to give more details of reax. A version moving on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple claims in a lawsuit that
Nissan Motor Corp. had a Japanese employee rent a room in their
home to spy on them and collect information about Americans' buying
habits.
   Nissan called the allegations ``totally absurd.''
   Maritza and Stephen French claim fraud, invasion of privacy,
trespassing and unfair business practices against Nissan and
Takashi Morimoto, a Nissan employee who rented a room in their
Costa Mesa home last summer.
   ``They just feel outraged,'' said Nancy Kaufman, the Frenches'
attorney. ``They just wonder what he was writing down, what about
their private lives is in a Nissan file somewhere. They feel
violated, they really do.''
   Nissan denied the couple's claims in a statement issued Friday
from its U.S. headquarters in Carson, Calif.
   ``Mr. Morimoto was very upfront with the French family about the
fact that he worked for Nissan and that he was in the U.S. to
better understand U.S. lifestyles and attitudes about cars,'' the
company said.
   Nissan said that not only was Morimoto not secretive, ``he was
plainly seen in the neighborhood photographing various cars, homes
and garages.''
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday in Orange County Superior Court,
seeks a court order forbidding Nissan from placing alleged
corporate emissaries into the homes of other unsuspecting families.
It also seeks unspecified damages.
   The lawsuit claims the 29-year-old Morimoto misrepresented and
concealed the reason for his six-week stay with the couple and
their two daughters.
   Ms. Kaufman said the French family responded in June to a
newspaper advertisement to find homes for Japanese students.
Placement services said no students were available but suggested
Morimoto, who moved in on June 16.
   Ms. Kaufman said the family knew Morimoto worked for Nissan but
thought he had been temporarily assigned to the firm's U.S.
headquarters in Carson.
   Morimoto stayed until July 31. The family learned of Morimoto's
alleged mission in October, when the Los Angeles Times reported
that Morimoto had been dispatched to Costa Mesa as part of an
effort to design a future car model designed especially for the
U.S. market.
   The newspaper article on Southern California car culture said
Morimoto was to ``unearth'' the lifestyle of an American town and
was among several ``operatives'' lured there by its trend-setting
image.
   In its statement, however, Nissan said the article ``was
actually sent to the French family by Nissan because we thought
they would enjoy it.''
   The lawsuit also named Makoto Tachikawa, a product strategy
director for Nissan, and two organizations involved in placing
Morimoto in the home, the Academic Recruit Communication
International of Los Angeles and the Japanese American Cultural
Center.
   A spokeswoman for the center said they were merely the landlord
for the other group. Terry Terasaki, an assistant to Gachiey
Nomura, the head of Academic Recruit Communication, said Mrs.
Nomura was out of town Friday and the only person who could discuss
the case in detail.
   Terasaki acknowledged that his organization placed Morimoto in
the Frenches' home, but said he had learned of the couple's
allegations for the first time Friday.
</TEXT>
