<FIRST>r a AM-Tinker-Gannett     12-08 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tinker-Gannett,0498</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Former NBC Head Grant Tinker Says Gannett Split Amicable ^By JAY
SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TV producer Grant Tinker, a former NBC chairman,
said Friday that the recent mutual decision of himself and Gannett
Co. to end their TV production partnership was amicable and ``just
as friendly as it could be.''
   The latter is a media company that publishes the USA Today
newspaper.
   GTG Entertainment, the Tinker-Gannett partnership, was formed in
1987. It produced the ill-fated ``USA Today on TV,'' which is
ending in January after 15 months, low ratings and a start-up cost
of $40 million.
   Gannett, Tinker said, ``just made a strategic decision that it's
(TV production) a business that they would just as soon not be in,
since it's not connected to what they do.
   ``And the fact we did not come out of the gate too quickly
probably helped them make (the decision).''
   GTG currently produces one network series, ``Baywatch,'' which
NBC recently approved for a full season.
   It also has gotten got CBS approval for a pilot for a comedy
series, ``Peace of Cake,'' and has three syndicated series in the
works, two of which probably would be shown at a national programs
convention next month in New Orleans, he said.
   Work on all those will continue, he said, while arrangements are
made for a new partner to replace Gannett. He said there have been
inquiries, but that nothing will be done ``until we can take
inventory.''
   He expects that process to be finished the middle of next week,
he said in a phone interview from GTG offices in Culver City, Ca.
   Tinker also said he doesn't want to return to network life, but
that two top producers considered to head CBS' programs department
would be ``great for CBS.''
   He referred to the team of Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner, whose
Carsey-Werner Co. produces network television's two top-rated
series, NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and ABC's ``Roseanne.''
   Until late Friday, when their negotiations with third-place CBS
ended unsuccessfully, they were being wooed by it to run CBS
Entertainment, the network's top programs job. The post was left
open last week when Kim LeMasters resigned after only two years in
it.
   Tinker, who spoke before the negotiations were called off, had
said he hoped the two executives would join CBS ``because I think
that would be great for CBS, and for those of us who want to do
business with CBS.''
   Credited with helping lead NBC to first in prime time ratings
before he left the company in 1986, Tinker laughed when asked if
CBS at some point had asked him about taking over LeMaster's job.
   ``Oh, no,'' he replied, then in a joking reference to his old
chairman's job at NBC, said, ``Hey, you're demoting me.'' He said
he had no desire to return to network life, ``nor was I asked'' to
by CBS.
</TEXT>
