<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0683,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Speaks of Chance for Peace `Rich With Promise of Permanence'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 10-13 bgng: `Bush has,'' with Des Moines comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush spoke glowingly Friday of improving
relations with the Soviet Union, saying his summit meeting with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was aimed toward peace ``rich
with the promise of permanence.''
   ``Yes there were differences at Malta,'' he said. But he added,
``We can express them in an agreeable and forceful way without
being disagreeable.''
   Bush made his remarks at a fund-raiser for Rep. Hank Brown, a
Colorado Republican running for the Senate.
   The president's comments about U.S.-Soviet relations were upbeat
throughout, with no mention of his negative comments the night
before when he told a Houston audience that Soviet activities with
Cuba and Nicaragua ``weigh heavily'' on the relationship.
   Bush said he envisions the decade of the 1990s as ``filled with
optimism, hope and a sense of new beginnings.'' And he heralded
``new beginnings as democracy blooms behind what used to be called
the Iron Curtain.''
   Earlier this week, a senior administration official, commenting
anonymously, had characterized Gorbachev's economic views as
``simplistic.'' And Vice President Dan Quayle had made remarks less
rosy than Bush did on his return from the summit.
   However, presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater quickly
disavowed the ``simplistic'' quote on behalf of the White House.
   And Quayle said in an interview with the Soviet newspaper
Izvestia, released Friday, that he regarded the summit as a ``very
positive'' meeting that could lead to conclusion of an agreement on
strategic nuclear arms by next summer.
   ``So we're very hopeful for improved relationship, for new
opportunities for reduction of tensions,'' Quayle said. He added,
``But as we are hopeful, we must also maintain our preparedness,
and that we will do.''
   Bush has used his series of speeches at Republican fundraising
events over the past two days to reflect on his summit meeting with
Gobachev.
   In Des Moines, Iowa Friday night at a fundraising banquet for
Rep. Tom Tauke, a 1990 Senate contender, Bush said, ``From Malta
came initiatives to nurture Europe's tide toward democracy,
accelerate arms control, and expand trade.''
   He reiterated his goal of granting the Soviet Union
most-favored-nation trade status by the time he and Gorbachev meet
next spring in the United States.
   ``This will relax trade barriers between East and West _
expanding markets for American agricultural and other exports,''
Bush said.
   In Denver, Bush said, ``Our mission to Malta was about peace.
Not the kind of uneasy peace we've known for the last 40 years _
hard and cold _ but about the new kind of peace we aspire to. One
that is rich with the promise of permanence.''
   He spoke of his hopes for ``a new American-Soviet relationship.
We took our first step toward the next decade and the new world
that is taking shape _ a new world of security and freedom.''
   Bush also issued a written statement noting the earthquake that
devastated Soviet Armenia a year ago Thursday.
   Recalling the assistance provided by U.S. government and private
groups, and the Soviet offer of help after this year's San
Francisco-area quake, Bush said, ``As we look to a new era in
U.S.-Soviet relations, we can take hope from these examples of
humanitarian cooperation between our two countries.''
</TEXT>
