<HEAD>Students Think Bush Should Do More in War on Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students who met with President Bush on Friday say
the president could be doing more in his war on drugs. Some of them
also disagreed with his stands on abortion and women.
   But they were all impressed that the president took time to sit
down with them and listen to what they had to say.
   Anna Valdez said she asked Bush about abortion, and accused the
administration of cutting back social programs. She said the Bush
administration should be doing more to provide child care.
   Valdez said Bush favored the right of parents to choose child
care, but did not favor a government program.
   ``I don't see the logic of his policy at all,'' said the John F.
Kennedy High School senior. ``If he's pro-life, then he should
support head start and other programs for children who already
exist.''
   Bush, on a three-state, two-day trip in which he was mixing
anti-drug speeches with Republican fund-raising, met privately with
a group of about two dozen students.
   Alex Kennaugh, a junior, said he asked the president what he
would do if he were leading the drug war in Colombia, and the
president responded that he would try to halt the export of drugs.
Kennaugh said he agreed, but thought the administration could do
more to educate young people about drug dangers.
   Hector Sanchez said he told Bush that the administration is
focusing on drugs such as cocaine, crack and a new cocaine
derivative called ``ice,'' but is getting away from fighting one of
the most abused drugs at the school, alcohol.
   ``Kids are being killed because of alcohol,'' Sanchez said.
   Sanchez said Bush denied overlooking alcohol, and told him the
administration is doing what it can.
   Bush later left Denver for Des Moines, where about 20
schoolchildren stood out in cold in the mid-20s Friday night to
watch the arrival of Air Force One.
   The pupils from Andrew Jackson Elementary School said they found
their glimpse of Bush ``neat,'' ``fun'' and ``interesting.''
   Bush was in Iowa for a radio discussion with farmers and a
political dinner for Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa.
