<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Castro-Reform     12-08 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Castro-Reform,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro Says East Europe's Winds of Change Not for Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro rallied
Communists around the world to defend socialism against the East
bloc reforms, which he said could only hurt Cuba's economy, an
official Cuban report said Friday.
   He said capitalism was gaining unusual strength in socialist
countries but rejected it as a means of solving Cuba's problems. He
said it would mean a loss of sovereignty and independence,
declaring, ``We would be an extension of Miami.''
   Some Eastern European countries have teams of Americans
programming their capitalist development, Castro said in his speech
late Thursday.
   Castro spoke for nearly an hour at funeral services for more
than 2,000 Cubans killed abroad over the past 14 years, most of
them in Africa, the Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina said
in a dispatch monitored in Mexico.
   If destiny assigns Cuba the role of being one of the last to
defend socialism, ``it will do it down to the last drop of its
blood,'' Prensa Latina quoted Castro as saying.
   He said his speech was directed ``to those who think we will not
be able to resist the changes that are occurring in Europe.''
   ``We can only expect negative consequences for the economy of
the country'' from the changes, he said. He did not elaborate.
   The Cuban president contrasted Cuba's socialism with that of
Eastern Europe, saying, ``Socialism did not arrive here through the
victorious divisions of the Red Army, but was forged with the
heroism of the Cubans.''
   Prensa Latina said he described as repugnant articles in the
Soviet press criticizing the Soviet system. Cuban authorities did
not hesitate in blocking circulation of the publications, he said.
   Castro spoke after Cubans lined up for hours for a silent
procession past the coffins of soldiers and civilian technicians
killed in Angola, Ethiopia and other African conflicts.
   Most workers were given the day off to attend the services in
five cemeteries and more than 160 mausoleums built for the war
victims.
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of Angola and government
representatives from Ethiopia attended the ceremonies.
   The government said this week that 2,289 Cubans were killed in
the conflicts, 2,016 of them in Angola. The remains of all but
about 100 were returned to this island nation and sent to their
hometowns.
   More than 400,000 Cubans have taken part in Cuban missions
abroad, mostly in Africa. At the peak of the Angolan war, Cuba had
50,000 troops and civilians there.
   Cuba agreed to withdraw all troops from Angola by 1991 under an
agreement negotiated by Chester Crocker, former U.S. assistant
secretary of state for African affairs. Cuba no longer has troops
in Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
