<FIRST>r a AM-SalvadoranCoffee     12-08 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvadoran Coffee,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hills Bros. Suspends Salvadoran Coffee Purchases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hills Bros. Coffee, the nation's
third-largest coffee distributor, announced Friday it has suspended
for 30 days any new deals to buy coffee from El Salvador .
   The San Francisco-based marketer of Hills Bros., MJB and Chase &amp;
Sanborn said the decision came in the wake of ``deep concern''
expressed by consumers about fighting and rights violations in El
Salvador during recent weeks.
   In Cincinnati on Friday, peace activists urged Procter &amp; Gamble
Co. not to buy coffee from El Salvador as part of an effort to
pressure the Salvadoran government to negotiate a settlement to
that country's civil war.
   The food products giant, which said it purchases just 3 percent
to 5 percent of its coffee from El Salvador, refused.
   ``We don't make foreign policy decisions for the United
States,'' said P&amp;G spokesman Donald Tassone. ``Right now, the
United States has an open trade policy with El Salvador, and we're
following that policy by buying some coffee beans from El Salvador
for our blend.''
   In San Francisco about three weeks ago, a group called Neighbor
to Neighbor called for a boycott of Salvadoran coffee, a $200
million cash crop to the Central American country that accounts for
about 5 percent of the coffee consumed in the United States.
   Hills Bros. spokeswoman Laurie Chase said Hills Bros. and its
parent company, Nestle, met with Neighbor to Neighbor
representatives to discuss the Salvadoran situation and agreed to
suspend coffee purchases from that nation while more closely
examining the situation.
   Chase did not have figures to indicate the amount of coffee
purchased from El Salvador by Hills Bros., but said it wasn't ``a
significant amount at all.''
   More than 70,000 lives have been lost in violence in El Salvador
during the past decade. Six Jesuit priests were murdered there
about a month ago. About 80,000 Salvadoran refugees live in the San
Francisco Bay area.
</TEXT>
