<FIRST>r a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0679 12-08 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hispanics Organize To Help Lozano; Clergy Call for Healing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Lozano comments,
clarify that money is being raised for his appeal. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
WOCN scheduled...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hispanic community launched a drive Friday to
raise money on behalf of a Colombian-born policeman convicted of
killing two black men, while religious leaders declared a weekend
of prayer to unify the races.
   Black leaders have hailed the manslaughter conviction of Miami
Officer William Lozano, 31, as a victory for justice. But many
Hispanics, particularly those in the 200,000-strong Colombian
community, say the officer was a scapegoat to racial politics. The
deaths of the two black men touched off three days of rioting in
January.
   Colombian-oriented radio stations WOCN-AM and WKAT-AM have
organized drives to help the officer and his family. Lozano's
tearful mother went on the air Friday morning to ask for help in
paying legal expenses for his appeal.
   ``My son, to everyone who has always known him, wouldn't hurt or
kill anyone without reason,'' she pleaded. ``We need money.''
   Lozano himself took to the airwaves on Spanish-language
television Friday evening, saying he was a symbol for police
officers around the country.
   ``It's now my duty as a police officer in the situation that I'm
in, to protect the civil rights of all policemen who are patrolling
the streets,'' he said, adding that he was publicly fighting his
conviction ``so that they can enforce the law the way they should
be able to.''
   WOCN scheduled a radiothon and rally at noon Saturday to raise
funds and seek signatures on a petition asking Circuit Judge Joseph
Farina to show leniency when he sentences Lozano on Jan. 24. Lozano
and his family are expected to participate in the broadcast, said
afternoon news coordinator Fernando Escobar.
   To help heal the wounds between blacks and Hispanics, a group of
Jewish, Protestant and lay religious leaders held a joint news
conference declaring a weekend of prayer for the families of Lozano
and the shooting victims, Clement Lloyd and Allan Blanchard.
   ``I think the worst thing we can do as a community is to sit
back smugly and say we came through this time without fires and
riots,'' said Rabbi Solomon Schiff, chairman of Dade County's
Community Relations Board.
   He also called for new economic programs, including asking
businesses to hire blacks in proportion to their numbers in the
community.
   The Rev. Vane Eubanks, a black minister and president of People
United to Lead the Struggle for Equality, said impromptu
celebrations after Thursday's verdict celebrated a victory for
justice, not the conviction of Lozano.
   ``We are not a bloodthirsty lynch mob out to get someone,''
Eubanks said, adding even an acquittal would not have caused a riot
because the black community could see the trial was conducted
fairly.
   Roman Catholic officials, who represent a largely Hispanic
following, did not attend the news conference. However, Mary Ross
Augusta, a spokeswoman for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami,
said church officials had been in contact with the Community
Relations Board and parish priests intended to speak out on the
issue of racial unity this weekend.
   Remarks by some Hispanic leaders, however, suggest they will not
be easily appeased.
   ``We are deeply hurt,'' said Hernando Torres, executive
secretary of the Colombian American Political Action Committee.
``We are convinced that Officer Lozano was doing his duty defending
the community.''
   Although Colombians have led the drive to support Lozano, many
in the larger Cuban-American community see the verdict as a blow to
all Hispanics.
   ``Mr. Lozano, being Latin, was sacrificed to appease a segment
of the community, to prevent riots and burning,'' said David Duenas
Sr., a retiree who said he closely followed the trial.
   Others supported the outcome, saying the trial was fair.
   ``The Hispanic community is mature,'' said Jorge
Hernandez-Torrano, president of the Cuban American Bar Association.
``Its immediate reaction _ sympathy for Lozano _ is natural, but
that will pass.''
   Many police officers _ especially Hispanics _ say they are
dismayed by the verdict, but will not give their names for fear of
retaliation by police officials.
   One said he would be reluctant to enter a threatening situation,
as Lozano did when he stepped into the street and fired a shot at
the motorcycle Lloyd and Blanchard were riding.
   ``I might have to do something _ and I might wind up where
Lozano was today,'' said the officer.
   But police spokesman David Rivero said many officers were
reacting in the heat of the moment.
   ``Any time you're faced with something like that, at first
you're going to be emotional, but after a while things get to
normal,'' Rivero said.
   Since the Jan. 16 shooting, which touched off three days of
racial violence, Lozano has been relieved of duty with pay.
Following his conviction, an administrative hearing was initiated
on possible dismissal, but no decision was expected this week, the
department said.
</TEXT>
