<FIRST>r a AM-WoodShooting     12-08 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wood Shooting,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunter Indicted for Manslaughter in Woman's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hunter who was spared criminal
prosecution when a grand jury refused to indict him in the 1988
shooting death of a woman near her house was indicted for
manslaughter Friday by another grand jury.
   Donald Rogerson was charged in the death of Karen Wood, a
37-year-old mother of young twins who was shot in woods behind her
house in Hermon, a Bangor suburb, on Nov. 15, 1988. The case has
stirred strong emotions among hunters and non-hunters alike in a
state known as a hunting haven.
   Rogerson, a supermarket produce manager and an experienced
hunter, has said he believed he was firing at a deer. Mrs. Wood
died of a single gunshot wound to the chest.
   Rogerson, 46, faces up to 20 years' imprisonment if convicted on
the charge of manslaughter, said Assistant Attorney General Jeffrey
Hjelm, who is prosecuting the case. There is no minimum sentence,
Hjelm said.
   No arraignment date was immediately set.
   Chief Deputy Attorney General James T. Kilbreth, explaining why
the state took the case before a second grand jury, cited news
stories that raised questions about the fairness of the decision by
the first grand jury.
   Kilbreth acknowledged for the first time Friday that ``the most
important aspect'' of the decision to reopen the case was the
discovery that a nephew of Lewis V. Vafiades, Rogerson's attorney
in the case, had served on the first grand jury.
   However, he said there was only the appearance of a conflict and
an investigation by his office had turned up no evidence of any
wrongdoing. The nephew, Vasor Vafiades, has been quoted in news
reports as saying he did not take part in the case.
   Rogerson had initially been charged with manslaughter. But the
first grand jury refused to indict him, finding he had not been
criminally negligent or criminally reckless, and the charge was
dropped.
   Vafiades described Rogerson as ``disappointed, obviously'' at
Friday's grand jury action in Superior Court in Penobscot County,
site of the first grand jury hearing.
   Mrs. Wood's husband, Kevin, who has moved to Iowa with his two
daughters, said he was encouraged by the indictment and that grand
jurors who voted to indict had reached ``the only decision logic
and reason would allow.''
   Wood, who settled a wrongful death lawsuit against Rogerson in
May for $122,000, said the case should be viewed the same as any
other criminal proceeding, not as a case that pits hunters against
non-hunters.
   State law prohibits hunting within 300 feet of a residence. Game
wardens found that at the time of the shooting Rogerson was 306
feet from the Woods' house and 286 feet from a neighbors' house.
</TEXT>
