<SECOND>AM-Ship Grounding, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0695,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Two in Ship Grounding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The brothers ..., to CORRECT town to Bayou La
Batre, sted Bayou Batry.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers aboard a ship that rammed a fragile
coral reef pleaded innocent Thursday to federal charges of
operating recklessly and while intoxicated.
   The Oct. 25 grounding of the 155-foot Alec Owen Maitland off Key
Largo was the first of three groundings in the Florida Keys during
three weeks.
   State and federal investigators say the empty freighter cut a
200-foot swath through a reef.
   A grand jury Wednesday indicted Michael Anthony Bishop, 43, who
was at the helm, and crew member Jerry Alan Bishop, 40. Both face
misdemeanor counts of operating while intoxicated and operating in
a grossly neglient manner. Each count carries a maximum term of one
year and $100,000 fine.
   The brothers pleaded innocent Thursday and were released on a
$30,000 bond co-signed by their mother. As conditions for their
release, U.S. Magistrate Linnea Johnson ordered them to live with
their mother in Bayou La Batre, Ala.
   No diesel oil leaked from the Maitland's fuel tanks during its
27 hours on the reef four miles east of Key Largo, a popular diving
spot.
   The Coast Guard also filed charges against the captain, Duane
Goodwin, 37, and Michael Bishop. Coast Guard investigators said
Goodwin, the only person aboard licensed to navigate the vessel,
was asleep when the ship ran aground.
