<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0750 12-08 1031</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0750,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Wants to Go to Drug Summit Despite Colombia Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 5: ``And, Bennett,'' with later Bennett quote;
INSERTS graf 17: ``Four men,'' with six arrested in Des Moines; following
graf edited for transition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he hopes to attend an
anti-drug summit in Colombia in February despite violence there and
he vowed to send ``a message to those merchants of death'' who
traffic in narcotics.
   Bush commented after his drug policy director, William Bennett,
said recent bombings in Colombia have raised new concerns about
safety at the meeting site.
   ``You have to be concerned with everybody's safety in Colombia
these days. It's really very very rough,'' Bennett told reporters
aboard Air Force One as he accompanied Bush on a three-state,
two-day trip in which the president was mixing anti-drug speeches
with Republican fund-raising.
   Violence in Colombia could delay the summit, or even bring about
a new location for it, but ``the burden of proof is still on those
who would argue that you shouldn't go,'' Bennett said.
   And, Bennett said later, ``I think he'll go there.''
   Some White House advisers, and several key members of Congress,
have urged that a new site be found for the summit. But Bush, when
asked by reporters if he was still determined to go to Colombia,
replied, ``I'd like to.''
   The president, addressing students at John F. Kennedy High
School, said his support for Colombian President Virgilio Barco was
unwavering.
   ``Barco has decided, I don't care how much it costs. I don't
care about the threat ... I'm going to do something,'' Bush said.
And he declared it was vital that the United States stand behind
Barco and ``do what we can to support him in his effort.''
   Bush lashed out at ``thugs who plant a bomb outside an office
building,'' referring to the explosion earlier this week in Bogota
that killed 52 people.
   And, he told an assembly at the school, it was important that
there be united action to drive drug traffickers out of business.
``Let us send a message to those merchants of death. ... We are
going to defeat you,'' he said.
   The president was in Denver for the high school anti-drug rally
with members of the Denver Broncos football team. He also attended
a fund-raiser for Republican Rep. Hank Brown, who is seeking the
Senate seat being vacated by Republican William Armstrong.
   Several dozen demonstrators, many carrying signs protesting U.S.
policy in El Salvador, were outside both Denver events.
   Bush told his GOP audience that his summit last weekend with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was a ``first hopeful step
into a new American-Soviet relationship.''
   ``Our mission to Malta was about peace,'' the president said.
``Not the kind of uneasy peace we've known for the last 40 years _
hard and cold _ but about a new kind of peace. One that is rich
with the promise of permanence.''
   He spoke of ``new beginnings as democracy blooms behind what
used to be called the Iron Curtain.''
   Later, Bush stopped in Des Moines, Iowa, on his way back to
Washington to appear at a fund-raising dinner for Senate hopeful
Rep. Tom Tauke, his third such appearance in two days.
   Four men and two women were arrested for trying to disrup the
speech as about 300 people marched outside the hall to protest U.S.
policies in Central America. ``I'm trying to tell the government of
America to get out of El Salvador,'' one of the two women shouted
as she was dragged away by police.
   Bush also told a local radio station, WHO, that, while he would
work to end trade-distorting government farm subsidies worldwide,
``we can't unilaterally get rid of them while we're being kept out
of certain markets.''
   In a live interview, Bush called an elimination of all farm
subsidies, which former President Reagan had proposed by the year
2,000 _ a ``utopian vision.''
   A snowstorm in the East made Bush cancel plans to spend the
weekend at the presidential retreat in Camp David, Md. in favor of
returning to the White House.
   In Washington, meanwhile, a Pentagon official said Friday that
some Soviet military forces in East Germany have raised their alert
status, but the action apparently is only to protect their bases
and nuclear weapons.
   ``It's a self-protection measure,'' said the official, who spoke
on condition he not be named.
   In light of the political turmoil in East Germany, he said,
``they have taken increased security measures, but it is similar to
something we might do at our bases if there are problems nearby.
... They haven't moved their troops forward, and they aren't
preparing for battle.''
   As for the drug summit in Colombia, Bennett was asked why Bush
wanted to go to violence-torn Colombia.
   ``Barco is brave and courageous. George Bush is brave and
courageous. George Bush just admires the hell out of Barco. You
could see that in a meeting we had in the White House,'' Bennett
said.
   ``I know that if Barco says its important for the president to
be there, the president's going to do it unless it doesn't make
sense.''
   ``I haven't seen any hesitation on the president's part,''
Bennett said. But he added, ``One of the things you have to
consider is not just the security of the president, but the
security of a whole lot of people who go where the president goes.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that the White
House is not having second thoughts about Colombia ``but as Bill
says, we continue to evaluate the situation.''
   ``At the moment we think security could be provided and there
are still tentative plans to go. We keep evaluating the situation.
The Secret Service believes they can provide security for the
president.''
   The summit is an attempt to focus international attention on
drug trafficking problems in Colombia, Peru and Bolivia.
   Bennett said that Colombia's battle against drug lords has
``obviously gotten to (them) and they're fighting back very hard.''
   Bush was wrapping up a two-day visit to Texas, Colorado and
Iowa, combining stops for 1990 Republican Senate candidates with
anti-drug appearances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
