<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror adv08   12-08 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, adv08,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Dec. 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Elderly: Penalized For Working</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Retransmitting to fix key word</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By John CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of older people is growing but
benefits for the elderly may be heading in the opposite direction.
It is a situation with explosive potential.
   In some respects the position of the elderly today is in sharp
contrast to that of just a few years ago, when some studies warned
against inordinate gray power, or the success of the elderly in
lobbying Congress for greater benefits.
   In recent years private pension plans have attempted to cut
health benefits to the elderly, and the government began taxing
Social Security payments. Sharp increases in home equity, source of
security for the elderly, have been muted.
  e against them. Restraints on inflation have been
a plus for those on fixed incomes. Should hig Not all has gonh-level inflation
reappear, Social Security beneficiaries have some protection
through escalation clauses.
   But the big issues aren't easily resolved. Rising health-care
costs are endangering corporate benefits plans. Attempts to make
life easier for the elderly run headlong into whether it is fair to
tax youth for the cost.
   Particular problems apply to the handling of Social Security,
which many critics say is working on outdated assumptions.
   James Ivers, fits.
   Beyond those dollar limits, beneficiaries lose 50 cents on the
dollar.
   For a married worker-beneficiary, not self-employed, says Ivers,
it means the loss of 50 cents because of the income cutoff, another
15 cents to income tax and another 7.5 cents to Social Security
taxes, leaving just 27.5 cents.
   Next year, the maximum that beneficiaries can earn will go up to
$9,360, with benefits reduced by $1 for every $3 earned beyond the
limit. But that still amounts to a 33 percent tax, often on
relatively low wages.
   Ivers, who teaches Chartered Financial Consultants at the
college, which is based in Bryn Mawr, Pa., says informed estimates
exist that as many as 1 million working recipients now lose some
benefits because they incur penalties.
   He estimates that another 100,000 between ages 65 and 70 do not
file for any Social Security benefits because they choose to
continue working full time. Preliminary work has begun in Congress
to relax the restrictions against income, but no bill is
anticipated soon. Still, there appears to be strong sentiment among
some House members to get rid of all income restrictions.
   While the elderly did benefit from a falling income tax rate in
the 1980s, they lost benefits too, among them the extra exemption
that those 65 years or older had been receiving, and the freedom
from taxes on benefits.
   Basically, if a married recipient has an adjusted gross income
of more than $32,000, that recipient pays tax on half the benefits,
says Ivers. He observes that $32,000 can include earnings on
otherwise tax-exempt bonds.
   Additionally, says Ivers, ``I've always wondered why Social
Security is taxed twice; first, when a person pays the system, and
again when they receive the benefits.''
   As the law stands, he continues, there are more inconsistencies.
   He asks, for example, why a person who chooses to work and make
payments into the system until 70 years of age shouldn't receive
benefits for the extra payments.
   He wonders why those who were disciplined enough to save money
for their retirement should be penalized _ perhaps because their
investment income pushed them beyond the limits.
   Whatever the laws are, he said, ``all older people should be
treated equally with each other.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Dec. 8.</NOTE>
