<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Romania'sCeausescu Adv14   12-08 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania's Ceausescu, Adv 14,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Releasea Thursday PMs, Dec. 14 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Museum Reveals Extent of Personality Cult Around Romanian Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While displays documenting most of
Romania's 2,000 years of history are crammed into the bottom floor
of the National History Museum, the top story deals with only the
past 24 years _ the era of Nicolae Ceausescu.
   Much of the three hours of state television programming
available nightly is dedicated to singing the praises of the
``Supreme Leader.'' His wife Elena also receives her share of
adulation.
   The state-run newspapers, the only ones sold, often dedicate
more than two-thirds of their contents to the couple: what they are
doing on a particular day, Ceausescu's thoughts, or his importance
to the country.
   Posters of Ceausescu depicting him decades younger than his 71
years decorate offices, cultural institutions and shop windows,
while book stores give prominent displays to works by and about the
leader and his 70-year-old wife.
   At a time when democratic upheaval is sweeping away the last
vestiges of Stalinism in most other parts of the East bloc, a look
at today's Romania and the personality cult surrounding the
Ceausescus is like stepping back to the early 1950s. The Communist
Party maintains total control, and controlling the party is one man.
   The cult around Ceausescu, who assumed control in 1965, is
unequalled, except in North Korea, where Kim Il Sung, the
77-year-old ``Great Leader,'' receives orchestrated public homage
of near religious character.
   Efforts to show Ceausescu in a prominent light even lead
authorities to retouch photographs.
   A photo in some newspapers of Ceausescu visiting a shipyard in
the Black Sea port of Constanta earlier this year showed Politburo
member Emil Bobu in conversation with someone behind Ceausescu as
the president pointed to a mockup architectural project.
   For his irreverence _ not paying attention to Ceausescu _ Bobu
was air-brushed out of later published versions of the same picture.
   The Communist Party's 14th congress in November also served as a
showcase of orchestrated displays of affection for Ceausescu.
   Day after day, delegates rose to applaud and shout slogans _
``Ceauescu, Heroism, Romania, Communism'' _ as the president spoke.
They were silenced by an imperious wave of his hand.
   The suppression of dissent or complaints over years of food and
energy shortages by a powerful secret police has created an
atmosphere of fear. While most ordinarly Romanians are unwilling to
risk trouble by talking bluntly to Westerners about the country and
its leader, some do take the risk.
   ``I hope that when you come back,'' one told a departing
Westerner, ``we'll be all dancing at the funeral.'' His wink left
little doubt whose funeral he was talking about.
   A joke going around Bucharest has the same theme.
   A man asks a friend why he is reading the front page of
Scinteia, the Communist Party newspaper, so intently, when everyone
knows that the paper publishes little real news.
   ``I am looking for the obituaries,'' the friend replies.
   ``But they're on a inside page.''
   ``Not the one I'm looking for.''
   There's no trace anything like that in the 10 rooms of Ceausescu
memorabilia on the top floor of the Natural History Museum, a
chilly and dark 19th-century building on Calea Victoria.
   Few people were inside one recent day. Several shabbily dressed
attendants stood by luke-warm radiators or turned lights on and off
as three Westerners moved from room to room.
   Displays alternated by theme or country, but all had the
Ceausescus as a focal point.
   A gigantic illuminated tableau showed Ceausescu and his wife
with foreign dignitaries, including Presidents Nixon, Ford and
Carter. No Soviet leaders were in it, a reflection of long-standing
strains with the Kremlin.
   Scores of paintings, carpets or tapestries depicted Ceausescu or
his wife in a variety of heroic poses _ Ceausescu holding a scepter
with the Romanian tricolor swathed across his chest, for example,
or his wife with an aura around her head, suggestive of a halo.
   Other rooms had massive granite or marble busts of the
Ceausescus, along with expensive vases, pottery, crystal, a bull
elephant's head with massive tusks and other objects described in a
museum brochure as gifts.
   In display cases were medals on velvet pillows, including
Britain's Order of the Garter bestowed by Queen Elizabeth II in the
1970s, when Western nations praised Ceausescu's relative
indepedendence of Moscow and ignored his country's poor human
rights record.
   The medals and orders were ``bestowed on him ... as a sign of
our people's love and gratitude for its most loved son and the
Romanian president's deep respect and highest regard he enjoys all
over the world,'' said the brochure.
   In a prominent place was a certificate attesting that Mrs.
Ceausescu was an honorary citizen of Texas, along with one
bestowing the same honors on her husband from civic officials of
Fresno, Calif.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thursday PMs, Dec. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
