<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Dinnerat8 Adv11   12-08 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Dinner at 8, Adv 11,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to correct slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>TNT Airs Cable Version of `Dinner at Eight'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long before producers routinely scoured
newspapers for tragedies suitable for bad TV movies, there was a
thing called imagination. That once led to a a fine 1932 Broadway
play, ``Dinner at Eight.''
   Tonight, Ted Turner's TNT cable network is showing an elegant TV
version of that comedy-drama _ last made into a movie in 1933 _ by
George S. Kaufman and Edna Ferber, good writers who wrote a total
of six plays together.
   This ``Dinner,'' like the original, remains a comedy and tragedy
of manners, a series of vignettes about various folks, most rich or
formerly rich, coping with life while gearing up for a black-tie
dinner at a Manhattan townhouse.
   With a fine cast that includes Marsha Mason as the hostess, John
Mahoney as her husband, and Lauren Bacall as his old flame, this
edition is very much updated, with references to Pee Wee Herman,
Madonna, PBS and arbitrage.
   There also is a subplot about a hostile takeover of the ailing
husband's failing shipping company that his family has owned since
1873.
   Even the art of fashionable dining gets a contemporary line that
is tossed at the society hostess, a persistent giver of fashionable
dinners: `You people are like McDonald's for rich folks.''
   Sad to say, Tom Griffin's teleplay is only half good. That half
is the show's first half. There, you hear echoes of Kaufman's
acerbic wit, and that's welcome, even though the sting of the humor
tends to be softened by Ron Lagomarsino's direction.
   Alas, the second half takes on a bleak, humorless tone and
dwells far too much on a coked-out, alcoholic and over-the-hill TV
star (Harry Hamlin) who is the secret lover of Mason's engaged
daughter (Stacy Edwards).
   It may give a chance for Hamlin, from NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' to
strut his thespic stuff. But it only tends to lower the show to the
level of a routine TV drama about an actor suffering the twin
horrors of cocaine addiction and no TV series.
   And a fight between an oafish, rapicious Texas tycoon (Charles
Durning) and his dense, social-climbing young wife (Ellen Greene)
doesn't improve matters, either. It's merely nasty, nothing more.
   All this makes the earlier fun take a powder, just like Hamlin's
faded star. Those who expect Kaufman-like wit in this part of
``Dinner'' will feel like the guy who bought a pumpkin farm, then
learned Halloween is canceled.
   But let us count our blessing, even though we may be no good at
fractions.
   The chief blessing is Bacall, who in her youth was directed on
stage by Kaufman. She just about steals the show's good first half
as a breezy, sophisticated, dried-up novelist who is financially
tapped out and reduced to talk shows to remain known, but refuses
to cry the blues.
   When she blows into town and is asked by her old flame what tore
her away from her old European haunts, she just laughs. ``Haunts,
indeed. Everywhere you turn, it's Robin Leach and some anorexic.''
   Bacall tosses off this and other lines beautifully, with Mahoney
nicely underplaying things as her still-affectionate former beau.
   Greene, in a low-I.Q. part similar to the one she played as a
blonde in off-Broadway's ``Little Shop of Horrors,'' also does a
nice turn early on as the low-born lady who leaps at the chance to
meet people with ``historic manners.''
   It's too bad that the makers of this updated ``Dinner'' didn't
fully keep the spirit of its yesteryear _ taking serious things
lightly and light things seriously.
   But at least their effort gives you a few moments of wit, and,
thanks to Bacall, a classy reminder of how they did it in the old
days.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   YULE, HULA AND HOPE _ The Judds, Barbara Eden and The Associated
Press All America Football team will be on Bob Hope's NBC Christmas
show from Hawaii on Saturday, Dec. 16. Heisman Trophy winner Andre
Ware, quarterback of the University of Houston Cougars, and 1990
Rose Queen Yasmine Delewari also will appear on the show.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Dec. 11</NOTE>
