<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv11   12-08 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 11,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>More Taxpayer Bailouts Coming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The multibillion-dollar savings and loan
disaster is far from the only federal credit fiasco that has
occurred in the past few years, and more are likely to come,
according to a Reagan administration official.
   ``More bad news is on the way,'' said Ronald Utt in an article
written for today's Roll Call, a privately owned newspaper
circulated among members of Congress and influential government
officials.
   Utt, now a fellow in political economy at the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think tank, suggests it is only the
sheer size of the savings and loan bailout that draws attention
from other debacles.
   Current estimates are that the cost of refinancing the savings
and loan system will require $159 billion over 10 years, but
various critics have suggestd much higher figures.
   The first of the series of other collapses involved the Farm
Credit System, whose lending practices helped create an
unsustainable speculative boom in farm prices in the 1970s.
Restructuring the system cost several billion dollars.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. went next, at what
Utt claims will be an ultimate cost of hundreds of billions of
dollars. Then the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. lost more than $4
billion last year.
   The latest was revealed in September, when the General
Accounting Office reported that the Federal Housing Administration
had lost $4.2 billion in 1988, wiping out its reserves to support
$303 billion of insurance in force.
   Utt, former deputy director of the White House Office of
Management and Budget, said additional losses should be expected
because of the vast array of government lending programs, insurance
schemes and loan guarantees.
   ``Many of these programs suffer from high default rates, minimal
reserves, lax management and persistent losses,'' he said. He cited
the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., which insures pensions of 39
million private-sector workers.
   To date, he said, the PBGC has suffered cumulative losses
amounting to $4 billion, a figure he said could go higher.
   He observes that while the PBGC collects premiums, holds
reserves and obligates itself to cover failed systems, it has no
measure of the extent of liability for the trillions of dollars of
systems it has agreed to insure.
   Moreover, he continues, a recent inspector general report
accused the corporation of a variety of aministrative and
supervisory failings ``that jepoardize the fund, the taxpaper and
the pensioners.''
   Utt claims government-sponsored enterprises _ privately owned
lending institutions created by government to pursue public
purposes _ collectively expose the government to about $700 billion
in risk.
   He said some of these enterprises already are in trouble. One,
the Federal National Mortgage Association, has a little more than
$1 billion to support a mortgage portfolio of $95 billion and $140
billion in mortgage-backed paper.
   ``If FNMA were subject to the standards of solvency required of
a savings and loan, it would have been taken over by federal
regulators years ago,'' he said.
   Utt expressed the view that other taxpayer bailouts of unknown
magnitude, perhaps involving the Federal Housing Administration and
the Veterans Administration, might occur if property values fall
and default rates rise.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
