<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Diesel Adv11   12-08 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Diesel, Adv 11,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Down-Home Style: Aussie Rocker Boomerangs to American Roots</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3 of Dec. 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American-born Australian Johnny Diesel may
prefer Vegimite to peanut butter, but his brand of rock 'n' roll
sounds like it comes fresh from the U.S. heartland, not the Aussie
bushland.
   ``The roots of our music are the '50s and '60s ... what was
happening in rock 'n' roll, R&amp;B and Motown,'' Diesel said in a
recent telephone interview from Australia. ``It's a huge
influence.''
   Refreshingly low-tech, Johnny Diesel &amp; The Injectors mix good
ol' American rock and blues with forceful guitar attacks honed in
the geographic isolation of Perth in Western Australia.
   Musically mature beyond his 23 years, Diesel pleads guilty to
fanning embers of the American rock 'n' roll fireball blown
worldwide three decades ago. ``We're bound to sound American,
because that's where the blues began,'' he said.
   The band cut their well-received debut album, ``Johnny Diesel &amp;
The Injectors'' (Chrysalis), at an unknown studio in Memphis,
Tenn., not Melbourne, Australia. They relied on veteran hard rock
producer Terry Manning to give them just enough rope, Diesel said.
   Backed-up by a vocal saxophone, reliable bass and punchy drums,
Diesel attracted an international mix to match his own far-flung
origins: French-born Australian Bernie Bremond on saxophone;
Anglo-Australian drummer Yak Sherrit; and native Aussie Johnny
Dalzell on bass.
   Their name is derived from the mumbled, automotive double
entendres of a New Zealand Maori friend. And even it hearkens back
to the hard-driving innocence of American rock music in its infancy.
   ``It's still got some rough edges there _ more than rough edges
really,'' Diesel concedes. ``We like rockin' but we can also be
very tender.''
   Their message is aimed at listeners' emotions, not their
brainpower or political bent, he says. ``The basic ingredient is
the accessibility of the music. I want to give people goosebumps; I
don't want to get inside their brain and start kicking around, or
get on a pedestal and start waving a big stick.''
   Judiciously sharing the solo spotlight with Bremond, Diesel
maintains command with lightning-bolt guitar licks that could
jump-start a Frankenstein monster. And he dispenses original song
lyrics with a clear, rangy voice tinged at times with mainstream
rock influences and at others sounding a bit like Marlon Brando's
deranged colonel in ``Apocalypse Now.''
   But he isn't afraid to calm down, take a step back and turn
soulful.
   ``Listening to the album, on some tracks we sound like a bunch
of angry little brats, and in other songs we sound sort of like
40-year-old, mellowed-out Memphis musicians,'' he said.
   Born Mark Lisotte to American parents, Diesel traveled with his
family of nine in a Volkswagen van to and from his father's
itinerate sax gigs around the northeastern United States before
they packed up and headed down under when he was 9.
   A huge hit at home and popular in Europe, he made new waves in
the United States with American critics who likened him to John
Cougar Mellencamp and Bruce Springsteen.
   But to make it with American audiences, Diesel will have to keep
touring here. He recently concluded a North American-European jaunt
that featured stops in Canada, Washington, Chicago and familiar
haunts in Texas.
   ``We just kind of roll along, soaking up influences as we go
along like a sponge,'' he said. ``Europe is great and we loving
playing at home, but we really fell for Texas, which is kind of
like Western Australia _ hot, dry and flat.''
   Through nightclub smoke he might be mistaken for a youthful
James Dean _ with his ripped T-shirt and crew-cut look, and his
matinee-idol good looks may help draw an American audience to his
Midwestern style. Yet he doesn't want to lose touch with the basic
rock roots he reveres, styles that include B.B. King and Buddy
Holly.
   ``We've done gigs with bands whose wardrobe cases were bigger
than anything else they had with them. I couldn't see the point in
that,'' he said. ``Our image is who we are, not what we wear. And a
guitar is the ultimate accessory you could ever put on. You don't
need anything else.''
   A sophomore album is scheduled for the spring, but Diesel is
sure his hoped-for U.S. success won't be founded on studio work. A
pro by age 15, he has played countless gigs in nameless Australian
venues, and plans to continue traveling. ``I think touring is a
great thing, the only thing _ no matter who you're playing to.''
   Perth is by no means a small city, with a population topping
800,000. Still, Diesel calls it the most remote city in the world.
``The closest things to it are Africa and Asia, but it's nurtured a
lot of good bands,'' he said.
   But that isolation has its advantages, too, partly allowing the
band to build and retain some element of purity.
   ``We've been left to our own devices,'' Diesel said. ``No one
has ever told us what to do, what to where or what to look like.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Dec. 11</NOTE>
