<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:AirAmerica Adv14   12-08 1001</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Air America, Adv 14,1025</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Dec. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hollywood Recreating `Secret War' in Laos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAE HONG SON, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crippled C-123 lies on an
airstrip flanked by sandbagged bunkers, stacks of ammunition and
men in fatigues. Nearby, a field of colorful opium poppies can be
seen swaying in the breeze.
   Flying into this remote town ringed by jungled mountains seems
an eerie descent into the Indochina War _ and two decades back in
time.
   On closer inspection, however, the howitzer shells prove to be
of wood, the crashed military transport is a hollow fake and
110,000 silk and polyester flowers make up the field of deadly
``opium.''
   And the blue-eyed macho type running out of a fly-blown bar that
has just been skewered by a hunk of exploding airplane wing happens
to be actor Mel Gibson.
   Welcome to ``Air America,'' Hollywood's recreation of the
mayhem, political machinations and hell-raising known as ``the
secret war'' in Laos.
   In real life, Air America was an outfit owned by the Central
Intelligence Agency. In Laos, it supported the Vientiane government
and an army of CIA-paid Hmong tribals who battled the communist
Pathet Lao and their North Vietnamese allies.
   Grizzled veterans of past conflicts, and retired military pilots
from the war in neighboring Vietnam flew for this secret shuttle
service. They carried guerrillas, refugees, rice, ammunition and _
most controversially _ opium.
   The pilots were variously described as mercenaries, patriots and
``the finest bunch of airplane drivers that has ever been got
together anywhere.'' They flew _ and sometimes died _ by the motto,
``Anything, Anywhere, Anytime.''
   The film focuses on the relationship between two pilots, played
by Gibson and Robert Downey Jr., as they fight, drink and womanize
in a bizarre war that officially doesn't exist.
   ``We're not here so what you and I just saw didn't happen,'' an
obnoxious CIA man lectures Gibson who has vainly tried to rescue a
fellow pilot, Charlie, from a burning plane. Moments earlier the
film shows President Nixon announcing on television that the United
States was not militarily involved in Laos.
   ``It may not have happened to you, and it may not have happened
to Nixon, but it sure as hell happened to Charlie,'' Gibson snaps
back.
   Director Roger Spottiswoode said he hopes the finished product
will work both as an adventure film featuring aerial stunts and
darkish humor and one with some political undertones.
   Gibson plays an outwardly cynical veteran flier ``who has made
his uneasy peace with a world he knows is corrupt,'' the director
said. Downey portrays a younger man fresh out of Los Angeles (where
he had his helicopter license yanked) who balks at compromise and
rebels when he discovers he has been ferrying opium.
   Some Air America veterans have grumbled to the producers that
they would be depicted as a bunch of drug runners and that the
story of the secret war would be distorted. The CIA has had made no
comment.
   While an earlier, discarded script reportedly was studded with
black humor and sharp slants on the war, the political guts were
torn out of the final script and the pilots are portrayed as
heroes. The final version goes lightly on the official American
conduct of the war in Laos, which included extensive secret
bombing, a string of lies and the CIA's helping hand in the
marketing of opium for its hill-tribe allies.
   A great deal of effort, however, has gone into recapturing the
look and atmosphere of 1971 Laos.
   The filmmakers relied in part on the book ``Air America,'' by
Christopher Robbins, as well as archival material and interviews
with Indochina war veterans, some of whom have settled in Thailand
and took small parts in the film.
   Marhsaled for the movie was a force of 26 aircraft, some 1,700
crew and extras and a budget of $35 million.
   ``It gives one more respect for Dwight D. Eisenhower when he
launched D-Day,'' said producer Daniel Melnick, stalking the set
wearing a cap emblazoned with three stars and ``Maj. Gen. Melnick.''
   Northern Thailand was chosen for more than two months of
location shooting because of its close resemblence to neighboring
Laos. Some of the same tribal groups live on both sides of the
border and opium, from which heroin is refined, is still grown in
both countries.
   Award-winning production designer Allan Cameron dressed up
sections of Chiang Mai, the major city of northern Thailand, to
resemble the Laotian capital of Vientiane. Real bar girls were
brought up from Bangkok to the recreated White Rose, a pilot
hangout in Vientiane where the sexual acrobatics were as madcap as
the aerial ones.
   Mae Hong Son proved strikingly similar to Long Tieng, a
sprawling CIA-run base dubbed ``Spook Heaven'' by journalists that
mushroomed into the second largest city in Laos.
   Three hangars, a hospital, warehouse and operations center were
built at Mae Hong Son's once sleepy airport with the Thai military
providing the aircraft and extra pilots.
   As Downey arrives from the United States, a baseball bat slung
over his shoulder, Spottiswoode tries to capture the frenetic
activity of what was at the height of the war one of the busiest
airports in the world. A damaged light aircraft dangles by a cable
from a big Sikorsky helicopter while a C-123 taxies, a light
observation helicopter descends and medics rush a wounded Air
America pilot from a Huey chopper.
   A few hundred yards away Gibson slings a wounded refugee over
his shoulder and flees Pathet Lao troops who have burst into a
squalid refugee camp. A small charge set below dirt and coconut
husks bursts just ahead of him, and the take ends.
   The star of ``Lethal Weapon,'' ``Road Warrior'' and
``Gallipoli'' whips off his shirt, hands it to an assistant and
swings his naked torso into a waiting Mercedes Benz.
   Time for a lunch break from the secret war.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Dec. 14</NOTE>
