<FIRST>a a BC-The'80s-ByTheNumbers 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-By The Numbers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Statistical Look at a Changing America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS graf 8, ``America offers,'' to fix millions to thousands.
Leads b0796, sent Dec. 7.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The numbers tell the tale of a changing
America in the 1980s: more golfers and softball players, less
liquor and red meat, more opera, more imported cars, more mail,
more TV-watching, more prisoners. Higher blood pressure.
   Getting right to the most basic number: The Census Bureau
estimated the population at 246,900,000 as of Jan. 1, 1989. That's
up from the 226,545,805 tallied in the 1980 national headcount.
   These Americans can expect to live longer than their
predecessors. Life expectancy rose from 73.7 years in 1980 to 74.9
as of 1988, according to the National Center for Health Statistics.
   And the shape of those lives is changing, judging from a
snapshot of statistics spanning the decade. (Because of the time it
takes to compile them, some of the latest available statistics are
for 1986 or 1987.)
   On the vital statistics front, the number of marriages and
divorces both slipped slightly. Marriages were down from 2,390,300
in 1980 to 2,389,000 in 1988, while divorces declined from
1,189,000 to 1,183,000.
   The numbers of births and deaths rose. In 1980, there were
1,989,800 deaths reported and 3,612,000 births. In 1988, the deaths
figure stood at 2,171,000, and births at 3,913,000.
   Recreation boomed in the decade. Participation in softball grew
from 30 million people in 1980 to 41 million in 1987. In the same
period the number of golfers increased from 15 million to 21.7
million.
   America also offers more beauty parlors today _ up from 65,700
in 1980 to 73,300 in 1986.
   And for those needing a touch-up, there are also more bathrooms.
In 1980, one single-family home in four had 2{ bathrooms or more.
By 1987 that was up to 38 percent of such homes.
   Speaking of comfort at home, the share of single-family
residences with air conditioning was up from 63 percent to 71
percent.
   In less comfortable circumstances: During the 1980s the number
of people in American prisons skyrocketed from 329,821 in 1980 to
581,609 in 1987.
   At the same time, college enrollment grew only slightly, from
12,097,000 to 12,173,000. The average Scholastic Aptitude Test
scores for college-bound students over those same years rose from
424 to 430 in verbal skills and from 466 to 476 in math.
   In 1980, 17.6 million households _ less than one in four that
had a television _ were served by cable. Now more than half of TV
households have cable, the National Cable Television Association
reports.
   Not everyone is watching MTV, however.
   The number of opera performances increased from 9,391 in 1980 to
11,794 in 1987, with attendance rising from 10.7 million to 16.4
million.
   Symphony concerts declined slightly during the period, from
22,229 to 20,059, but attendance increased from 22.6 million to
25.1 million.
   The cost of mailing a letter, 15 cents in 1980, is 25 cents
today. But the rising price doesn't seem to have discouraged
letter-writing. The Postal Service carried 60.2 billion first-class
letters in 1980 and 82.3 billion in 1988.
   The value of new car imports rose from $16.7 billion in 1980 to
$47.8 billion in 1987, while exports of new cars edged up from $3.9
billion to $6.7 billion in the same period.
   Americans are drinking less liquor. Per-capita consumption fell
from 1.98 gallons in 1980 to 1.54 gallons last year. Even so,
significant increases were reported in sales of cordials and
flavored vodkas, according to the Distilled Spirits Council of the
United States.
   Consumption of red meat has declined from almost 157 pounds per
person in 1980 to just 144 pounds in 1987. Pork also plummeted,
from 68 to 59 pounds per person.
   But the Agriculture Department says Americans ate more fish, up
from 13 pounds in 1980 to almost 15 pounds in 1987. At the same
time, poultry consumption jumped from 50 to 62 pounds.
   Fresh fruit consumption also rose, from 86 to almost 99 pounds
each, and Americans are eating more vegetables, too, up from 73 to
79 pounds each.
   Despite healthier habits overall, American health indexes are
not all upbeat. The National Center for Health Statistics reports
that almost 123 of every 1,000 Americans had high blood pressure in
1986, up from 114 per thousand in 1980.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
