<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strict new financial standards took effect
that will force more than a third of the nation's savings
institutions to shrink or shut down if they can't raise new capital.
   Only 1,800 of the 2,900 S&amp;Ls have enough capital to satisfy the
requirement, prompting industry analysts to nickname Thursdays'
deadline ``Pearl Harbor Day'' because it coincided with the 48th
anniversary of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.
   The new rules were required under S&amp;L bailout legislation
enacted Aug. 9 and are considered the cornerstone reform of the
bill. The Office of Thrift Supervision published them Nov. 6.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators asked a judge to dismiss a
suit against them by the former owner of Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association, saying they can show Phoenix millionaire Charles H.
Keating Jr. was operating the thrift in violation of the law.
   Deals that the hearing is focusing on are ``literally just the
tip of the iceberg,'' James P. Murphy, an attorney for the Treasury
Department's Office of Thrift Supervision, told U.S. District Court
Judge Stanley Sporkin on Thursday.
</TEXT>
