<FIRST>r f PM-MoneyFunds     12-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Funds,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $431.4 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 469 money market mutual
funds fell $431.4 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said.
   The decline, to $367.14 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $660 million drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said
Thursday.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $368.23 billion in the week
ended Nov. 21, 1989.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 228 general purpose funds rose $319.6 million to $119.53
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds dropped $36.1 million to
$159.03 billion, and assets of 144 institutional funds declined
$714.9 million to $88.58 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.94 percent from 7.93 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 7.97 percent from 8.01 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
44 days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan associations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.37 percent as of Wednesday from 6.36 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.08 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.01
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.05 the
previous week. Yields were 8.04 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.07 percent; 7.98 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.01 percent;
and 7.99 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.01 percent.
</TEXT>
