<DOCNO> AP891208-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerCredit     12-08 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Credit,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indebtedness Posts Biggest Increase in 5 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.34 billion more in
consumer credit than they retired in October, posting the biggest
increase in net consumer debt in five months, the Federal Reserve
Board said.
   The Fed said Thursday that consumer credit advanced in October
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.7 percent, the sharpest
increase since a 7.3 percent gain in May, when credit rose $4.21
billion.
   Consumer credit outstanding had risen 2.3 percent in September,
which was revised upward from the 1 percent increase originally
reported. Net loan totals were adjusted from $606 million to $1.37
billion.
   Auto loans, which fell 3.2 percent in September after remaining
flat in August, grew by $1.1 billion, or 4.5 percent on an annual
rate, in October.
   But economists said that because of a lag in approving
applications and then reporting credit, the auto loan figures
reflected sales made in September, not October.
   ``The timing of credit and the sales often don't match up,''
said Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI-McGraw-Hill, a Lexington,
Mass., forecasting organization.
   ``There's really a rush to get cars into the sales column, but
if you sign an agreement to buy a car, you might not actually get
the credit for another week,'' she said.
   Automakers had reported that October sales of new cars and light
trucks were down 14.1 percent from October 1988 as incentives were
dropped and new-model sticker prices rose.
   But sales were robust in August and September as consumers were
lured by end-of-model-year incentives and fears of higher prices
for 1990 models.
   The category of debt that includes credit cards jumped to a 6.4
percent annual rate of growth from a 5.6 percent advance in
September. Total revolving debt rose $1.04 billion, compared to a
$904 million gain the previous month.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose
$1.23 billion, a 7.5 percent annual rate of growth, compared with a
gain of $1.2 million, or 7.3 percent, in September.
   Mobile home debts fell again, down $26 million or a 1.4 percent
rate of decline. These debts had fallen for seven consecutive
months until rising $53 million in September, 2.8 percent on an
annual rate.
   The various changes left total consumer debt in October at a
seasonally adjusted $707.7 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
