<DOCNO> AP891208-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 0240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PolishCableTV Bjt   12-08 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polish Cable TV, Bjt,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Company To Build Poland's First Cable TV System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut company has announced it will
build Poland's first cable television system in a $900 million
partnership with several Polish groups.
   Chase Enterprises of Hartford said Thursday it will have a 70
percent stake in Polska Telewizja Kablowa, or PTK, a cable
television system it will build and operate along with Poltelkab SA.
   Poltelkab SA, which will own the remaining 30 percent, is a
partnership comprising the Polish post, telephone and telegraph
company; Polish Radio and Television Productions Co.; and the city
governments of Warsaw and Cracow.
   Company Chairman David Chase, a Pole who fled the Auschwitz Nazi
concentration camp at age 14 during World War II, said it is the
first communications-related joint venture established under
Poland's December 1988 joint venture law.
   ``We view this as only the first of many projects we will
undertake with Poland and in other economically emerging Eastern
European countries,'' Chase said in a statement.
   The programming for the Polish system still is under
negotiation, but is expected to include a number of
satellite-delivered U.S. services, including CNN, ESPN and MTV, as
well as movie, drama and sports channels, Chase said.
   The announcement was another indication of the new business
opportunities that are opening up in Eastern Europe for Western
telecommunications businesses. Just this week:
   _Denver-based US West International announced it will build and
operate Eastern Europe's first cellular telephone system in Hungary
in a joint venture with Magyar Posta, the Hungarian postal,
telegraph and telecommunications organization.
   _US West also said Thursday it plans a joint venture to build a
fiber-optic cable telecommunications line across the Soviet Union
to link the Soviets with Japan and Europe. Other principals in the
project are the Soviet Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications;
Kokusai Denshin Denwa of Japan; Societa Finanziaria Telefonica of
Italy; British Telecom; OTC of Australia; Denmark's Great Nordic
Telegraph Co. and Telecom Denmark; and the Deutsche Bundespost
Telekom of West Germany.
   _San Francisco-based Pacific Telesis will have a 26 percent
interest in the Mannesmann Mobilfunk GmbH consortium that will
build and operate a second national cellular telephone system in
West Germany. The West German government operates the other.
Pacific will be partners with Mannesmann AG; Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank; Cable and Wireless PLC; Lyonnaise des Eaux;
and the National Associations of Electrical and Automobile Trades.
   Chase Enterprises' 20-year joint venture will provide cable TV
service to Poland's 8 million homes, with construction to begin
within months in Warsaw and Cracow on an 18-channel system that
will reach 1.8 million homes, Chase said.
   He said Poland currently has two television channels, each
broadcasting a portion of the day. He said about 90 percent of
Polish households have TV sets.
   Polish Ambassador Jan Kinast called the agreement ``yet another
proof that Poland, which has embarked on a new road of profound
political and economic change, is fully open to cooperation abroad.
The development of this specific investment is an important
reflection of the increasingly dynamic and expanding
Polish-American relationship.''
   Chase is a retail shopping center developer whose interests also
include radio and TV stations, cellular telephone and cable TV
systems, insurance and financial services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
