<FIRST>u f PM-Unemployment Bjt   12-08 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unemployment, Bjt,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whither Interest Rates? A Lot Depends On Employment Report Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be led after 8:30 a.m. release of report. Also on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slowing of the economy has some analysts
at odds over whether a recession is on the horizon and Federal
Reserve policy-makers looking to give the economy a boost without
exacerbating inflation.
   Whether the Fed will seek to nudge interest rates lower again
before the end of the year is the subject of much debate among
financial analysts, and most agree that today's unemployment report
from the Labor Department will heavily influence the Fed's course.
   Financial markets drifted Thursday as most traders awaited
today's data, the first comprehensive look at the economy's
performance in November.
   If job growth was sluggish, the central bank is expected to ease
its hold on credit for the sixth time since March in an effort to
spur the economy. A strong report likely will persuade the Fed to
hold tight and await further data on economic growth and inflation
as the year draws to a close.
   Analysts contacted in advance of the report's release were split
on whether it would bring an easing from the Fed.
   ``It will show that the general slowdown in the economy
continues, and in fact the Fed might want to ease further on these
numbers,'' said Kathleen Stephansen, senior economist at Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. ``The prime concern has shifted
away from inflation and onto the overall state of the economy.''
   She predicted the Labor Department would report an addition of
120,000-130,000 new non-farm payroll jobs last month, with the
civilian unemployment rate either holding steady at 5.3 percent or
perhaps climbing slightly to 5.4 percent.
   But Roger Brinner of DRI-McGraw Hill predicted the Fed would
``just hold tight'' if the report was in line with his company's
prediction of 125,000 new jobs last month.
   Brinner said the jobs number will be artificially deflated by
about 60,000 because the Labor Department's survey was taken in a
week in which Boeing Corp. workers were on strike.
   ``Our view is that the Federal Reserve is not pleased with
inflation,'' said Brinner, adding that the economy, while growing
at a slower pace, does not appear at risk of toppling into
recession.
   ``We're running in the middle gears right now and any further
downshifts to low, or as some people fear, reverse, are yet to
come,'' he said.
   Concurring with that view was Washington economist Michael
Evans, who predicted the report would show 150,000 new jobs last
month.
   ``I think the Fed is just going to sit tight,'' Evans said.
``The economy has pulled out of whatever was ailing it at the
beginning of the year and inflation is still rearing its head. If
growth and inflation are both up, that's not when you ease.''
   The October report was comparatively strong, with the government
reporting the creation of 233,000 jobs in the non-farm sector. For
the past six months the month-to-month gains have averaged 203,000,
well below last year's average of more than 300,000.
   For the past six months, the jobless rate has changed only
slightly; three of those months it was 5.2 percent, the other three
5.3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
