<HEAD>Dollar Rallies Against Guilder in Quiet Market; Gold Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed this morning as a quiet
European market waited for direction from U.S. economic data. Gold
prices firmed.
   Traders said the market was quiet, with most traders waiting on
the sidelines for the release of U.S. unemployment data for
November due later in the day.
   One trader at a large West German commercial bank in Frankfurt
said a rumor today that non-farm payrolls will be up far less than
the expected 155,000, which would be an indication the U.S. economy
is slowing and could prompt the U.S. Federal Reserve to ease credit
policies, pushed the dollar slightly higher rather than lower, as
one would expect on such a rumor.
   ``It's a perverse market,'' said the trader. ``At the moment
every dollar movement is unexplainable.''
   Another trader said the dollar could rise but added, ``We have
to wait and see how the market interprets the numbers.'' Because
volume was dropping with the approach of the holiday, the trader
added, movements could be sharp.
   In Tokyo, the dollar ended the day at 144.27 yen, up 0.14 yen
from its close on Thursday. Later in the day in London, the dollar
was quoted at 144.23 yen.
   The dollar, which dipped below 2.0000 Dutch guilders for the
first time since Jan. 3 on Thursday, trading at a late rate of
1.9963, rallied to 2.0025 Dutch guilders today.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.7745 West German marks, up from 1.7720; 1.5952
Swiss francs, up from 1.5920; 6.0610 French francs, up from 6.0560;
1,307.95 Italian lire, down from 1,308.00; and 1.1620 Canadian
dollars, from 1.1625.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.5772, compared to
$1.5750 late Thursday.
   Gold bullion dealers in London fixed a recommended price of
$408.85 a troy ounce this morning, up from $404.25 bid late
Thursday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $408.40, up from $404 bid late
Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose $2.74 to close at a bid $407.75.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.62 a troy ounce, up 2
cents from Thursday.
