<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Rises on Japan Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost
ground today for the first time this week, while the dollar edged
up against the yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average ended the week at 37,724.06,
down 134.05 points or 0.35 percent from its record-high closing of
37,858.11 Thursday. Volume on the market's first section was
estimated at 1 billion shares, up from 944 million shares Thursday.
   Analysts saw the drop as a healthy sign after the market's rapid
gains in recent weeks. ``There are no negatives that should push
the market down. But (the drop in prices today) is keeping the
market developing in a smooth and gradual ascent,'' said Chuck
Lambert, an international equity salesman at Jardine Fleming.
   A salesman at Kleinwort Benson securities said he didn't expect
that the market's recent rally, in which the Nikkei average has
advanced in all but two of the past 22 trading days, had ended
despite today's drop.
   ``It's not time yet to say this rally has come to an end. There
are a lot of people still waiting to put money into the market,''
said the trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar ended the day at
144.27 yen, up 0.14 yen from its close of 144.13 yen on Thursday.
After opening at 144.32 yen, the U.S. currency ranged between
144.20 and 144.40 yen.
   There were no strong trends in the market as many Japanese
traders stayed on the sidelines, said Minori Takeuchi, a trader at
Chemical Bank.
   The dollar's higher opening in Tokyo followed an overnight
upswing in New York, where it ended at 144.30 yen.
   Some speculators in Tokyo seemed to be waiting until the dollar
rose more before selling to buy yen, Takeuchi said. Finance
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto indicated a relative lack of concern
with the dollar's strength above the 144 yen level at a regular
news conference this morning.
   ``Inside a delicate situation we are taking a delicate look,''
he said. The remark was seen as indicating the ministry was not
alarmed by the dollar's recent rise.
   Many market players also were awaiting the release of U.S.
jobless figures for November, due out in Washington later today,
traders said.
