<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-FmHA-BadFaith 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FmHA-Bad Faith, 1st Ld-Writethru,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>FmHA Says Bad-Faith Borrowers Taking Advantage of Debt Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 2-3, The FmHA, with updated number of borrowers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some financially troubled borrowers who
cheated the Farmers Home Administration avoided foreclosure by
taking advantage of debt settlement measures intended for borrowers
who acted in good faith, officials say.
   The FmHA estimates 330 bad-faith borrowers paid off their debt
or bought back foreclosed farms through provisions in the 1987
Agricultural Credit Act.
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., has sponsored a Senate-approved bill
to limit the debt-restructuring program to farmers who acted
properly.
   A General Accounting Office fact sheet given to Conrad last week
lists examples of eight borrowers in one unspecified county office
who benefited from the program despite cheating FmHA by selling
collateral, hiding income or paying other creditors more than
necessary.
   One farmer who is eligible for the program had $91,284 in his
checking account while he was $76,269 past due on FmHA loans.
   ``We're not talking about a big thing, (but) obviously we don't
want those who acted in bad faith to get the benefits of the
legislation, and that was clearly Congress' intent when they passed
the Agricultural Credit Act,'' said Conrad, chairman of the
Senate's agricultural credit subcommittee.
   FmHA would actually lose some money by foreclosing on those
borrowers, but the agency estimates a net savings of $10 million
because other farmers would be discouraged from cheating, Conrad
said.
   ``I think it is really an issue of assuring taxpayers that the
system is going to operate in a way that assures that those who
haven't operated in good faith don't get the benefits of the
Agricultural Credit Act,'' Conrad said.
   The Senate passed Conrad's bill shortly before Congress
adjourned last month. The House has taken no action on the measure,
which is backed by FmHA.
   ``We are in favor of anything that will enable us to collect
reasonable debts on a reasonable basis. That (Conrad's bill) is a
step in the right direction,'' Agriculture Department spokesman
John Kislak said Thursday.
   FmHA is often called the government's farm lender of last resort
because loans are made only to those who cannot qualify at banks or
other commercial sources.
   With loan delinquencies rising in 1987, Congress forced FmHA to
write down loans or spread out payments whenever that would cost
the government less than foreclosure.
   Bad-faith borrowers have taken advantage of a provision under
which farmers who don't qualify for restructuring can buy out of
their debt at the adjusted value of their collateral, according to
the GAO report.
   In one location, borrowers who ``engaged in multiple instances
of bad faith'' bought out their loans that way, the GAO said.
   Another provision bad-faith borrowers have used gives them the
option to purchase or lease land the FmHA took from them in
foreclosure.
   Among the examples of borrowers who cheated FmHA were:
   _A farmer who sold farm equipment that was FmHA security
equipment and had another family member sell additional equipment.
None of the money was applied to the farmer's $626,000 in FmHA debt.
   _A farmer who borrowed money from other lenders for farm
equipment FmHA had told him he didn't need. The farmer repaid those
loans and even made advanced principal payments on them while
becoming delinquent on $187,000 in FmHA debt.
   _A farmer who claimed a son had not made rental payments on his
farm, even though the borrower was current or ahead on payments to
other creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     12-08 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Say Latest UAL Buyout Proposal Still No Good</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' machinists, who have opposed
recent plans to take over the airline's parent company, say they
haven't seen anything to change their minds in the latest
management-worker buyout proposal.
   ``The machinists will oppose any transaction that would unduly
put the company at risk as the last proposal did,'' said Brian
Freeman, an adviser to the Machinists union, representing about
25,000 UAL employees.
   Freeman said Thursday that the union would not participate in
any buyout that includes current senior management of UAL
   UAL management has not met with Machinists union leaders on the
new buyout proposal nor set a date for a meeting, Freeman said.
   Although some managers have met with other employee unions,
neither officials at the parent of United Airlines nor leaders of
the airline's labor unions have offered many details.
   Analysts say UAL management is seeking ironclad commitments from
lenders and the company's three major unions before publicly
announcing the particulars of its revised buyout effort.
   But one union official said Thursday the failure of a previous
bid was prompting UAL's discretion.
   The earlier buyout proposal accepted by UAL's board _ a
$300-a-share, $6.75 billion deal involving UAL management, the
7,000-member United chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association and
British Airways PLC _ collapsed in October when lenders refused to
finance it.
   One factor in banks' wariness of financing the deal was the
continued opposition of the Machinists.
   ``A number of people were embarrassed with (the failure) of the
first ESOP proposals. Most of the parties want to avoid that,''
said Carol Holmes, the outgoing vice president of the 14,000-member
United Airlines unit of the Association of Flight Attendants.
   UAL officials presented a revised employee buyout proposal to
officials of the flight attendants' union on Wednesday. Holmes
refused to provide details of the proposal but said she would
outline it for union members.
   Meetings between UAL management and its 70,000 employees will
continue for some time, said UAL spokesman Rob Doughty. He
described the meetings as roundtable discussions, during which
employees are asked for ideas on the buyout proposal.
   ``It's our policy not to discuss matters that would affect the
value or trading of our stock,'' he said, refusing to divulge
details of the plan.
   ``It also has long been our policy not to discuss labor
negotiations,'' he said, noting the proposal addresses some issues
that usually are covered in union contracts.
   Industry analysts say they believe the revised management buyout
plan will value UAL at $210 to $240 a share, or a total of $4.75
billion to $5.42 billion.
   UAL stock traded at $176.50 a share at mid-day today, down 50
cents from Thursday's close on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv11   12-08 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv11,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Guaranteed' Investment Contracts Not a Sure Bet, But Record Is Unblemished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During recent Congressional testimony that
disclosed private pension fund fraud, many Americans may have felt
reassured because their nest egg is protected in a so-called
guaranteed investment contract.
   Maybe they shouldn't breathe so easily.
   Those ``guaranteed'' contracts, often used as part of 401 (k)
retirement savings plans, are not ironclad. The only guarantee
behind them is the belief that the issuer is of sufficient
financial strength to keep paying the contracts' fixed rate of
interest.
   Despite their name, chances are no government agency would step
in to make good should a sponsor of the contracts, typically an
insurance company, hit the skids.
   Many insurance companies put their money in junk bonds, risky
mortgages and other investments that may give an investor pause.
The degree to which they are involved in risky investments is
reflected in the credit rating they receive from credit-rating
agencies.
   ``Most of the companies in this market we have rated AA or
higher, which would suggest that the guarantee is pretty good _
very good, actually,'' said Weston Hicks, a vice president at
Moody's Investors Service Inc., a credit-rating agency that ranks
companies on a scale of AAA to C.
   But, he said, ``there's really no protection per se'' if a
company issuing a guaranteed investment contract, or GIC, goes
under.
   There has never been a GIC default. But Hicks said there are
differences in creditworthiness that an investor should consider
between an insurance company rated AAA and one rated AA or lower.
   GICs exploded in popularity with the growth of 401 (k) plans,
which are company-sponsored programs that allow employees to put
away a portion of their income in a savings fund and defer income
taxes on it until the money is withdrawn at retirement, when it is
taxed at a lower rate.
   The 401 (k) plans have mushroomed as many smaller companies have
dropped company-sponsored pension plans. These companies say the
federal rules that govern pension plans make them too complex and
costly for small businesses.
   Employees often have a choice of several investment options for
their 401 (k) savings, including GICs and various stock or bond
mutual funds. Many 401 (k) plans spread the funds among several
GICs, thereby reducing the risk to the savings should there be a
GIC default.
   The advantages of GICs are that they pay a steady rate of
interest and the principal is fixed. With some mutual funds
principal can deteriorate depending on market conditions, while the
rate of interest is never guaranteed.
   GICs typically pay interest rates that exceed the yields on
Treasury bills and money market funds by 0.5 to 1.5 percentage
points.
   The total amount of money invested in GICs exceeds $150 billion,
industry officials estimate.
   Hank Madden, an IDS Securities Corp. financial planner in
Jacksonville, Fla., said that ``as tightly regulated as the
insurance industry is,'' investors should have little to worry
about with GICs.
   ``Thus far, the insurance industry since the Great Depression
has had a pretty good track record of making those guarantees come
about,'' he said.
   Even when insurance companies have had financial trouble the
investors holding annuities and other investments in them have not
been burnt, he said, mentioning the bankruptcy reorganization of
Baldwin-United Corp. several years ago as an example.
   However, Hicks said, all is not well in the insurance industry
today.
   ``There's clearly been a deterioration in the insurance
industry's credit quality over the past few years,'' he said.
   In addition, he said: ``The GIC market is highly competitive and
insurance companies are writing this business at quite thin
spreads. In order to make it profitable they have to put a lot of
liabilities on their books.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
