<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain and Soybean Futures Drift Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices came under pressure from selling that continued
from Thursday's weak close. The market was expected to get some
support from reports that Egypt and the Soviet Union would be
targeted for additional wheat under the export bonus program.
   Good export sales figures, released Thursday by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, were expected to give support to corn
futures. And reports Spain may be in the market for one million
metric tons of corn also might boost prices, said analyst William
Biedermann of Allendale Inc. in Chicago.
   Soybean futures were under pressure from reports planting is
progressing smoothly in South America, and the existance of
shipping problems along the Mississippi River.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to \ cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.08\ a bushel; corn was \
cent to } cent lower with December at $2.36 a bushel; oats were \
cent to { cent higher with December at $1.44{ a bushel; soybeans
were } cent to 1{ cents lower with January $5.74\ a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mixed and pork futures lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork belly futures were down the limit due to followthrough
selling from Thursday. Analysts also attributed the decline to
disappointment over a lack of government buying in recent tenders
for bellies to Poland.
   The large number of bellies going into storage also is hurting
prices.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .02 cent higher with December
at 75.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .33
cent higher with January at 82.85 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent
to .52 cents lower with December at 51.20 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.30 cents to 2 cents lower with February at
52.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mixed and pork futures were lower in
Thursday's trading.
