<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground today with a lift
from falling interest rates and new signs of sluggish economic
growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 15.57 to
2,736.35 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 755 up, 510 down and
554 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported this morning that the civilian
unemployment rate increased 0.1 percentage point to 5.4 percent in
November.
   The figures showed an increase of 210,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, after an October increase in jobs that was revised
sharply downward to 93,000.
   Analysts said that painted a picture of continued softness in
some major sectors of the economy, apparently improving the chances
for further moves by the Federal Reserve to relax its credit policy.
   In the credit markets, prices of long-term government bonds rose
about $5 for each $1,000 in face value, lowering their yields to
the 7.87 percent-7.91 percent range.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up [ at 43~; General Electric, up [ at 63{; DuPont, up
1\ at 122, and Chrysler, up \ at 19[.
   Pfizer, which projected slightly lower earnings for the fourth
quarter, dropped 2~ to 70|.
   Tonka Corp. lost 1} to 12. The company lowered its revenue
estimate for the year, citing slower-than-expected sales during the
holiday season.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.62 to 193.00. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .39 at 375.48.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.20 million shares at
noontime, against 74.88 million at the same point Thursday.
