<FIRST>r f BC-SeaContainers-Temple 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sea Containers-Temple, 1st Ld-Writethru,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Temple Sweetens Sea Containers Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Sea Containers ..., to ADD spokeswoman. Picks
up 9th graf pvs, The company ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Temple Holdings Ltd. said Friday it sweetened
for a second time its hostile offer for Sea Containers Ltd., by
around $20 million to $1.04 billion, and heated up a proxy battle
for control of the shipping company.
   Temple, which began its takeover bid last spring, increased a
previously raised cash offer in August for Sea Containers' common
stock to $70 a share from $63 a share, and for each of its
convertible preferred stock to $112.70 from $101.43.
   A Temple spokesman said the new bid, which was extended to Dec.
22 from Dec. 11, valued Sea Containers at $1.04 billion, up from
$1.02 billion.
   The initial offer in May totaled $824 million, or $50 a share
per common share and $80.50 for preferred.
   Wall Street reacted positively to the latest offer Friday. In
midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Sea Containers
jumped $2.50 a share to $68.75.
   In announcing its latest bid, Temple also said that if Sea
Containers refused to hold a prompt annual meeting, it would call a
special meeting for the purpose of voting on a slate of Temple
nominees to replace the current board of directors.
   Temple Holdings Ltd. is owned by Sweden's Stena Holdings AG and
Britain's Tiphook PLC. Stena already owns about 8 percent of Sea
Containers stock.
   Sea Containers, which is based in Hamilton, Bermuda, and
operates ferries in the English Channel, had no immediate comment
on the latest offer, said Alison Hogan, a spokeswoman for the
company.
   The company has rejected the previous bids, and in August
announced it would forge ahead with a recapitalization plan that
would involve an undisclosed cash distribution and the issuance of
new common stock and other securities.
</TEXT>
