<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TieRack Bjt   12-08 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tie Rack, Bjt,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tie Retailer Has Taken Expansion Tack in U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tie Tidbits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Malta summit not only may have symbolized
another high point in superpower relations, but also was the
pinnacle so far for a tie retailing newcomer to the United States.
   Tie Rack got a pleasant surprise when President Bush sported its
``GlasnostTie'' at a joint news conference with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev after the talks concluded last Sunday.
   The chain _ owned by a company that bills itself as the world's
biggest necktie retailer _ opened its first U.S. store two years
ago. And it couldn't have hoped for a better attention getter and
the timing was perfect.
   The holidays are the most important time for retailers of any
stripe and ties are a Christmas present standby. Pundits have
predicted this year will be a penny-pinching Christmas as shoppers
hunt for inexpensive gifts, with accessories high on their lists.
   Being able to boast about Bush wearing one of his company's ties
was a welcome change for Roy Bishko, chairman of the British parent
company Tie Rack PLC, who last month had to explain some
disappointing financial results.
   In an interview this week, the breathlessly fast-talking Bishko
brimmed with enthusiasm about his concept of bringing affordable
high-quality neckwear to the masses. His eyes gleamed as he
lovingly displayed the latest designs at a Tie Rack store in
midtown Manhattan, one of 41 the company operates in the United
States.
   ``Ties are important to me,'' Bishko proclaimed.
   Bishko said the idea of founding Tie Rack was borne out of his
frustration at not being able to afford a nice silk tie. Plus, he
thought it was a merchandising mistake for ties to be relegated to
tiny sections in mens' departments of big stores.
   Thus, Tie Rack's compact little stores are located in
high-traffic areas, typically along a route that commuters take
going to and from work, such as New York's Grand Central Station.
   They overflow with a bright, broad assortment, ranging from
funky, bold patterns to staid stripes, starting at around $15 and
going up past $60 a piece. The stores also stock scarves, shawls,
floppy bow ties and other neckwear for women. Silky-textured
polyester scarves can be bought for under $10 while real silk
scarves range from $26 to $150.
   Through an arrangement with the Paisley Museum in Scotland, Tie
Rack has access to old designs and adapts them for neckwear. Its
designers also cull ultra-modern patterns from popular culture,
including Hollywood films, and work with contemporary artists.
   On the Glasnost Tie, presented to Bush earlier this year and to
various world leaders last year, there are miniature reproductions
of American and Soviet flags and a Dove of Peace. The background is
dark blue. Tie Rack commissioned it from London's St. Martin
College of Art and royalties on its sales go to a British cancer
charity.
   Bishko, a South African native who emigrated to England in the
early 1970s, had limited experience in retailing before he founded
Tie Rack in 1981. He was working in property and finance at the
time.
   ``I must say I am self-taught'' in retailing, said 44-year-old
Bishko.
   His specialty retailing idea captivated investors when the
company went public in Britain in the summer of 1987. The initial
public offer of Tie Rack stock drew 85 times the number of
potential takers it could accomodate.
   But more recently investors might consider Tie Rack to be a pain
in the neck. The stock has been trading at around 50 pence a share
lately, down from 1.45 pounds when the stock was floated.
   The stock, which isn't traded in the United States, was battered
last month when Tie Rack reported an unexpectedly poor performance
for the first half of the year. In the 28 weeks ended Aug. 13, Tie
Rack lost 272,000 pounds compared with a profit of 374,000 pounds a
year earlier.
   The cost of U.S. expansion and Tie Rack's slow progress in the
United States were cited as causes of its troubles. In addition to
the United States, the company's 220 stores are in the United
Kingdom, Ireland, Canada, Australia, France, the Netherlands and
Norway.
   Outside this country, Tie Racks typically are operated as
franchises and Bishko said the company eventually will sell
franchises here. Now, all U.S. stores are company-owned and run.
   Bishko said he is undaunted and will continue to try and foster
awareness here of his company, which is billed as the world's
biggest neckwear retailer with more than $100 million in sales last
year. Financial analysts, he said, are too preoccupied with the
short-term.
   Other British retailers catering to small market niches have had
success in exporting their concept here and Tie Rack probably won't
be an exception. Sock Shop stores and Body Shops, selling
all-natural health and beauty aids, both have set up U.S.
operations and found plenty of eager American customers.
   ``We regard America as a long-term investment,'' Bishko said.
``I'm sure the share price will look after itself in due course.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
