<FIRST>u f AM-TieTidbits     12-08 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tie Tidbits,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>When In Doubt, Christmas Shoppers Turn to Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tie Rack Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giving a tie as a Christmas gift may seem like a
cliche but the Neckwear Association of America thinks knot.
   The holiday season is the busiest time of year for all retailers
and ties move fastest then, too. The Neckwear Association, a trade
group for the nearly $1 billion industry, estimates that 100
million ties will be sold this year in the United States and about
20 million of them will be bought as holiday gifts. ``The fact that
there are that many ties sold year in and year out indicates that
ties are a very popular gift,'' said Gerald Andersen, the group's
executive director.
   Retailers say ties are a good choice because shoppers don't have
to worry about sizes. Ties, retailers say, have one of the lowest
return rates for any apparel category.
   This year, Andersen said, the tie business is expected to be
very strong because ``ties are bolder and more exciting than they
have been in years and consumers are really responding.''
   To help gift givers make the right selection, the association
offers the following tips:
   _Buy one that fits the receiver's tastes, not yours. ``This is
probably the most common mistake in buying a tie gift,'' Andersen
says.
   _Get to know someone's wardrobe before buying the person a tie.
Take note of color preferences and choose a complementing tie.
   _If someone favors a particular designer or clothing
manufacturer, look for a tie of the same make.
   _Consider a person's interests. Ties that reflect hobbys are a
safe bet, such as a tie dotted with tiny golf balls for an avid
golfer.
   _Choose a tie that is in fashion.
   Ties are wider this year, with the most popular widths being 3{
inches to 3} inches. Some designers are moving to a 4-inch shape.
   Popular patterns are bold. Looks inspired by the 1940s and early
1950s as well as European themes are hot. Paisleys in rich colors
are selling well. Silk printed neckwear is still a favorite but
woven neckwear is gaining a following.
   The present ``power'' tie is one with a jacquard overprint,
meaning a design printed on a solid color patterned background.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
