<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-08 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumors Of Increased Sales to USSR Sends Wheat Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher in
quiet trading Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices were higher amid reports that the Soviet Union may
be offered up to 2 million metric tons of wheat under the U.S.
Agriculture Department's export bonus program.
   Under the program private exporters can sell U.S. commodities at
reduced prices to meet foreign competition and collect free
government surpluses as bonuses or subsidies.
   Corn prices were lower despite reports Spain may be in the
market for one million metric tons of corn, said analyst Joel
Karlin of Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Reports that the Soviet Union also may enter the market for corn
did little to help corn prices.
   A strong soybean oil market helped lift soybean futures higher.
Prices were helped by reports the United States may assist several
North African nations in buying soyoil, Karlin said.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.10\ a bushel; corn was \
cent to } cent lower with December at $2.36 a bushel; oats were {
cent lower to unchanged with December at $1.44 a bushel; soybeans
were 2 cents to 4 cents higher with January at $5.79{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
