<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-777     12-08 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-777,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Forming Division for New Widebody Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. officials announced Friday they are
forming a division to develop a new widebody plane that could
become the 777.
   The new jet will be larger than an existing 767 but smaller than
the familiar 747 model.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said the
company is going ahead and developing the plane and making first
offers to airlines. But Thornton said no airlines have yet offered
to buy the plane and Boeing is far from committed to actually
building it.
   Neither Thornton nor Phil Condit, Boeing Commercial Airplanes
executive vice president, would say how much it would cost Boeing
to develop the new plane, although Thornton said it would be in the
billions of dollars.
   Condit estimated the new plane would sell for slightly less than
$100 million.
   Speculation about a new Boeing jet model has focused on the role
Japanese companies might have in its development. Thornton said
Boeing has been talking to three Japanese companies, but that no
contract has been signed.
   If enough airlines agree to buy it, the new jet would go into
production as the 777. Until now, talk about such a new jet has
referred to it as a 767X.
   Thornton said the new plane would be smaller and have a shorter
range than the 747 jumbo jet but would be larger than Boeing's
other widebody, the 767.
   Condit said Boeing envisions the plane as having capacity for
about 350 passengers. It initially would be marketed as a
replacement for the Lockheed L-1011 and the McDonnell Douglas
DC-10, which are mainly used on long-distance domestic routes.
   Many of those competing planes have been in service since the
mid-1970s and will be 20 years old by 1995, when Boeing hopes to
introduce the new models, Condit said.
   Boeing later would like to offer an international version of the
777, capable of trans-Atlantic and trans-Pacific flight, said
Condit, who has been named general manager of the new division
which will develop the jet.
   Condit said Boeing will use many of its existing facilities to
build the plane but expects it would require a new assembly line,
probably at Boeing's existing widebody plant at Everett, Wash.
   The plane would be a twin-engine jet that Boeing hopes will be
able to accommodate essentially the same two-man cockpit as the 767.
   The seating would range from six to 10 across in two fare
classes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
