<DOCNO> AP891208-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-08 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended marginally weaker Friday
against most key currencies after the government reported the
jobless rate rose to a 10-month high of 5.4 percent last month.
   Gold rose in domestic trading following a big advance overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $411.80 a troy ounce, up $1.80 from late
Thursday. Republic National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for
gold at $411.50 an ounce, up $1.90.
   Currency dealers said the November unemployment data did little
to move the dollar because it was within market expectations,
although some traders were confused by a sharp revision in the
previous month's figures.
   The Labor Department said the civilian unemployment rate
increased to 5.4 percent in November from 5.3 percent in October _
the highest level since January _ despite the addition of 210,000
non-farm jobs last month.
   While the 210,000 new jobs was a moderately strong number, the
government also sharply revised its job growth figures for October
to 93,000 from 233,000.
   ``It's hard to know how much to react to data that's subject to
revisions of that magnitude,'' said Trevor Woodland, a vice
president and chief corporate dealer for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in
Chicago. ``What we got was a mixed bag.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar ended at 144.27 Japanese yen, up 0.14 yen from
Thursday's close. It traded at 144.20 yen in London, and 144.300
yen in New York, down from 144.305.
   The dollar declined against the British pound. Sterling traded
at $1.5793 in London, up from $1.5750 Thursday, and at $1.5825 in
New York, up from $1.5780.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
quotes, included: 1.7705 West German marks, down from 1.7725;
1.5970 Swiss francs, up from 1.5900; 6.04885 French francs, down
from 6.0515; 1,304.00 Italian lire, down from 1,307.25; and 1.16225
Canadian dollars, up from 1.16175.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Thursday: 1.7720 West
German marks, unchanged; 1.5985 Swiss francs, up from 1.5920;
6.0565 French francs, up from 6.0560; 1,306.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,308.00; and 1.1615 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1625.
   The dollar, which on Thursday dipped below two Dutch guilders in
Europe for the first time since Jan. 3, recovered at 2.000 guilders
late Friday.
   Gold soared in London to a late bid of $411.55 an ounce from
$404.25 late Thursday. In Zurich, it rose to $409.25 an ounce from
$404.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold gained $2.74 to close at $407.75 an
ounce.
   Silver prices also strengthened.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose
2.1 cents to $5.644 a troy ounce. Silver closed in London to $5.64
an ounce, up from $5.60 Thursday.
</TEXT>
