<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-StockFraud     12-08 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stock Fraud,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Haas Securities Chairman Convicted of Stock Manipulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of a Wall Street brokerage that
collapsed in the wake of the October 1987 market crash was
convicted Friday of manipulating the prices of over-the-counter
securities.
   A federal jury found Eugene Laff, 52, former chairman of Haas
Securities Corp., guilty of five charges _ conspiracy, two counts
of stock manipulation, mail fraud and obstruction of a Securities
and Exchange Commission investigation.
   The case in U.S. District Court in Manhattan was the first
investigation emanating from trading activity surrounding the Oct.
19, 1987, crash.
   Prosecutors had charged that the firm's scheme to artificially
inflate the prices of penny stocks _ inexpensive securites traded
over the counter _ could not be maintained after the market drop
and share prices tumbled.
   Laff, of Greenwich, Conn., faces up to five years in prison and
a $250,000 fine on each of the five counts when sentenced Feb. 15
by Judge Thomas P. Griesa.
   His attorney, John Lang, said he would likely appeal the
conviction.
   Prosecutors said Laff manipulated the stock prices by making it
appear that the stocks were in demand, orchestrating purchases
through accounts controlled by Henry Lorin, the head of a small
investment company, and Stanley Aslanian, a former Haas trader and
president.
   Both Lorin and Aslanian pleaded guilty and agreed to cooperate
with prosecutors in the Laff case.
   The defense had argued that Laff was unaware of any scheme to
inflate prices. His attorney blamed the scheme on Lorin and
Aslanian.
   Many of the witnesses during the two-month trial were Haas
customers who testified that they lost their life savings when the
company collapsed.
   Haas Securities was a 75-year-old firm that had 12,000 customers
before going out of business nine days after the crash when it no
longer had enough capital to stay afloat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
