<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up a moderate gain
Friday, aided by falling interest rates and new signs of sluggish
economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.66 to 2,731.44,
winding up the week with a net loss of 16.21 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
813 up, 646 down and 525 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported Friday morning that the civilian
unemployment rate increased 0.1 percentage point to 5.4 percent in
November.
   The figures showed a gain of 210,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, after an October increase in jobs that was revised
sharply downward to 93,000.
   Analysts said that painted a picture of continued softness in
some major sectors of the economy, apparently improving the chances
for further moves by the Federal Reserve to relax its credit policy
in the weeks ahead.
   In the credit markets, prices of long-term government bonds rose
about $5 for each $1,000 in face value, lowering their yields to
the 7.87 percent-7.91 percent range.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Coca-Cola, up 1[ at 78;
DuPont, up [ at 120~; Exxon, up ] at 49; Sears Roebuck, up ] at 38,
and Chrysler, up { at 19].
   Pfizer, which projected slightly lower earnings for the fourth
quarter, tumbled 4] to 69[.
   Tonka Corp. lost 2{ to 11\. The company lowered its revenue
estimate for the year, citing slower-than-expected sales during the
holiday season.
   That prompted selling as well in the shares of Toys R Us, which
was down 1} at 35}.
   Elsewhere, several stocks that had run up dramatic gains earlier
in the year came under pressure.
   Federal National Mortgage led the active list, down 2 at 34|,
and Federal Home Loan Mortgage fell 3{ to 72|. Brokers said the
stocks have suffered lately from concern about the outlook for
real-estate credit.
   L.A. Gear slumped 3] to 30]. A Wall Street Journal article said
the footwear manufacturer faced the ``perils of shifting fads.''
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 144.91 million
shares, down from 161.98 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 175.14 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $7.10 billion, or 0.21
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .54 to 192.92.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.33 to 399.22, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.10 at 348.69.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dipped .09 to 456.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 375.45, up .36.
