<FIRST>r f AM-BurgerKing     12-08 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burger King,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burger King Plans Improvements to Counter Slow Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burger King Corp.'s new owners plan to introduce a
chicken sandwich on an oat bran bun and install new computers in an
effort to boost sluggish sales at the nation's second-largest fast
food restaurant chain.
   The proposed changes were outlined following release of a
financial report Thursday that indicated sales at Burger King's
5,900 restaurants haveincreased 3 percent since Grand Metropolitan
PLC acquired it in January.
   ``The things that need to be done to fix Burger King are not
instant coffee. It's a two-year task,'' said Burger King Chairman
Ian Martin.
   Burger King, which reported sales of $5.4 billion last year, has
average store sales of about $1 million, compared with $1.6 million
per store at No. 1 McDonald's.
   In addition to a chicken sandwich with an oat bran bun, Burger
King plans to introduce about a half dozen new menu items by next
summer.
   Martin said breakfast is an area of particular scrutiny.
   ``There is absolutely no secret that when you look at what
Burger King has done, it has been substandard,'' said Martin
referring to the breakfast offerings.
   Burger King also plans to install upgraded computers at
company-owned stores which automatically track sales, said Martin.
   Grand Met hopes to open 250 to 300 Burger King restaurants next
year and convert its Wimpy's restaurants in Great Britain, Turkey,
Japan and Egypt to Burger Kings.
   Also, the company hopes to install a toll-free customer
complaint and information line next year.
   ``Before one could say they've turned around, you've got to wait
until next year and probably the year after that,'' said Jonathan
Goble, an analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd in London.
</TEXT>
