<FIRST>a f BC-EasternStrikers Adv11   12-08 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern Strikers, Adv 11,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gloomy Christmas for Eastern Picketers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paper route and occasional freelance
photography jobs have hardly helped Adolfo Collazo cover the loss
of his Eastern Airlines paycheck during the 9-month-old Machinists
strike, a fact that has hit like a winter storm with the holiday
season approaching.
   ``This Christmas _ very sad,'' the father of three sons said.
``They know it. I told them, one toy each.''
   Collazo, a ramp service worker with 14 years at Eastern, spoke
about his financial ordeal as he walked the picket line at
Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport. ``I'm still trying to
catch up with my bills,'' he said.
   Money is tight, and tempers sometimes are too, for many of the
Machinists union members who struck Eastern March 4.
   ``If you hadn't worked in nine months, how would you be getting
along?,'' J.D. Filey snapped from within the small rectangle,
bordered by yellow tape, that Hartsfield allows for picketing on
the Eastern concourse.
   Some, such as Filey and Collazo, occasionally have found
part-time work to supplement the $100 a week the union pays for
walking the picket line. Others have working spouses or a decent
savings account balance to help them get by. Some have left to take
jobs elsewhere. Some say they are just broke.
   But the pickets, who have become fixtures this year at airports
served by Eastern, say they are determined to continue their
strike, even though the airline's pilots and flight attendants have
abandoned their sympathy strikes and little hope for a settlement
exists.
   ``We didn't think we'd be out this long,'' said Katie Cantrell,
who was a hangar maintenance worker with Eastern 16 years until the
strike. ``Now, I think I'll be in this box this time next year.''
   Ms. Cantrell and Filey, a 21-year ramp service worker, said
they've had trouble finding work to help them make ends meet.
Employment agencies aren't much help.
   ``Once you put down you work for Eastern, no one will hire you
on a permanent basis,'' said Ms. Cantrell, who has relied on her
husband's salary since the strike began.
   ``They say, `You're going back to work soon.' Here it is, nine
months. That's soon?'' said Filey.
   The strikers' anger toward Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's
parent Texas Air Corp., seems to have turned to frustration at the
federal government and court system, which they say favor airline
management. Eastern sought bankruptcy court protection from
creditors five days after the strike.
   ``The supposed government has done nothing, and after I voted
for Bush,'' said Collazo.
   ``The unity is still here because of the way the politicians
have treated us,'' said Ms. Cantrell. ``Everyone's been bought.
That judge (U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton) Lifland, everything's
gone their way. That's amazing to me. They won't even give us a
spark of hope.''
   Their base of operations is now a dilapidated white wood-frame
house about two miles from Hartsfield. It's been the Machinists'
strike headquarters since a Nov. 26 rock-throwing fracas that
resulted in the expulsion of a union ``tent city'' from airport
grounds. There's no sign of progress in the strike.
   ``We're still out. We're gonna stay out,'' said mechanic Wayne
Macie, who was hanging out at the small house decorated with
anti-Lorenzo signs, a large U.S. flag and a 5-foot-tall Santa Claus
poster. ``The good part is, the guys are hanging together.''
   Macie said it was difficult to explain what has sustained the
strikers through the lengthy walkout.
   ``People who don't know what's going on have never worked for
Frank Lorenzo and his supervisors,'' Macie said.
   Eastern claims it's survived the Machinists strike, partly by
hiring 2,800 mechanics, including 300 union members who have
crossed the picket lines. About 8,500 Machinists, including 4,500
mechanics, went on strike.
   James Ashlock, an Eastern spokesman in Atlanta, the airline's
main hub, said the company is continuing to hire mechanics and ramp
service workers, but that the Machinists would get no preferential
treatment if they came back.
   ``They'd essentially be treated as new hires,'' Ashlock said.
``Quite frankly, a lot of them are not even around. The majority
have gone on to other jobs, including other airlines.''
   But R.J. Lavender, a striking ramp service worker at Hartsfield,
said, ``I figure maybe 80 to 85 percent are still walking the
picket line.''
   At the airport, Filey was asked if his enthusiasm for the strike
might dip with the plunging temperatures of December.
   ``The weather don't have nothing to do with this,'' he said.
``We'll be out here until the bitter end.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Dec. 11</NOTE>
