<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-08 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold weather helped buoy heating oil futures
prices Friday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, while crude oil
and gasoline futures finished lower.
   Domestic heating oil for January delivery rose 0.90 cent to
finish at 66.37 cents a gallon after a gain of 1.01 cents on
Thursday. Contracts for delivery through June closed on the plus
side, while those scheduled for later delivery posted slight
declines.
   Analysts attributed the gains in heating oil to strong demand
stemming from unusually cold weather in parts of the United States
and Europe.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which declined
0.36 cent on Thursday, sank another 0.16 cent to 52.65 cents a
gallon. Other contracts closed mixed.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the main grade
of U.S. crude oil, lost 3 cents to settle at $20.48 per 42-gallon
barrel in fairly slow trading. The contract, which had gained 4
cents in the previous session, traded as low as $20.25 a barrel.
   ``We had good demand to start with and the cold weather just
adds to that,'' said Michael Hiley, energy broker for Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., of the activity in heating oil.
   Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said
barge problems on the Rhine River continued to boost gasoil prices
on European futures markets, which had a bullish effect on energy
markets here. Gasoil is Europe's equivalent of U.S. heating oil.
   Low water levels on the Rhine have created logistical problems
for vessels transporting gasoil to customers and in some cases have
resulted in delays, Baker said. The delays have come during a time
of the year when demand for heating oil is high, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
