<DOCNO> AP891208-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv09-10   12-08 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 09-10,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec 9-10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grain Traders Disappointed By Lack of Increased Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders have been hoping the Soviets would line up with vastly
larger orders for American grain because of the East-West thaw, but
so far the only people standing in line are the bread buyers in
Moscow.
   Grain prices rallied on the Chicago Board of Trade late last
month on speculation that the Malta shipboard meeting between
President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev would yield
trade agreements, boosting commodity exports to the Soviet Union.
   However, no new trade agreement came out of the summit, and no
announcements resulted from the first round of talks in Moscow on a
new long-term grain agreement between the United States and the
Soviet Union.
   ``There is some disappointment the talks in Moscow didn't result
in some kind of announcement,'' said analyst Susan Leighty of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``It was expected
that the U.S. would raise the limit on the amount of grain that can
be purchased by the Soviet Union from 16 million metric tons to 20
million.''
   After the close of trading Friday, the U.S. Agriculture
Department announced the USSR will be permitted to buy 20 million
metric tons of grain without seeking prior approval. In October,
the USDA increased the purchase level from 12 million metric tons
to 16 million.
   So far this year, the Soviets have purchased 10.978 million
metric tons of corn, said William Biedermann, research director of
Allendale Inc., a Chicago brokerage firm. He said it's possible the
Soviets will purchase 1.4 million metric tons of corn a month from
March through August.
   Biedermann said what has been disappointing is the small wheat
purchases by the Soviets this year.
   Biedermann noted that during the grain talks, there was
increased buying by speculators of grain futures.
   ``We sold in that,'' he said. ``We felt the retail purchasing
was based on emotion.''
   Ms. Leighty said it is hard to resist the good feeling resulting
from the changes in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, and what
it means to the grain trade.
   ``It is assuming too much to link the grain talks to the
political changes going on in Eastern Europe and the Soviet
Union,'' she said. ``The U.S. and the USSR have long-standing links
in the grain trade. The events don't alter that.''
   What the Soviets want is more liberal credit terms, Ms. Leighty
said. But to get that, they most liberalize their immigration laws
to the satisfaction of the United States. But they failed to do
that this year.
   However, she predicted some kind of accommodation between the
United States and the Soviet Union on credit and grain trade.
   ``But it may not happen until next summer,'' Ms. Leighty said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Livestock and pork</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Pork futures were hit hard during the past week, pulled lower by
pork bellies. Analysts attributed the decline to disappointment
over a lack of government buying in recent tenders for bellies to
Poland.
   The large number of bellies going into storage also hurt prices.
   Live cattle futures drifted during a historically slack time of
retail demand.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Precious metals</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   After a sharp selloff early in the week, precious metal prices
rebounded _ led by gold. A weak dollar and political turmoil in
Eastern Europe acted boosted prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Energy</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Heating oil strengthened overall prices, as unseasonably cold
weather prevailed in some parts of the country. The market
generally ignored American Petroleum Institute figures showing a
large buildup in crude oil and refined products stock.
</TEXT>
