<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AdvancingJapanese     12-08 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Advancing Japanese,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecast: Japanese Computer Firms Advancing On U.S. Competitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top Japanese computer makers are overtaking
their U.S. competitors and that forward march is likely to continue
into the next decade, according to a report by the Arthur D. Little
consulting firm.
   The shift will become apparent in the rankings of the top
computer companies, the report's author, consultant Martyn Roetter,
said Friday.
   Furthermore, Roetter warned that if overseas suppliers become
the major provider of computers and information services to
American businesses at large, it could harm U.S. competitiveness.
   U.S. businesses using foreign computer systems ``will be at a
less privileged customer relationship,'' he said.
   Roetter's report uses his estimated revenue to rank the world's
20 leading companies in the $270 billion information systems and
services industry. He looked backward to 1988 and projected ahead
to 1993.
   Continuing a survey he makes annually, Roetter added two
Japanese firms, Toshiba and Matsushita, to the top 20, joining
Fujitsu, NEC and Hitachi. Fujitsu also displaced U.S.-based Unisys
from the third place on the list.
   The top ranked firms for 1988 were, in this order (unless
otherwise indicated, the firms are U.S.-based): International
Business Machines, Digital Equipment, Fujitsu (Japan), Unisys, NEC
(Japan), Hitachi (Japan), Hewlett-Packard, Siemens (W. Germany),
NCR, Groupe Bull (France), Olivetti (Italy), Apple, Toshiba
(Japan), Control Data, Wang, Nixdorf (W. Germany), Matsushita,
STC-ICL (England), Philips (Netherlands), Compaq.
   Looking ahead to 1993, Roetter forecast this ranking: IBM,
Digital, Fujitsu, Groupe Bull-NEC (strengthening a current
relationship), Unisys, Hitachi, Hewlett-Packard, Siemens, NCR,
Olivetti, Toshiba, Apple, Wang, Nixdorf, Matsushita, STC-ICL,
Compaq, Philips, EDS, Amdahl.
   The study also forecast an overall growth rate among the top 20
of 8 percent to 10 percent through 1993. While respectable, this is
far down from the early 1980s, when growth rates ranged up to 25
percent.
   Roetter attributed his projections to several factors:
   _Impending saturation of the markets for mainframes and
minicomputers.
   _Hesitation by consumers facing too many choices.
   _Lack of technology as yet that will integrate computer systems
so well that users can communicate with each other as easily as it
is to make an international telephone call.
   _Smaller competitors capturing the fledgling business of
software-intensive services.
   Roetter also warned that while many U.S. companies have
succeeded in making their presence felt overseas, some are badly
positioned in the international marketplace, pushing product lines
that are fast becoming obsolete.
   He predicted that stepped up competition will foster more
mergers, acquisitions and close partnerships, with U.S., Japanese
and European firms seeking out partners that will provide strategic
geographic access to markets.
   It was last year that the maturation of the
information-processing industry became more apparent, Roetter said
in his report.
   Most of the firms in the top 20 were troubled by diminished
profits and some lost money.
   ``Many found it necessary to reduce personnel and trim product
lines, and the specter of increased merger activity hung over the
entire industry,'' Roetter said in his report.
   ``Against this gloomy backdrop, however, Japanese companies,
fueled by long-term strategic planning and strength in
communications and semiconductor markets, gained ground on their
European and American counterparts,'' his report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
