<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lagging Exports Sends Pork Futures Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork belly futures prices plunged Friday on the Chicago Board of
Trade as concern over lagging export sales prompted traders to bail
out of the weak market. Livestock futures also were lower.
   On other commodity markets, cotton continued to lose ground;
grain and soybeans were mixed; precious metals gained and energy
futures were mostly higher.
   Live cattle settled .07 cent to .47 cent lower with the contract
for delivery in December at 75.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.03 cent to .18 cent lower with January at 82.77 cents a pound;
hogs were .30 cent to 1.18 cents lower with December at 50.82 cents
a pound; and frozen pork bellies were 1.85 cents to 2 cents lower
with February at 52.45 cents a pound.
   The belly contracts for February, March and May were down the
2-cent limit Friday as traders liquidated their long positions,
said analyst Paul Hare of Linnco Futures Inc. in Chicago.
   Less than expected government purchases of bellies for shipment
to Poland and sentiment the gains in the pork market during the
past two months was overdone also contributed to the selloff, Hare
said, adding that the brisk pace of bellies into storage pressured
prices.
   Hare said the selloff in pork bellies began two weeks ago after
rumors the Soviet Union may be interested in buying U.S. pork
products failed to materialize.
   Cotton futures declined sharply on New York's Cotton Exchange as
traders reacted to rumors a major cotton merchant was liquidating
long positions.
   Adding to the pressure to sell were expectations the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's estimate of U.S. crop production, due
out Tuesday, will be higher than its November estimate, said
analyst Ed Whitten of Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New York.
   Cotton was .70 cent to 2 cents lower with March at 66.18 cents a
pound.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices were higher amid reports that the Soviet Union may
be offered up to 2 million metric tons of wheat under the U.S.
Agriculture Department's export bonus program.
   Corn prices were lower despite reports Spain may be in the
market for one million metric tons of corn, said analyst Joel
Karlin of Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Reports that the Soviet Union also may enter the market for corn
did little to help corn prices.
   A strong soyoil market helped lift soybean futures higher.
Prices were helped by reports the United States may assist several
North African nations in buying soyoil, Karlin said.
   Wheat was 1\ cents to 2\ cents higher with December at $4.10\ a
bushel; corn was \ cent lower to unchanged with December at $2.36\
a bushel; oats were { cent lower to unchanged with December at
$1.44 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 3{ cents higher with
January at $5.79 a bushel.
   Energy futures were higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Heating oil futures provided the strength in the oil market on
expectations of a resurgence of cold weather along the East Coast.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 3 cents lower to 6 cents
higher with January at $20.48 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent
lower to .90 cent higher with January at 66.37 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was .28 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
January at 52.65 cents a gallon.
   Precious metals prices were higher on the New York Commodity
Exchange.
   Concerns about the economy and the possibilty of falling
interest rates sent gold and silver futures higher, said analyst
Fred Demler of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Gold was $1.80 to $2.80 higher with the December at $411.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 2 cents to 2.1 cents higher with December at
$5.644 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
