<FIRST>a f BC-NewspaperOutlook Adv11   12-08 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Newspaper Outlook, Adv 11,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Expect More of the Same in 1990 Newspaper Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper publishers likely will match this
year's modest earnings gains in 1990 as slow advertising revenue
growth mutes the benefit of cheaper newsprint.
   Analyst projections of earnings growth ranging from 8 percent to
10 percent would mean next year's profits will be slightly below
average for the newspaper business. Earnings gains of 10 percent to
12 percent are the average.
   ``A soft advertising performance and the inability to raise ad
rates much greater than the inflation rate has put some pressure on
profits,'' said John Morton, media analyst for Lynch, Jones &amp; Ryan
in Washington.
   ``What will help is that newsprint price hikes are not likely,''
he said.
   Morton and other analysts say that while their estimates of
overall earnings performance call for little change from the gains
posted in 1989, the pattern will be different.
   They expect weak results in the first half of the year and
stronger gains in the second half, barring an unexpectedly sharp
decline in the level of overall economic activity.
   In 1989, the newspaper business got worse as the year went along.
   ``1990 will almost be the mirror image of this year,'' said
Dennis McAlpine, who follows the newspaper business for Oppenheimer
&amp; Co.
   Revenue growth from advertising continues to be sluggish with
analysts looking for 4 percent to 6 percent growth next year.
   The analysts see signs that ad spending by retailers may be
about to pick up, but they say the outlook has worsened for
classified ad spending.
   Retail advertising accounts for more than half of newspaper ad
revenue, but gains have been limited in the past two years as
stores have restrained their spending because of consolidation in
the retail industry and the problems some new owners have faced in
meeting hefty debt payments.
   ``We are looking for some of those problems to be resolved next
year,'' said Michael Kupinski, analyst for A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
in St. Louis.
   On the other hand, classified advertising revenues, which
account for about 30 percent of newspaper ad revenues, have begun
to deteriorate, falling in the past two months from the previous
year's levels.
   Kupinski expects classified ad revenue will decline 3 percent
next year, mostly because of a falloff in help-wanted advertising.
``That reflects a weakening economy,'' he said.
   National ad revenue, which makes up the balance of newspaper ad
revenue, is expected to be up about 7 percent again this year,
Kupinski said.
   McAlpine said the newspaper industry's increased marketing
efforts may lead to a 1 percent increase in circulation revenue for
newspapers next year compared with no growth or slight declines
last year.
   On the cost side, the price of newsprint has been falling,
helping the bottom line.
   Newsprint costs typically comprise 25 percent to 30 percent of
newspaper costs and newsprint prices fell 7 percent to 8 percent on
average this year with similar declines expected next year,
McAlpine said.
   Morton said newsprint prices are falling because of overcapacity
in the newsprint business. He said newsprint suppliers decided
several years ago when prices were rising steadily to build or
expand production facilities, and those plants are now producing
more newsprint than the market can absorb.
   Increases in labor costs are not expected to change much in the
coming year, although some newspaper companies face potentially
difficult negotiations with their unions on new contracts.
   At the moment, the analysts said companies with operations in
the Northeast and Southwest seem to be headed for the toughest
times because of regional economic weakness.
   They said the West and parts of the Midwest should continue to
benefit from relative economic strength.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
