<FIRST>u f AM-KodakChairman 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak Chairman, 1st Ld-Writethru,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Announces Next Chief Executive Officer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more information and quotes, analysts'
comments; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. President Kay R.
Whitmore will succeed Colby H. Chandler as chief executive officer,
the company said Friday.
   Whitmore, 57, will assume his new position when Chandler retires
June 1 after 40 years with the company. Chandler has been chief
executive since 1983.
   Whitmore, who has been with Kodak since 1957, has been president
of the company for six years and an executive officer since 1986.
   Kodak Vice Chairman J. Phillip Samper, 55, who had been
considered a rival of Whitmore for the top job, said he would take
early retirement effective Jan. 1. He had become vice chairman and
an executive officer in 1986.
   Chandler, Whitmore and Samper have ruled Kodak through a
three-man executive council that officials said will now be
disbanded, giving Whitmore sole control of the company. Kodak
spokesman Henry Kaska said the company had no plans to name a
president or vice chairman for at least a year.
   Financial analysts said Whitmore's succession did not represent
a change in policy for the company, which is in the midst of a
restructuring and job-cutting plan aimed at turning around sagging
profits.
   ``Whitmore has been part of the recent direction anyway,'' said
Eugene Glazer of Dean, Witter, Reynolds. ``I don't see that the
course of the company is likely to change.''
   ``A change in the top by itself does not change the fundamental
challenges that Kodak confronts,'' said Mark Obenzinger of Trinity
Trading Co.
   Whitmore said he planned to continue the restructuring plan
begun this year.
   ``We're following a path and I don't think we'll fundamentally
change,'' he said. ``I don't expect the challenges will go away. We
will do what is necessary to be competitive into the future.''
   Chandler said Whitmore has ``solid management experience'' and
is ``fully capable of leading this company forward towards the next
century.''
   Obenzinger said consolidating Kodak's executive control in one
person is likely to speed up communication and decision-making.
   ``A one-stop decision-maker is clearly an advantage for Kodak,''
he said.
   Analysts expressed surprise at the departure from the company of
Samper, who said he was leaving Kodak for a mixture of personal and
business reasons. He did not elaborate on those reasons.
   ``This is a moment for me of considerable emotion _ mixed
emotions _ and gratitude,'' Samper said. ``Kodak is a marvelous
company.
   ``Kay Whitmore has my total confidence,'' he said. ``I leave
without any difference of opinion as to where Kodak plans to take
the company.''
   Samper said he plans to retire to California with his wife.
   ``While we regret Phil Samper's decision to retire early, we
respect his wishes,'' Chandler said. ``He leaves Kodak with the
thanks of us all for his 28 years of dedicated service,'' Chandler
said.
   Kodak also announced a number of other changes made at Friday's
board meeting, including the naming of Wilbur J. Prezzano as
general manager of a new International Group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891208-0285 </DOCNO>
