<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     12-08 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0868</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment climbed to a 10-month high of 5.4
percent in November and manufacturing payrolls shrunk for the
eighth consecutive month, the government said.
   The increase in the civilian jobless rate from 5.3 percent came
despite the addition of 210,000 non-farm jobs last month because of
a big jump in the number of Americans looking for work.
   The 210,000 new non-farm jobs reported Friday by the Labor
Department was in itself a moderately strong number, but the
government also sharply cut its job growth figures for October from
233,000 to 93,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is considering
significant relaxation of a U.S. ban on high technology exports to
Eastern Europe, Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher says.
   Mosbacher indicated that Hungary and Poland could be two of the
main beneficiaries of such a change. He said in a television
interview that those two countries were discussing with U.S.
officials how to prevent the transfer of militarily strategic items
to neighboring Communist-bloc countries.
   A change in U.S. restrictions would be designed to encourage the
political liberalization in Eastern Europe and to deal with heavy
pressure from U.S. allies seeking an easing of export controls to
the Soviet bloc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil giant Chevron Corp. said it had moved
to thwart buyout threats raised by Pennzoil Co.'s purchase of an
8.8 percent stake, suing to force the sale of the stock and beefing
up its takeover defenses.
   Chevron, in a U.S. District Court suit filed late Thursday,
scoffed at Pennzoil's claim that it was not interested in a
takeover and accused the much smaller company of plotting to force
a restructuring that would benefit Pennzoil.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government incorrectly cut off cash
benefits to some of the most vulnerable of America's poor _ the
elderly, blind and disabled _ in more than half the cases reviewed
in a study, the Social Security Administration said.
   The findings suggest more than 10,000 recipients of Supplemental
Security Income may have their benefits suspended each year
``despite being unable to act or unlikely to understand'' what they
must do to continue receiving benefits, an agency report released
Friday said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the 12-nation European
Community, closing ranks amid upheaval in Eastern Europe, agreed to
press ahead with an economic and monetary union despite British
opposition.
   The decision Friday, on the opening day of a two-day summit,
means the EC will convene a special conference in December 1990 to
start negotiations for the adoption of a single currency and to set
up a system of central banks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. officials announced they are forming a
division to develop a new widebody plane that could become the 777.
The new jet will be larger than an existing 767 but smaller than
the familiar 747 model.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said Friday
the company is going ahead and developing the plane and making
first offers to airlines. But Thornton said no airlines have yet
offered to buy the plane and Boeing is far from committed to
actually building it.
