<DOCNO> AP891208-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-DalkonShield Adv11   12-08 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dalkon Shield, Adv 11,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Dec. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Long-Running Dalkon Shield Case Nears End</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda Hightower has carried 13 years of
guilt and another five years of anger as a victim of the Dalkon
Shield birth control device.
   Now that $2.5 billion is about to go into a trust fund to pay
thousands of women who were injured by the intrauterine device, she
is relieved.
   ``I felt comfortable once we got the Supreme Court's approval of
the plan,'' said Ms. Hightower, director of the Atlanta-based
Dalkon Shield Victims' Association.
   ``What we're gearing for now is trying to make sure women are
prepared for the process of reviewing their medical records,'' she
said. ``This is the real nitty gritty.''
   The compensation is part of the reorganization of the A.H.
Robins Co., a pharmaceutical manufacturer that distributed and sold
thousands of the IUDs in the early 1970s.
   As of this Friday, Robins will become a part of the American
Home Products Corp. of New York, closing the Richmond-based
company's Chapter 11 bankruptcy case that began in August 1985 when
Robins sought protection from creditors in the aftermath of
thousands of lawsuits claiming injury from the IUD.
   The acquisition of Robins also involves a $700 million exchange
of stock.
   For Ms. Hightower, the Dalkon Shield story began in the summer
of 1971 when she began using the device. Nevertheless, she
subsequently became pregnant, carried the baby to full term but
began to bleed severely during labor. Her daughter was born
brain-damaged.
   At the time, Ms. Hightower did not know the name of the IUD she
was using. She said her doctor told her that problems during
pregnancy resulted from her body's reaction to the IUD and that the
product itself was not at fault.
   Not until 1984, when she read about another woman's Dalkon
Shield lawsuit, did she learn the name of the IUD and that others
had similar problems.
   ``Until then, every time I looked at my daughter, I felt guilty
for what I had done to her,'' she said.
   Soon, however, her guilt turned to anger at Robins. She is
convinced that the company knew of potential defects in the IUD
when the product was put on the market.
   ``To deliberately do something like that ...,'' she said, her
voice trailing off.
   Last month, the Supreme Court refused to take up an appeal of
the Robins' case, rejecting a challenge brought by a group of
Dalkon Shield claimants who wanted to seek additional compensation
from the company's officers and others.
   The decision left intact the reorganization package approved
June 15 by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   John R. Stafford, chairman, president and chief executive
officer of American Home Products, announced last week that the
company would complete the acquisition of Robins, the cornerstone
of the reorganization, on Dec. 15.
   On that day, the Dalkon Shield trust will get the $2.5 billion,
said Michael Sheppard, director of the trust's claims resolution
facility.
   The trust, which is independent of both Robins and American Home
Products, has been working on a packet of information that will be
sent to approximately 112,000 remaining claimants about March 1,
Sheppard said.
   The claimants will have four options, he said _ a $725 payment
for women who do not have major injuries and for which no medical
records are required; a scheduled payment based on the type of
injury and requiring some medical documentation; a full review of
medical records for severe injuries; and a delay in the evaluation
of claims for up to three years for women who used the device but
have experienced no injury or only a slight injury and think the
problem may get worse.
   The trust, which received $100 million in startup money last
year pending the case's appeal, already has settled the claims of
about 80,000 women.
   Ms. Hightower, whose organization's mailing list includes about
1,000 claimants, said every day that the trust has waited for the
full settlement has cost thousands of dollars in interest and
raised the possibility that vital medical records needed by
claimants could get misplaced or destroyed.
   ``Lots of women believe that the trust is going to take care of
them,'' she said. ``The trust is trying to make things simple, and
they're very nice people who are trying to help us. ... But (women)
need to get their medical records, and they should take the records
to an attorney to see what problems they foresee. It's worth $50 to
have somebody look at your forms.''
   Roscoe E. Puckett Jr., a Robins spokesman, said the company will
continue to operate under that name as a subsidiary of American
Home Products after Friday. No decision has been announced on the
role of Robins' executives, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Dec. 11</NOTE>
