<FIRST>r f AM-Fuji-Kleinwort     12-08 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuji-Kleinwort,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Approves Fuji Bank Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York Friday
approved Fuji Bank Ltd.'s request to buy the 75.1 percent of
Kleinwort Government Securities Inc. of Chicago that it did not
already own.
   Fuji Bank bought a 24.9 percent stake in the securities company
in January.
   Kleinwort Benson is one of 44 primary dealers in U.S. government
securities designated by the New York Fed.
   Terms of the transaction were not announced but a Fuji bank
official earlier put the price at about $44 million.
   Fuji earlier paid Kleinwort Benson's parent, London-based
Kleinwort Benson Lonsdale PLC, $14.5 million for the 24.9 percent
stake in addition to $25 million for all of the Chicago unit's
subordinated debt.
   The U.S. central bank voted in August to allow Japanese firms to
continue to act as primary dealers in U.S. Treasury securities.
Primary dealers, which may conduct business in government
securities directly with the Fed, have access to advance
information about note and bond auctions.
   Fuji Bank, the No.3 Japanese bank, with assets totaling the
equivalent of about $351 billion at the end of last year, has six
U.S. branches and bought the U.S. finance company Walter E. Heller
in 1984.
   Fuji bank officials said purchase of the securities firm was
part of a business expansion program in the United States.
</TEXT>
