<DOCNO> AP891208-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Campeau-Bloomingdale's     12-08 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau-Bloomingdale's,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau Says Several Parties Interested in Bloomie's _ But Mum on
Who</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The bidding process officially began Friday for the famed
Bloomingdale's department store chain and owner Campeau Corp. said
a number of parties have expressed an interest in buying it.
   Campeau declined to identify the parties, specify how many there
were or how much they would be willing to pay for the 17-store
chain. In a brief news release, Campeau said it ``has received a
number of expressions of interest.'' Friday was the deadline by
which initial bids were to be submitted. Campeau and its advisors,
including First Boston Corp., are composing a list of contenders.
   ``A short list of no more than five or six finalists will
proceed to the second stage of the bidding process,'' Campeau's
release stated.
   The finalists will be given more detailed financial and other
information about the chain that was acquired by Toronto-based
Campeau last year in its $6.7 billion takeover of Federated
Department Stores Inc.
   The second stage of the sale process is expected to take eight
weeks, Campeau said. A definitive announcement on the sale is
expected to be made sometime in February.
   Campeau put Bloomingdale's on the block in September as part of
a plan to cope with a cash crunch. The high price Campeau paid for
Federated, financed mainly with high-interest junk bonds, has been
blamed for the financial woes facing the Canadian retail and real
estate company.
   The plan to sell Bloomingdale's, considered the crown jewel of
Campeau's retail empire, was formed when Canada's Olympia &amp; York
Developments Ltd. agreed to lend Campeau $800 million.
Bloomingdale's had nearly $1.2 billion in sales last year and is
expected to have $1.3 billion this year.
   The head of Bloomingdale's, Marvin S. Traub, has said he would
like to lead a buyout of the chain. Bloomingdale's spokeswoman
Carol Gies said Friday she didn't have any information on whether
Traub had submitted a buyout proposal.
   Traub, the company's chairman, was in meetings late Friday and
was said to be unavailable for comment. He had been in Tokyo
earlier this month during which he said he talked with various
parties that might join him in a possible buyout.
   Japanese news reports have said Tokyu Department Store, one of
that country's best-known chains, was interested in pursuing a
takeover of Bloomingdale's. Tokyu reportedly was willing to offer
$1.3 billion.
   Another party that has publicly disclosed an interest in
Bloomingdale's is Crown American Corp., a privately held company
that is one of the biggest U.S. developers of shopping malls. It
also owns Hess's Inc., a chain of stores.
   The switchboard at Crown American's Johnstown, Pa., headquarters
was closed late Friday and an answering service employee said no
one was available from the company.
   Retail analysts estimate Bloomingdale's could fetch anywhere
from $1.1 billion to $1.3 billion. The total could be on the low
side if it included a significant portion of cash, which Campeau
needs.
   The flagship Bloomingdale's store is in Manhattan with branches
elsewhere in New York and in Connecticut, Florida, Massachusetts,
Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Texas and Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
