<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Canada     12-08 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Canada,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Offers $100 Million in Export Credits to Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada has offered a U.S. $100 million credit
line to Mexico through its Export Development Corporation, Mexico's
Treasury Department said Friday.
   The credit will be offered through Mexican banks and is aimed at
small and medium-sized importers, the Treasury statement said.
   The agreement was signed Friday by Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe
and Canadian Ambassador David J.S. Winfield.
   Aspe praised the move, saying that the credit would improve
relations between the two countries and would contribute to
Mexico's development.
   Canadian-Mexican trade last year heavily favored Mexico,
according to the Canadian Embassy. Mexico's exports to Canada
totaled $1.1 billion in 1988, while Mexico bought U.S. $418 million
from Canada.
   Mexico exports motors, spare parts, gold, copper and petroleum
to Canada, while Canada sends wheat, wood pulp, steel, newsprint
and powdered milk to Canada.
</TEXT>
