<FIRST>r f AM-FDIC-Seidman     12-08 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDIC-Seidman,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seidman: RTC Gearing Up To Sale Assets From Thrift Seizures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are gearing up to sell the more
than 35,000 properties they have received through the seizure of
hundreds of failed thrifts, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
Chairman William Seidman said Friday.
   Seidman, who also heads the Resolution Trust Corp., said about
half of the properties are in Texas and Oklahoma, where much of the
industry's troubles have been located. The RTC is the agency
created to rescue the industry.
   Seidman said an inventory of the properties will be completed by
Dec. 31 _ the first time regulators will know exactly what they
own. The process of selling the property, however, could take time
as some of the assets are tied up in litigation.
   No figures currently are available on the value or breakdown of
those properties, he said. However Carmen Sullivan, who heads the
RTC's Dallas region, said an Aug. 31 estimate valued the land held
at about $3 billion in 8,000 parcels, 1,400 parcels of commercial
property at $3 billion and $748 million worth of residential
property.
   Seidman said the RTC already has sold $2.25 billion worth of
assets from institutions taken over by the government. Those assets
had been carried on the institutions' book at $2.9 billion, he said.
   ``I think we're off to a reasonable start. ... I think (sales)
are going very well,'' Seidman told reporters.
   The RTC currently has about 280 thrifts under conservatorship,
with at least another 300 already insolvent and expected to be
taken over.
</TEXT>
